{"title_page": "Fetch the Bolt Cutters", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name         = Fetch the Bolt Cutters\n| type         = studio\n| artist       = [[Fiona Apple]]\n| cover        = Fiona Apple - Fetch the Bolt Cutters.png\n| alt          = \n| released     = {{Start date|2020|4|17}}\n| recorded     = 2015\u2013March 2020\n| studio       =\n* Apple's house (Los Angeles)\n* Stanley (Los Angeles)\n* [[Sonic Ranch]] ([[Tornillo, Texas]])\n* [[Dave Way|Waystation]] (Los Angeles)\n| genre        = <!-- Please don't add unsourced genres  -->\n| length       = 51:59\n| label        = [[Epic Records|Epic]]\n| producer     = \n* Fiona Apple\n* Amy Aileen Wood<br/> with [[Sebastian Steinberg]]\n* [[Dav\u00edd Garza]]\n| prev_title   = [[The Idler Wheel...]]\n| prev_year    = 2012\n| next_title   = \n| next_year    = \n}}\n'''''Fetch the Bolt Cutters''''' is the fifth studio album by American singer [[Fiona Apple]]. It was released on April 17, 2020, and is Apple's first release in nearly eight years, since ''[[The Idler Wheel...]]'' in 2012.\n\n==Background and recording==\nIn 2012, Apple began conceptualising a new album, considering a [[concept album]] based on her home in [[Venice Beach]] or the [[Pando (tree)|Pando]] in Utah. In 2015, she began recording the album with bassist [[Sebastian Steinberg]], drummer Amy Aileen Wood and guitarist [[Dav\u00edd Garza]].<ref name=\"newyorker\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2020/03/23/fiona-apples-art-of-radical-sensitivity|title=Fiona Apple's Art of Radical Sensitivity|last=Nussbaum|first=Emily|author-link=Emily Nussbaum|website=[[New Yorker (magazine)|New Yorker]]|date=March 16, 2020|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThey began recording in Apple's [[Venice Beach]] home studio, using home-made percussive objects and chanting  as they marched around the house. They spent three weeks at the [[Sonic Ranch]] studio in rural Texas, with little success. Upon returning to Venice Beach, they began making progress, with Apple recording long takes consisting of instruments being hit against surfaces and objects. Apple's vocals were unedited, and the album developed a highly percussive sound.<ref name=\"newyorker\"/>\n\nBy July 2019, Apple had begun mixing the album. In September, the process began to slow down, with Apple developing doubts about the album.<ref name=\"newyorker\"/> At this time, the artist first mentioned work on her new project in an interview with ''[[Vulture (magazine)|Vulture]]'', explaining that she was still working hard on her next album which should have been released \"a million years ago\" and was hoping to put it out in 2020. She also admitted to being reclusive due to ongoing recording sessions at her Venice Beach house.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/09/fiona-apple-is-still-calling-bullshit.html|title=Fiona Apple Is Still Calling Bullshit|last=Handler|first=Rachel|website=[[Vulture (magazine)|Vulture]]|date=September 25, 2019|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, she played the mixes to her band members, whose positive response brought Apple back on track.<ref name=\"newyorker\"/> In an interview that month, she said that the album process was in its final stages, with the only things left being \"artwork and stuff\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2020/01/fiona-apple-new-album-soon/|title=Fiona Apple says new album will \"be done soon\"|last=Bacior|first=Robin|website=Consequence of Sound|date=January 22, 2020|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2020/01/fiona-apple-new-album-updates.html|title=15 Minutes With Fiona Apple|last=Handler|first=Rachel|website=Vulture|date=January 22, 2020|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref> On March 9, 2020, she revealed that she had finished recording, making the announcement in sign language.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/fiona-apple-reveals-her-new-album-is-finished-2622233|title=Fiona Apple reveals her new album is finished|last=Langford|first=Jackson|website=NME|date=March 9, 2020|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Music and lyrics==\nThe album's sound is percussive and raw. Songs feature looped sections, and sudden tempo changes. Apple's long-time bassist [[Sebastian Steinberg]] compared the album to Apple's 2012 song \"Hot Knife\", describing it as \"very raw and unslick\". Lyrically, Apple identified its main theme as \"not being afraid to speak\". She also explores her complex social relationships with other women.<ref name=\"newyorker\"/>\n\n==Release==\nOn March 16, 2020, Apple announced the album and its title in an extensive ''[[New Yorker (magazine)|New Yorker]]'' profile. The title, ''Fetch the Bolt Cutters'', is a quote from the British-Irish crime drama television series ''[[The Fall (TV series)|The Fall]]'', where the protagonist, a sex-crimes investigator portrayed by [[Gillian Anderson]], recites the phrase while investigating a crime scene where a woman was tortured.<ref name=\"newyorker\"/> The next month, she announced that the album was set to be released digitally on April 17.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/fiona-apple-releasing-new-album-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-this-month/|title=Fiona Apple Releasing New Album ''Fetch the Bolt Cutters'' This Month|last=Minsker|first=Evan|date=April 1, 2020|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| MC =  99/100<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/fetch-the-bolt-cutters/fiona-apple|title=Fetch the Bolt Cutters by Fiona Apple Reviews and Tracks|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev1 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev1score = A-<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/music/music-reviews/fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-album-review/|title=Fiona Apple returns with the wild, wooly ''Fetch the Bolt Cutters''|last=Greenblatt|first=Leah|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[Entertainment Weekly|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[The Independent]]''\n| rev2score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/fiona-apple-fetch-bolt-cutters-review-new-album-tracklist-stream-a9468761.html|title=Fiona Apple, Fetch the Bolt Cutters review: A witty, wonderful album laced with defiance|last=Pollard|first=Alexandra|date=April 16, 2020|website=[[The Independent]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[The Irish Times]]''\n| rev3score = {{rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/music/fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-review-a-bracing-collection-1.4228651|title=Fiona Apple: Fetch the Bolt Cutters review \u2013 A bracing collection|last=Clayton-Lea|first=Tony|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[The Irish Times]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]''\n| rev4score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"Telegraph\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/music/what-to-listen-to/fiona-apple-fetch-bolt-cutters-review-proof-one-greatest-songwriters/|title=Fiona Apple, Fetch the Bolt Cutters review: a masterpiece for the #MeToo era|last=McCormick|first=Neil|author-link=Neil McCormick|date=April 16, 2020|website=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[The Times]]''\n| rev5score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-review-she-has-kate-bushs-poetry-and-the-spirit-of-tom-waits-j088600fq/|title=Fiona Apple: Fetch the Bolt Cutters review \u2014 she has Kate Bush\u2019s poetry and the spirit of Tom Waits|last=Hodgkinson|first=Will|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[The Times]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev6score = 10/10<ref name=\"Pitchfork\"><{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters/|title=Fiona Apple: Fetch the Bolt Cutters Album Review|last=Pelly|first=Jenn|date=April 16, 2020|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\nAt [[Metacritic]], which assigns a [[standard score|normalized]] rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream publications, the album received an average score of 99, based on 5 reviews.<ref name=\"MC/> The album was awarded ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'''s  first perfect score since [[Kanye West]]'s ''[[My Beautiful Dark Twisted Fantasy]]'' (2010), with Jenn Pelly writing, \"No music has ever sounded quite like it.\"<ref name=\"Pitchfork\"/><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://musicfeeds.com.au/news/lana-del-rey-just-scored-pitchforks-highest-album-rating-since-2014/ |title=Lana Del Rey Just Scored Pitchfork's Highest Album Rating In Five Years |last=Langford |first=Jackson |date=September 4, 2019 |website=[[Music Feeds]] |accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref> [[Neil McCormick]] of ''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]'' described it as \"a masterpiece for the [[Me Too movement|#MeToo]] era\", writing that it \"feels about as real as music can be\".<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/> Mikael Wood of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' wrote of the \"stunning intimacy of the material here \u2014 a rich text to scour,\" adding \"you\u2019d need to go back to the later parts of [[Nina Simone]]\u2019s catalog to find another pop vocalist as eager as Apple is to make such a show of unprettiness.\"<ref>https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/music/story/2020-04-16/fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-review</ref> The ''[[Boston Globe]]'' praised the album for its \"matter-of-fact depictions of everyday brutality,\" but added that \"even the most intense moments of \u201cFetch,\u201d her lyrics retain a playfulness that acts as a ballast.\" It also commended Apple's \"husky [[alto]],\" which \"remains the focal point, launching into melodies that are instantly sticky as effortlessly as it engages in tensely rhythmic ''[[Sprechstimme]]''.\"<ref>https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/04/16/arts/fiona-apple-makes-defiance-sound-exhilarating-fetch-bolt-cutters/</ref> Patrick Ryan of ''[[USA Today]]'' wrote the album \"simmers with defiance, dark wit and quiet rage,\" describing it as \"a dense and richly poetic\u00a0masterpiece from one of music's best modern storytellers\" with \"razor-sharp statements and evocative lyrics that reveal themselves in every new listen.\"<ref>https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/music/2020/04/17/fetch-bolt-cutters-review-fiona-apple/5128604002/</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| all_writing = [[Fiona Apple]], except where noted\n| title1 = I Want You to Love Me\n| length1 = 3:57\n| title2 = Shameika\n| length2 = 4:08\n| title3 = Fetch the Bolt Cutters\n| length3 = 4:58\n| title4 = Under the Table\n| length4 = 3:21\n| title5 = Relay\n| length5 = 4:49\n| title6 = Rack of His\n| length6 = 3:42\n| title7 = Newspaper\n| length7 = 5:32\n| title8 = Ladies\n| note8 = lyrics written by Apple; music composed by [[Sebastian Steinberg]] and [[Dav\u00edd Garza]]\n| length8 = 5:25\n| title9 = Heavy Balloon\n| length9 = 3:26\n| title10 = Cosmonauts\n| length10 = 3:59\n| title11 = For Her\n| length11 = 2:43\n| title12 = Drumset\n| length12 = 2:40\n| title13 = On I Go\n| length13 = 3:09\n| total_length = 51:59\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\nCredits are adapted from ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/fiona-apple-shares-new-album-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-listen-and-read-the-full-credits/|title=Fiona Apple Shares New Album ''Fetch the Bolt Cutters'': Listen and Read the Full Credits|last=Minsker|first=Evan|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n'''Band'''\n* [[Fiona Apple]] \u2013\u00a0vocals {{small|(all tracks)}}, piano {{small|(1, 2, 4, 9, 10)}}, [[Casio]] {{small|(1, 9)}}, drums {{small|(1, 3, 5\u20137, 9, 11, 13)}}, percussion {{small|(2, 3, 5\u20137, 9, 10, 13)}}, background 