ll|(1\u20135, 8\u201310, 12, 13)}}, mixing {{small|(8)}}\n* Fiona Apple \u2013\u00a0recording {{small|(5\u20137, 9\u201311, 13)}}\n* [[Dave Way]] \u2013\u00a0recording {{small|(7, 9)}}, mixing {{small|(1, 5, 9)}}\n* [[Tchad Blake]] \u2013\u00a0mixing {{small|(2\u20134, 6, 7, 10\u201313)}}\n* [[Bob Ludwig]] \u2013\u00a0mastering\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Fiona Apple}}\n\n[[Category:2020 albums]]\n[[Category:Fiona Apple albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name         = Fetch the Bolt Cutters\n| type         = studio\n| artist       = [[Fiona Apple]]\n| cover        = Fiona Apple - Fetch the Bolt Cutters.png\n| alt          = \n| released     = {{Start date|2020|4|17}}\n| recorded     = 2015\u2013March 2020\n| studio       =\n* Apple's house (Los Angeles)\n* Stanley (Los Angeles)\n* [[Sonic Ranch]] ([[Tornillo, Texas]])\n* [[Dave Way|Waystation]] (Los Angeles)\n| genre        = <!-- Please don't add unsourced genres  -->\n| length       = 51:59\n| label        = [[Epic Records|Epic]]\n| producer     = \n* Fiona Apple\n* Amy Aileen Wood<br/> with [[Sebastian Steinberg]]\n* [[Dav\u00edd Garza]]\n| prev_title   = [[The Idler Wheel...]]\n| prev_year    = 2012\n| next_title   = \n| next_year    = \n}}\n'''''Fetch the Bolt Cutters''''' is the fifth studio album by American singer [[Fiona Apple]]. It was released on April 17, 2020, and is Apple's first release in nearly eight years, since ''[[The Idler Wheel...]]'' in 2012.\n\n==Background and recording==\nIn 2012, Apple began conceptualising a new album, considering a [[concept album]] based on her home in [[Venice Beach]] or the [[Pando (tree)|Pando]] in Utah. In 2015, she began recording the album with bassist [[Sebastian Steinberg]], drummer Amy Aileen Wood and guitarist [[Dav\u00edd Garza]].<ref name=\"newyorker\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2020/03/23/fiona-apples-art-of-radical-sensitivity|title=Fiona Apple's Art of Radical Sensitivity|last=Nussbaum|first=Emily|author-link=Emily Nussbaum|website=[[New Yorker (magazine)|New Yorker]]|date=March 16, 2020|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThey began recording in Apple's [[Venice Beach]] home studio, using home-made percussive objects and chanting  as they marched around the house. They spent three weeks at the [[Sonic Ranch]] studio in rural Texas, with little success. Upon returning to Venice Beach, they began making progress, with Apple recording long takes consisting of instruments being hit against surfaces and objects. Apple's vocals were unedited, and the album developed a highly percussive sound.<ref name=\"newyorker\"/>\n\nBy July 2019, Apple had begun mixing the album. In September, the process began to slow down, with Apple developing doubts about the album.<ref name=\"newyorker\"/> At this time, the artist first mentioned work on her new project in an interview with ''[[Vulture (magazine)|Vulture]]'', explaining that she was still working hard on her next album which should have been released \"a million years ago\" and was hoping to put it out in 2020. She also admitted to being reclusive due to ongoing recording sessions at her Venice Beach house.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/09/fiona-apple-is-still-calling-bullshit.html|title=Fiona Apple Is Still Calling Bullshit|last=Handler|first=Rachel|website=[[Vulture (magazine)|Vulture]]|date=September 25, 2019|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, she played the mixes to her band members, whose positive response brought Apple back on track.<ref name=\"newyorker\"/> In an interview that month, she said that the album process was in its final stages, with the only things left being \"artwork and stuff\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2020/01/fiona-apple-new-album-soon/|title=Fiona Apple says new album will \"be done soon\"|last=Bacior|first=Robin|website=Consequence of Sound|date=January 22, 2020|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2020/01/fiona-apple-new-album-updates.html|title=15 Minutes With Fiona Apple|last=Handler|first=Rachel|website=Vulture|date=January 22, 2020|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref> On March 9, 2020, she revealed that she had finished recording, making the announcement in sign language.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/fiona-apple-reveals-her-new-album-is-finished-2622233|title=Fiona Apple reveals her new album is finished|last=Langford|first=Jackson|website=NME|date=March 9, 2020|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Music and lyrics==\nThe album's sound is percussive and raw. Songs feature looped sections, and sudden tempo changes. Apple's long-time bassist [[Sebastian Steinberg]] compared the album to Apple's 2012 song \"Hot Knife\", describing it as \"very raw and unslick\". Lyrically, Apple identified its main theme as \"not being afraid to speak\". She also explores her complex social relationships with other women.<ref name=\"newyorker\"/>\n\n==Release==\nOn March 16, 2020, Apple announced the album and its title in an extensive ''[[New Yorker (magazine)|New Yorker]]'' profile. The title, ''Fetch the Bolt Cutters'', is a quote from the British-Irish crime drama television series ''[[The Fall (TV series)|The Fall]]'', where the protagonist, a sex-crimes investigator portrayed by [[Gillian Anderson]], recites the phrase while investigating a crime scene where a woman was tortured.<ref name=\"newyorker\"/> The next month, she announced that the album was set to be released digitally on April 17.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/fiona-apple-releasing-new-album-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-this-month/|title=Fiona Apple Releasing New Album ''Fetch the Bolt Cutters'' This Month|last=Minsker|first=Evan|date=April 1, 2020|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| MC =  99/100<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/fetch-the-bolt-cutters/fiona-apple|title=Fetch the Bolt Cutters by Fiona Apple Reviews and Tracks|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev1 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev1score = A-<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/music/music-reviews/fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-album-review/|title=Fiona Apple returns with the wild, wooly ''Fetch the Bolt Cutters''|last=Greenblatt|first=Leah|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[Entertainment Weekly|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[The Independent]]''\n| rev2score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/fiona-apple-fetch-bolt-cutters-review-new-album-tracklist-stream-a9468761.html|title=Fiona Apple, Fetch the Bolt Cutters review: A witty, wonderful album laced with defiance|last=Pollard|first=Alexandra|date=April 16, 2020|website=[[The Independent]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[The Irish Times]]''\n| rev3score = {{rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/music/fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-review-a-bracing-collection-1.4228651|title=Fiona Apple: Fetch the Bolt Cutters review \u2013 A bracing collection|last=Clayton-Lea|first=Tony|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[The Irish Times]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]''\n| rev4score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"Telegraph\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/music/what-to-listen-to/fiona-apple-fetch-bolt-cutters-review-proof-one-greatest-songwriters/|title=Fiona Apple, Fetch the Bolt Cutters review: a masterpiece for the #MeToo era|last=McCormick|first=Neil|author-link=Neil McCormick|date=April 16, 2020|website=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[The Times]]''\n| rev5score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-review-she-has-kate-bushs-poetry-and-the-spirit-of-tom-waits-j088600fq/|title=Fiona Apple: Fetch the Bolt Cutters review \u2014 she has Kate Bush\u2019s poetry and the spirit of Tom Waits|last=Hodgkinson|first=Will|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[The Times]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev6score = 10/10<ref name=\"Pitchfork\"><{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters/|title=Fiona Apple: Fetch the Bolt Cutters Album Review|last=Pelly|first=Jenn|date=April 16, 2020|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\nAt [[Metacritic]], which assigns a [[standard score|normalized]] rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream publications, the album received an average score of 99, based on 5 reviews.<ref name=\"MC/> The album was awarded ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'''s  first perfect score since [[Kanye West]]'s ''[[My Beautiful Dark Twisted Fantasy]]'' (2010), with Jenn Pelly writing, \"No music has ever sounded quite like it.\"<ref name=\"Pitchfork\"/><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://musicfeeds.com.au/news/lana-del-rey-just-scored-pitchforks-highest-album-rating-since-2014/ |title=Lana Del Rey Just Scored Pitchfork's Highest Album Rating In Five Years |last=Langford |first=Jackson |date=September 4, 2019 |website=[[Music Feeds]] |accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref> [[Neil McCormick]] of ''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]'' described it as \"a masterpiece for the [[Me Too movement|#MeToo]] era\", writing that it \"feels about as real as music can be\".<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/> Mikael Wood of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' wrote of the \"stunning intimacy of the material here \u2014 a rich text to scour,\" adding \"you\u2019d need to go back to the later parts of [[Nina Simone]]\u2019s catalog to find another pop vocalist as eager as Apple is to make such a show of unprettiness.\"<ref>https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/music/story/2020-04-16/fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-review</ref> The ''[[Boston Globe]]'' praised the album for its \"matter-of-fact depictions of everyday brutality,\" but adding that \"even the most intense moments of \u201cFetch,\u201d her lyrics retain a playfulness that acts as a ballast.\" It also commended Apple's \"husky [[alto]],\" which \"remains the focal point, launching into melodies that are instantly sticky as effortlessly as it engages in tensely rhythmic ''[[Sprechstimme]]''.\"<ref>https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/04/16/arts/fiona-apple-makes-defiance-sound-exhilarating-fetch-bolt-cutters/</ref> Patrick Ryan of ''[[USA Today]]'' wrote the album \"simmers with defiance, dark wit and quiet rage,\" describing it as \"a dense and richly poetic\u00a0masterpiece from one of music's best modern storytellers\" with \"razor-sharp statements and evocative lyrics that reveal themselves in every new listen.\"<ref>https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/music/2020/04/17/fetch-bolt-cutters-review-fiona-apple/5128604002/</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| all_writing = [[Fiona Apple]], except where noted\n| title1 = I Want You to Love Me\n| length1 = 3:57\n| title2 = Shameika\n| length2 = 4:08\n| title3 = Fetch the Bolt Cutters\n| length3 = 4:58\n| title4 = Under the Table\n| length4 = 3:21\n| title5 = Relay\n| length5 = 4:49\n| title6 = Rack of His\n| length6 = 3:42\n| title7 = Newspaper\n| length7 = 5:32\n| title8 = Ladies\n| note8 = lyrics written by Apple; music composed by [[Sebastian Steinberg]] and [[Dav\u00edd Garza]]\n| length8 = 5:25\n| title9 = Heavy Balloon\n| length9 = 3:26\n| title10 = Cosmonauts\n| length10 = 3:59\n| title11 = For Her\n| length11 = 2:43\n| title12 = Drumset\n| length12 = 2:40\n| title13 = On I Go\n| length13 = 3:09\n| total_length = 51:59\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\nCredits are adapted from ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/fiona-apple-shares-new-album-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-listen-and-read-the-full-credits/|title=Fiona Apple Shares New Album ''Fetch the Bolt Cutters'': Listen and Read the Full Credits|last=Minsker|first=Evan|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n'''Band'''\n* [[Fiona Apple]] \u2013\u00a0vocals {{small|(all tracks)}}, piano {{small|(1, 2, 4, 9, 10)}}, [[Casio]] {{small|(1, 9)}}, drums {{small|(1, 3, 5\u20137, 9, 11, 13)}}, percussion {{small|(2, 3, 5\u20137, 9, 10, 13)}}, background vocals {{small|(2\u20135, 7\u201313)}}, metal butterfly {{small|(3)}}, [[Mellotron]] {{small|(6, 12)}}, electronic drums {{small|(7)}}, timpani {{small|(7)}}, [[Wurlitzer electric piano|Wurlitzer]] {{small|(8)}}, bells {{small|(9)}}, chair {{small|(12)}}\n* [[Sebastian Steinberg]] \u2013\u00a0bass {{small|(1\u201310, 12, 13)}}, drums {{small|(1)}}, percussion {{small|(2, 5, 9)}}, [[Autoharp#Electric autoharp|electric autoharp]] {{small|(10, 13)}}, acoustic 12-string guitar {{small|(10)}}, slide guitar {{small|(10)}}, background vocals {{small|(12)}}, lighter on Wurlitzer {{small|(12)}}, harp {{small|(12)}}, watertower {{small|(13)}}, stomps {{small|(13)}}, breathing {{small|(13)}}\n* Amy Aileen Wood \u2013 drums {{small|(1\u201310, 12, 13)}}, percussion {{small|(2, 4, 5, 9, 10, 13)}}, loops {{small|(10)}}\n* [[Dav\u00edd Garza]] \u2013\u00a0[[vibraphone|vibes]] {{small|(4, 8)}}, percussion {{small|(5, 8, 9, 12, 13)}}, guitar {{small|(6, 7)}}, background vocals {{small|(8, 12)}}, Mellotron {{small|(8)}}, electric guitar {{small|(10)}}, Wurlitzer {{small|(10)}}, organ {{small|(12)}}, watertower {{small|(13)}}\n\n'''Additional musicians'''\n* [[Best Coast|Bobb Bruno]] \u2013\u00a0special effects {{small|(2, 5)}}\n* [[Cara Delevingne]] \u2013 background vocals {{small|(3)}}\n* Mercy \u2013\u00a0backing barks {{small|(3)}}, collar jangles and thrashing {{small|(5)}}\n* Maddie \u2013\u00a0backing barks {{small|(3)}}\n* Leo \u2013\u00a0backing barks {{small|(3)}}\n* Alfie \u2013\u00a0backing barks {{small|(3)}}\n* [[John Would]] \u2013\u00a0Wurlitzer {{small|(4)}}, organ {{small|(4)}}, piano {{small|(8)}}\n* Little \u2013\u00a0collar jangles and thrashing {{small|(5)}}\n* [[Maude Maggart]] \u2013 background vocals {{small|(7, 8)}}\n* Winifred Lucky \u2013 background vocals {{small|(7)}}\n* Spencer Maggart \u2013\u00a0soft shoe stomp {{small|(13)}}\n\n'''Engineers'''\n* Amy Aileen Wood \u2013\u00a0recording {{small|(1\u201310, 13)}}\n* John Would \u2013\u00a0recording {{small|(1\u20135, 8\u201310, 12, 13)}}, mixing {{small|(8)}}\n* Fiona Apple \u2013\u00a0recording {{small|(5\u20137, 9\u201311, 13)}}\n* [[Dave Way]] \u2013\u00a0recording {{small|(7, 9)}}, mixing {{small|(1, 5, 9)}}\n* [[Tchad Blake]] \u2013\u00a0mixing {{small|(2\u20134, 6, 7, 10\u201313)}}\n* [[Bob Ludwig]] \u2013\u00a0mastering\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Fiona Apple}}\n\n[[Category:2020 albums]]\n[[Category:Fiona Apple albums]]\n", "name_user": "Calcutecs", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCritical reception", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fetch_the_Bolt_Cutters"}
{"title_page": "Oxford Circus", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{short description|Road junction in London, UK}}\n[[File:Oxford Circus - New crossing - geograph.org.uk - 1568709.jpg|thumb|220px|Oxford Circus in November 2009]]\n'''Oxford Circus''' is a [[road junction]] connecting [[Oxford Street]] and [[Regent Street]] in the [[West End of London]]. It is also the entrance to [[Oxford Circus tube station]].\n\nThe junction opened in 1819 as part of the Regent Street development under [[John Nash (architect)|John Nash]], and was originally known as '''Regent Circus North'''. After the original lease expired, it was redesigned around a series of four quadrant buildings by [[Henry Tanner (architect)|Henry Tanner]] between 1913 and 1928, the north-eastern of which has been used by [[Peter Robinson (department store)|Peter Robinson]], [[Topshop]], the [[BBC]] and the [[London Co-operative Society]]; these are now [[listed building|Grade II listed buildings]]. Oxford Circus remains a busy junction for traffic, and a \u00a35&nbsp;million upgrade for pedestrians opened in 2009. It has also attracted attention as a place for demonstrations and protests, including by  [[Extinction Rebellion]].\n\n==History==\n===19th century===\n[[File:Oxford Circus (22891646886).jpg|thumb|Oxford Circus in 1904, showing [[John Nash (architect)|John Nash]]'s original design]]\nThe junction was designed as part of [[John Nash (architect)|John Nash]]'s work on [[Regent Street]].{{sfn|Weinreb|Hibbert|Keay|Keay|2008|p=685}} Circuses had become popular in English architecture after [[George Dance the Younger]] had popularised them in the [[Minories]] in East London. Nash wanted to use extra land space so that vehicles could move around one another when turning, with a concave layout attracting shopkeepers and increasing the potential for land value. He originally intended the circus to be [[colonnade]]d, but when the New Street Bill was proposed to parliament, it was rejected, with one MP fearing the circus would \"be a nuisance by day and something worse by night\".{{sfn|Bartlett|p=1}} He redesigned the circus so that the new Regent Street would meet the established Oxford Street at a near right-angle, with a smaller {{convert|164|ft|adj=on}} diameter reducing its land intake.  Parliament approved the design in 1813.{{sfn|Bartlett|p=2}}\n\nConstruction of the circus began in 1816, with Nash working in association with Samuel Baxter. Work was complicated by the [[compulsory purchase]] of properties along Oxford Street. Eight houses on the north side and eleven on the south were demolished to make way for the junction.{{sfn|Bartlett|pp=3\u20134}} To avoid legal challenges, Nash attempted to rehouse existing tenants in the new buildings around the circus wherever possible. After John Richardson, proprietor of Richardson's silk shop on 118 Oxford Street died, Nash ensured his widow and surviving family and employees were all housed in a building on the circus's north-eastern section. After the family complained and demanded changes, Nash worked with Baxter to try to accommodate them as much as possible.{{sfn|Bartlett|pp=3\u20135}}\n\nMost buildings around the circus were designed in a more disciplined manner than some of Nash's later work, and were based on [[Palladian architecture]]. They featured [[Fluting (architecture)|fluted]] [[Corinthian order|Corinthian]] [[pilaster]]s and artificial stone capitals. The pilaster order continued down Regent Street.{{sfn|Bartlett|p=7}}\n\nThe circus opened officially in November 1819.{{sfn|Bartlett|p=3}} It was originally known as Regent Circus North, with the corresponding [[Piccadilly Circus]] named Regent Circus South.{{sfn|Weinreb|Hibbert|Keay|Keay|2008|p=685}}<ref>{{cite journal|title=The rebuilding of Piccadilly Circus and the Regent Street Quadrant|work=Survey of London|volume=31 and 32, St James Westminster, Part 2|editor=F H W Sheppard|location=London|year=1963|pp=85\u2013100|url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/survey-london/vols31-2/pt2/pp85-100|accessdate=11 February 2020}}</ref> However, unlike Piccadilly Circus, Oxford Circus had no decorations and was designed as a straightforward traffic crossing.{{sfn|Glinert|2008|p=88}} Fellow architect [[James Elmes]] described Nash's work on the circus as giving \"an air of grandeur\" and \"as elegant in form as it is useful in application\".{{sfn|Bartlett|p=8}} The current name began to be used around 1836.{{sfn|Bartlett|p=2}}\n\nIn 1842, the MP [[Joseph Hume]] proposed a commemorative [[obelisk]] should be constructed in the middle of the circus.{{sfn|Bartlett|p=8}} Construction began in December 1842, but was quickly disrupted and abandoned after the Marylebone parish [[vestry]] realised they only had authority to clean and maintain the circus, and not to construct anything on top of it. The obelisk was eventually built in 1850 at [[Nunhead Cemetery]] to a slightly different design.{{sfn|Bartlett|p=10}}\n\n===20th century===\n[[File:London Oxford Circus, 1949 geograph-3044387-by-Ben-Brooksbank.jpg|thumb|left|Oxford Circus in 1949]]\nThe lease on the four quadrants around the interchange was due to expire in 1917, and it was determined they would need to be rebuilt. In 1904, the [[Commissioners of Woods and Forests]] outlined a plan to redevelop Regent Street, including Oxford Circus. In 1909, they invited proposals to redevelop the site.{{sfn|Bartlett|p=11}} The new design was awarded in October 1910 to [[Henry Tanner (architect)|Henry Tanner]], who saw off several rival designs, and was built in stages between 1913 and 1928.{{sfn|Weinreb|Hibbert|Keay|Keay|2008|p=610}}{{sfn|Bartlett|p=14}} Tanner's design was inspired by 18th-century French architecture, particularly that of [[Ange-Jacques Gabriel]].{{sfn|Bartlett|p=15}} Each quadrant was designed to be symmetrical with the others.<ref name=NHLE/>\n\nThe south-eastern quadrant was completed first in 1913, before work stopped at the beginning of [[World War I]].{{sfn|Bartlett|p=16}} The north-western quadrant opened in May 1922 as the London premises for the [[Magasins du Louvre]]. The store was never popular and closed in 1930.{{sfn|Bartlett|p=17}} The south-western quadrant followed in 1925 and the north-eastern in 1928.{{sfn|Weinreb|Hibbert|Keay|Keay|2008|p=610}}{{sfn|Bartlett|p=17}}\n\nThe new north-eastern quadrant was originally occupied by the [[Peter Robinson (department store)|Peter Robinson]] department store. An extension to the store was added to the original quadrant building in 1924.{{sfn|Bartlett|p=17}}<ref>{{NHLE|num=1227690|accessdate=13 February 2020}}</ref> During [[World War II]], it was badly damaged by bombs in September 1940 but survived owing to its steel frame construction and was quickly repaired to a high standard. The [[BBC]] requisitioned part of the block and it saw significant use in overseas broadcasting during the war. It was sold to the [[London Co-operative Society]] in 1944.{{sfn|Bartlett|p=18}} Through a series of buyouts and mergers, Peter Robinson became [[Topshop]], which now occupies the site.{{sfn|Bartlett|p=17}} It is the flagship store of the franchise, covering four floors and attracting around 28,000 shoppers a day, half of whom buy something.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/06/21/business/worldbusiness/21topshop.html?adxnnl=1&adxnnlx=1415214562-edQGoGWtOdP4K7Vcqbj+RA|title=But Will It Play in Manhattan?|newspaper=New York Times|date=21 June 2006|accessdate=13 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe buildings are constructed of [[Portland stone]] with a cladding steel frame and slate roofs. They have been listed at Grade II since 1973.<ref name=NHLE>{{NHLE|num=1227716|accessdate=13 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{NHLE|num=1235171|accessdate=13 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Tube station==\n[[File:Oxford Circus Tube Station Entrance.jpg|thumb|One of the entrances to [[Oxford Circus tube station]]]]\nThe [[Oxford Circus tube station|tube station]] opened on 30 July 1900 when the first section of the [[Central line (London Underground)|Central line]] opened. A connection to the [[Bakerloo line]] opened on 10 March 1906; the station was modified below ground to accommodate this.{{sfn|Wolmar|2005|p=173}}{{sfn|Horne|2001|p=17}}\n\nFor five years from 1963 as part of connecting the tube station to the [[Victoria line]], the road surface was carried on a temporary 850-ton umbrella bridge, accommodating all four directions of travel while work continued underneath.{{sfn|Day|Reed|2010|p=161}}<ref name=londonist>{{cite web|url=https://londonist.com/london/5-secrets-of-oxford-circus|title=5 secrets of Oxford Circus|work=Londonist|accessdate=11 February 2020}}</ref> It was dismantled on 12 April 1968.<ref>{{cite news|title=BY A STAFF REPORTER. \"'Umbrella' bridge is removed#|newspaper=The Times|date=13 April 1968|p=2|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/CS34696845/TTDA?u=kccl&sid=TTDA&xid=1c704400|accessdate=13 February 2020|url-access=subscription}}</ref> The station was badly damaged by [[Oxford Circus fire|fire]] in November 1984, but there were no fatalities.{{sfn|Bartlett|p=32}}\n{{-}}\n\n==Traffic==\n{{wide image|Oxford circus panorama.jpg|800px|Panorama view of the Oxford Circus diagonal crossing, 2014}}\nOxford Circus is one of the busiest pedestrian crossings in London.<ref name=atkins/> In 1924, shipbuilder [[Alfred Yarrow]] proposed building a [[grade-separated junction]] to segregate traffic, paid for by his own funds. The offer was turned down by Westminster City Council.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sir Alfred Yarrow's Traffic Scheme|newspaper=The Times|date=16 April 1924|p=11|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/CS186717840/TTDA?u=kccl&sid=TTDA&xid=456e859f|accessdate=13 February 2020|url-access=subscription}}</ref> In 1935, Westminster City Council proposed fitting pedestrian guard rails at the junction, restricting crossing in order to improve safety.<ref>{{cite news|title=Proposed Railings At Oxford Circus|newspaper=The Times|date=20 December 1935|p=11|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/CS186330516/TTDA?u=kccl&sid=TTDA&xid=e5374bba|accessdate=13 February 2020|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of the 2000s, Oxford Circus had the highest pedestrian volumes recorded anywhere in London.<ref name=\"atkins\" /> At the busiest times, over 40,000 pedestrians per hour pass through the junction, including those accessing the tube station. The average traffic flow is around 2,000 vehicles per hour during the week, and the junction operates at near capacity for most of the day with regular queues, particularly west along Oxford Street. 24 bus routes pass through Oxford Circus, and over 400 buses cross the junction on an average weekday. There are bus stops within {{convert|200|m}} on every arm of the crossing.<ref name=atkins>{{cite report|url=https://www.atkinsglobal.com/~/media/Files/A/Atkins-Global/Attachments/sectors/roads/library-docs/technical-journal-4/scrambled-pedestrian-crossings-at-signal-controlled-junctions-a-case-study.pdf|p=57|title=\u2018Scrambled\u2019 pedestrian crossings at signal controlled junctions \u2013 A case study|first=Chris|last=Greenwood|publisher=Atkins Global|accessdate=11 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, [[Transport for London]] redesigned the intersection to facilitate a [[pedestrian scramble]]. The crossing opened in November and cost around \u00a35&nbsp;million.<ref name=bbcx>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/london/8337341.stm|title=Oxford Circus X-crossing' opens|work=BBC News|date=2 November 2009|accessdate=9 February 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2009/nov/02/x-oxford-circus-crossing|title=X marks the spot: new Oxford Circus crossing opens|newspaper=The Guardian|date=3 November 2009|accessdate=9 February 2009}}</ref> It was inspired by street crossings in [[Tokyo]], and opened by the [[Mayor of London]], [[Boris Johnson]], who called the scheme \"a triumph for British engineering, Japanese innovation and good old fashioned common sense\".<ref name=bbcx/><ref name=londonist/> The scheme added an additional {{convert|312|m2}} of pedestrian space and removed the guard rail, adding 70% more capacity to the crossing.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2010/WORLD/europe/04/06/UK.urban.oxford.street.crossing/index.html|title=Londoners love Tokyo-style crossing|work=CNN|date=7 April 2010|accessdate=18 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Events==\n[[File:Berta C\u00e1ceres boat.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Extinction Rebellion]] protesting in Oxford Circus with the [[Berta C\u00e1ceres]] boat]]\nIn February 1872, a tripartite arch made of flowers and decorated with flags was erected in the middle of Oxford Circus, to commemorate [[Edward VII|Albert, Prince of Wales]]' recovery from [[typhoid fever]]. [[Queen Victoria]] passed along the parade with the Prince to a crowd of cheering children.{{sfn|Bartlett|p=10}}\n\nOn 20 December 1938, 50 people took part in an unemployment protest staged in Oxford Circus. Campaigners threw themselves into the road shouting \"We want work, we want bread\", before being restrained by police.<ref>{{cite news|title=Unemployed Demonstration In Oxford Circus|newspaper=The Times|date=21 December 1938|p=6|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/CS102052757/TTDA?u=kccl&sid=TTDA&xid=70de8969|accessdate=13 February 2020|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 May 2001, an anti-capitalism demonstration converging on Oxford Circus broke into violence. Police attempted to contain the crowd in the circus, but 50\u201360 demonstrators broke free and started destroying property and set fire to a nearby shop.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2001/may/01/mayday.immigrationpolicy1|title=Violence erupts in central London|newspaper=The Guardian|date=1 May 2001|accessdate=13 February 2020}}</ref> Along with 3,000 others, Lois Austin was kept [[kettling|kettled]] in the circus for around 7 hours. She later appealed to the [[European Court of Human Rights]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/jul/19/metropolitan-police-kettling-human-rights|title=Metropolitan police's 'kettling' tactic challenged in European court|newspaper=The Guardian|date=19 July 2009|accessdate=13 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2011/sep/14/kettling-student-european-court-lois|title=Kettled British woman takes case to European court of human rights|date=14 September 2011|accessdate=13 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 March 2011, around 500,000 protested against government public service cuts in London. At Oxford Circus, they clashed with [[riot police]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/gallery/2011/mar/26/thousands-march-against-cuts-in-pictures|title=Thousands march against spending cuts \u2013 in pictures|newspaper=The Guardian|date=26 March 2011|accessdate=13 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn [[Black Friday (shopping)|Black Friday]], 24 November 2017, police responded to a possible terrorist incident at Oxford Circus after receiving calls of gunfire on Oxford Street and the tube station. The area was busy and commuters and shoppers took refuge in shops. The Metropolitan Police later announced it would stand down the response.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/live/2017/nov/24/oxford-circus-police-london-tube-gunshots-live|title=Oxford Circus: police stood down after incident in central London \u2013 as it happened|newspaper=The Guardian|date=24 November 2017|accessdate=13 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, the environmental group [[Extinction Rebellion]] protested by blockading Oxford Circus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.brightonandhovenews.org/2020/01/28/green-councillor-in-court-over-extinction-rebellion-protests/|title=Green Councillor in Court over Extinction Rebellion Protests|date=28 January 2020|accessdate=11 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-bristol-51389053|title=Priest, 77, joined Extinction Rebellion protest 'to save human life'|date=5 February 2020|accessdate=11 February 2020}}</ref> Protesters chained themselves to the road, and The [[Metropolitan Police]] drafted additional police officers to help clear the area, who helped tear down a pink boat named after the environmental activist [[Berta C\u00e1ceres]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2019/apr/20/extinction-rebellion-protests-police-start-to-clear-oxford-circus|title=Extinction Rebellion: protest lawfully or go home, urges Met police chief|work=April 2019|accessdate=13 February 2020}}</ref> In October, protesters erected a giant wooden pyramid structure in the centre of the circus, which had to be dismantled by a JCB.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-50094594|title=Extinction Rebellion: Central London targeted despite ban|work=BBC News|date=18 October 2019|accessdate=12 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/extinction-rebellion-protests-london-oxford-circus-whitehall-red-hand-march-a9161936.html|title=Extinction Rebellion protests: Activists blockade Oxford Circus with wooden pyramid before \u2018red hand\u2019 march on Westminster|newspaper=The Independent|date=18 October 2019|accessdate=13 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2019, a protest against the imprisonment of far-right extremist [[Tommy Robinson (activist)|Tommy Robinson]] at the circus descended into violence. A man was arrested for [[actual bodily harm]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/tommy-robinson-protest-arrest-met-police-medic-attack-london-a9044696.html|title=Tommy Robinson: Man hands himself in after medic kicked in head at London protest|newspaper=The Independent|date=7 August 2019|accessdate=12 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n===Citations===\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|last=Day|first=John R|last2=Reed|first2=John|year=2010|origyear=1963|title=The Story of London's Underground|publisher=Capital Transport|isbn=978-1-85414-341-9|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Glinert|first=Ed|title=West End Chronicles: 300 Years of Glamour and Excess in the Heart of London|publisher=Penguin|year=2008|isbn=978-0-141-02464-6|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Horne |first=Mike |year=2001 |title=The Bakerloo Line: An Illustrated History |publisher=Capital Transport |location=Harrow |isbn=978-1-85414-248-1 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Wolmar |first=Christian |authorlink=Christian Wolmar |title=The Subterranean Railway: How the London Underground Was Built and How It Changed the City Forever |publisher=Atlantic Books |location=London |isbn=978-1-84354-023-6 |origyear=2004 |year=2005 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|title=Oxford Circus|work=Survey of London|author=Bartlett School of Architecture|url=https://www.ucl.ac.uk/bartlett/architecture/sites/bartlett/files/sol_oxfordst_chapter12.pdf|volume=Chapter 12|ref={{harvid|Bartlett}}}}\n{{london encyclopedia}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category-inline}}\n{{coord|51|30|55|N|00|08|31|W|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Oxford Street]]\n[[Category:Road junctions in London]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{short description|Road junction in London, UK}}\n[[File:Oxford Circus - New crossing - geograph.org.uk - 1568709.jpg|thumb|220px|Oxford Circus in November 2009]]\n'''Oxford Circus''' is a [[road junction]] connecting [[Oxford Street]] and [[Regent Street]] in the [[West End of London]]. It is also the entrance to [[Oxford Circus tube station]].\n\nThe junction opened in 1819 as part of the Regent Street development under [[John Nash (architect)|John Nash]], and was originally known as '''Regent Circus North'''. After the original lease expired, it was redesigned around a series of four quadrant buildings by [[Henry Tanner (architect)|Henry Tanner]] between 1913 and 1928, the north-eastern of which has been used by [[Peter Robinson (department store)|Peter Robinson]], [[Topshop]], the [[BBC]] and the [[London Co-operative Society]]; these are now [[listed building|Grade II listed buildings]]. Oxford Circus remains a busy junction for traffic, and a \u00a35&nbsp;million upgrade for pedestrians opened in 2009. It has also attracted attention as a place for demonstrations and protests, including by  [[Extinction Rebellion]].\n\n==History==\n===19th century===\n[[File:Oxford Circus (22891646886).jpg|thumb|Oxford Circus in 1904, showing [[John Nash (architect)|John Nash]]'s original design]]\nThe junction was designed as part of [[John Nash (architect)|John Nash]]'s work on [[Regent Street]].{{sfn|Weinreb|Hibbert|Keay|Keay|2008|p=685}} Circuses had become popular in English architecture after [[George Dance the Younger]] had popularised them in the [[Minories]] in East London. Nash wanted to use extra land space so that vehicles could move around one another when turning, with a concave layout attracting shopkeepers and increasing the potential for land value. He originally intended the circus to be [[colonnade]]d, but when the New Street Bill was proposed to parliament, it was rejected, with one MP fearing the circus would \"be a nuisance by day and something worse by night\".{{sfn|Bartlett|p=1}} He redesigned the circus so that the new Regent Street would meet the established Oxford Street at a near right-angle, with a smaller {{convert|164|ft|adj=on}} diameter reducing its land intake.  Parliament approved the design in 1813.{{sfn|Bartlett|p=2}}\n\nConstruction of the circus began in 1816, with Nash working in association with Samuel Baxter. Work was complicated by the [[compulsory purchase]] of properties along Oxford Street. Eight houses on the north side and eleven on the south were demolished to make way for the junction.{{sfn|Bartlett|pp=3\u20134}} To avoid legal challenges, Nash attempted to rehouse existing tenants in the new buildings around the circus wherever possible. After John Richardson, proprietor of Richardson's silk shop on 118 Oxford Street died, Nash ensured his widow and surviving family and employees were all housed in a building on the circus' northeast section. After the family complained and demanded changes, Nash worked with Baxter to try to accommodate them as much as possible.{{sfn|Bartlett|pp=3\u20135}}\n\nMost buildings around the circus were designed in a more disciplined manner than some of Nash's later work, and were based on [[Palladian architecture]]. They featured fluted [[Corinthian order]] pilasters and artificial stone capitals. The pilaster order continued down Regent Street.{{sfn|Bartlett|p=7}}\n\nThe circus opened officially in November 1819.{{sfn|Bartlett|p=3}} It was originally known as Regent Circus North, with the corresponding [[Piccadilly Circus]] named Regent Circus South.{{sfn|Weinreb|Hibbert|Keay|Keay|2008|p=685}}<ref>{{cite journal|title=The rebuilding of Piccadilly Circus and the Regent Street Quadrant|work=Survey of London|volume=31 and 32, St James Westminster, Part 2|editor=F H W Sheppard|location=London|year=1963|pp=85\u2013100|url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/survey-london/vols31-2/pt2/pp85-100|accessdate=11 February 2020}}</ref> However, unlike Piccadilly Circus, Oxford Circus had no decorations and was designed as a straightforward traffic crossing.{{sfn|Glinert|2008|p=88}} Fellow architect [[James Elmes]] described Nash's work on the circus as giving \"an air of grandeur\" and \"as elegant in form as it is useful in application\".{{sfn|Bartlett|p=8}} The current name began to be used around 1836.{{sfn|Bartlett|p=2}}\n\nIn 1842, the MP [[Joseph Hume]] proposed a commemorative [[obelisk]] should be constructed in the middle of the circus.{{sfn|Bartlett|p=8}} Construction began in December 1842, but was quickly disrupted and abandoned after the Marylebone parish [[vestry]] realised they only had authority to clean and maintain the circus, and not to construct anything on top of it. The obelisk was eventually built in 1850 at [[Nunhead Cemetery]] with a slightly different design.{{sfn|Bartlett|p=10}}\n\n===20th century===\n[[File:London Oxford Circus, 1949 geograph-3044387-by-Ben-Brooksbank.jpg|thumb|left|Oxford Circus in 1949]]\nThe lease on the four quadrants around the interchange was due to expire in 1917, and it was determined they would need to be rebuilt. In 1904, the [[Commissioners of Woods and Forests]] outlined a plan to redevelop Regent Street, including Oxford Circus. In 1909, they invited proposals to redevelop the site.{{sfn|Bartlett|p=11}} The new design was awarded to [[Henry Tanner (architect)|Henry Tanner]] in October 1910, who saw off several rival designs, and built in stages between 1913 and 1928.{{sfn|Weinreb|Hibbert|Keay|Keay|2008|p=610}}{{sfn|Bartlett|p=14}} Tanner's design was inspired by 18th-century French architecture, particularly that of [[Ange-Jacques Gabriel]].{{sfn|Bartlett|p=15}} Each quadrant was designed to be symmetrical with the others.<ref name=NHLE/>\n\nThe southeastern quadrant was completed first in 1913, before work stopped at the start of [[World War I]].{{sfn|Bartlett|p=16}} The northwest quadrant opened in May 1922 as the London premises for the [[Magasins du Louvre]]. The store was never popular and closed in 1930.{{sfn|Bartlett|p=17}} The southwest quadrant followed in 1925 and the northeast in 1928.{{sfn|Weinreb|Hibbert|Keay|Keay|2008|p=610}}{{sfn|Bartlett|p=17}}\n\nThe new northeast quadrant was originally occupied by the [[Peter Robinson (department store)|Peter Robinson]] department store. An extension to the store was added to the original quadrant building in 1924.{{sfn|Bartlett|p=17}}<ref>{{NHLE|num=1227690|accessdate=13 February 2020}}</ref> During [[World War II]], it was badly damaged by bombs in September 1940 but survived owing to its steel frame construction and was quickly repaired to a high standard. The [[BBC]] requisitioned part of the block and it saw significant use in overseas broadcasting during the war. It was sold to the [[London Co-operative Society]] in 1944.{{sfn|Bartlett|p=18}} Through a series of buyouts and mergers, Peter Robinson became [[Topshop]] which now occupies the site.{{sfn|Bartlett|p=17}} It is the flagship store of the franchise, covering four floors and attracting around 28,000 shoppers a day, half of whom buy something.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/06/21/business/worldbusiness/21topshop.html?adxnnl=1&adxnnlx=1415214562-edQGoGWtOdP4K7Vcqbj+RA|title=But Will It Play in Manhattan?|newspaper=New York Times|date=21 June 2006|accessdate=13 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe buildings are constructed of [[Portland stone]] with a cladding steel frame and slate roofs. They have been Grade II listed since 1973.<ref name=NHLE>{{NHLE|num=1227716|accessdate=13 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{NHLE|num=1235171|accessdate=13 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Tube station==\n[[File:Oxford Circus Tube Station Entrance.jpg|thumb|One of the entrances to [[Oxford Circus tube station]]]]\nThe [[Oxford Circus tube station|tube station]] opened on 30 July 1900 when the first section of the [[Central line (London Underground)|Central line]] opened. A connection to the [[Bakerloo line]] opened on 10 March 1906; the station was modified below ground to accommodate this.{{sfn|Wolmar|2005|p=173}}{{sfn|Horne|2001|p=17}}\n\nFor five years from 1963 as part of connecting the tube station to the [[Victoria line]], the road surface was carried on a temporary 850-ton umbrella bridge, accommodating all four directions of travel while work continued underneath.{{sfn|Day|Reed|2010|p=161}}<ref name=londonist>{{cite web|url=https://londonist.com/london/5-secrets-of-oxford-circus|title=5 secrets of Oxford Circus|work=Londonist|accessdate=11 February 2020}}</ref> It was dismantled on 12 April 1968.<ref>{{cite news|title=BY A STAFF REPORTER. \"'Umbrella' bridge is removed#|newspaper=The Times|date=13 April 1968|p=2|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/CS34696845/TTDA?u=kccl&sid=TTDA&xid=1c704400|accessdate=13 February 2020|url-access=subscription}}</ref> The station was badly damaged by [[Oxford Circus fire|fire]] in November 1984, but there were no fatalities.{{sfn|Bartlett|p=32}}\n{{-}}\n\n==Traffic==\n{{wide image|Oxford circus panorama.jpg|800px|Panorama view of the Oxford Circus diagonal crossing, 2014}}\nOxford Circus is one of the busiest pedestrian crossings in London.<ref name=atkins/> In 1924, shipbuilder [[Alfred Yarrow]] proposed building a [[grade-separated junction]] to segregate traffic, paid for by his own funds. The offer was turned down by Westminster City Council.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sir Alfred Yarrow's Traffic Scheme|newspaper=The Times|date=16 April 1924|p=11|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/CS186717840/TTDA?u=kccl&sid=TTDA&xid=456e859f|accessdate=13 February 2020|url-access=subscription}}</ref> In 1935, Westminster City Council proposed fitting pedestrian guard rails at the junction, restricting crossing in order to improve safety.<ref>{{cite news|title=Proposed Railings At Oxford Circus|newspaper=The Times|date=20 December 1935|p=11|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/CS186330516/TTDA?u=kccl&sid=TTDA&xid=e5374bba|accessdate=13 February 2020|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of the 2000s, Oxford Circus had the highest pedestrian volumes recorded anywhere in London.<ref name=\"atkins\" /> At the busiest times, over 40,000 pedestrians per hour pass through the junction, including those accessing the tube station. The average traffic flow is around 2,000 vehicles per hour during the week, and the junction operates at near capacity for most of the day with regular queues, particularly west along Oxford Street. 24 bus routes pass through Oxford Circus, and over 400 buses cross the junction on an average weekday. There are bus stops within {{convert|200|m}} on every arm of the crossing.<ref name=atkins>{{cite report|url=https://www.atkinsglobal.com/~/media/Files/A/Atkins-Global/Attachments/sectors/roads/library-docs/technical-journal-4/scrambled-pedestrian-crossings-at-signal-controlled-junctions-a-case-study.pdf|p=57|title=\u2018Scrambled\u2019 pedestrian crossings at signal controlled junctions \u2013 A case study|first=Chris|last=Greenwood|publisher=Atkins Global|accessdate=11 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, [[Transport for London]] redesigned the intersection to facilitate a [[pedestrian scramble]]. The crossing opened in November and cost around \u00a35&nbsp;million.<ref name=bbcx>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/london/8337341.stm|title=Oxford Circus X-crossing' opens|work=BBC News|date=2 November 2009|accessdate=9 February 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2009/nov/02/x-oxford-circus-crossing|title=X marks the spot: new Oxford Circus crossing opens|newspaper=The Guardian|date=3 November 2009|accessdate=9 February 2009}}</ref> It was inspired by street crossings in [[Tokyo]], and opened by the [[Mayor of London]], [[Boris Johnson]], who called the scheme \"a triumph for British engineering, Japanese innovation and good old fashioned common sense\".<ref name=bbcx/><ref name=londonist/> The scheme added an additional {{convert|312|m2}} of pedestrian space and removed the guard rail, adding 70% more capacity to the crossing.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2010/WORLD/europe/04/06/UK.urban.oxford.street.crossing/index.html|title=Londoners love Tokyo-style crossing|work=CNN|date=7 April 2010|accessdate=18 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Events==\n[[File:Berta C\u00e1ceres boat.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Extinction Rebellion]] protesting in Oxford Circus with the [[Berta C\u00e1ceres]] boat]]\nIn February 1872, a tripartite arch made of flowers and decorated with flags was erected in the middle of Oxford Circus, to commemorate [[Edward VII|Albert, Prince of Wales]]' recovery from [[typhoid fever]]. [[Queen Victoria]] passed along the parade with the Prince to a crowd of cheering children.{{sfn|Bartlett|p=10}}\n\nOn 20 December 1938, 50 people took part in an unemployment protest staged in Oxford Circus. Campaigners threw themselves into the road shouting \"We want work, we want bread\", before being restrained by police.<ref>{{cite news|title=Unemployed Demonstration In Oxford Circus|newspaper=The Times|date=21 December 1938|p=6|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/CS102052757/TTDA?u=kccl&sid=TTDA&xid=70de8969|accessdate=13 February 2020|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 May 2001, an anti-capitalism demonstration converging on Oxford Circus broke into violence. Police attempted to contain the crowd in the circus, but 50\u201360 demonstrators broke free and started destroying property and set fire to a nearby shop.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2001/may/01/mayday.immigrationpolicy1|title=Violence erupts in central London|newspaper=The Guardian|date=1 May 2001|accessdate=13 February 2020}}</ref> Along with 3,000 others, Lois Austin was kept [[kettling|kettled]] in the circus for around 7 hours. She later appealed to the [[European Court of Human Rights]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/jul/19/metropolitan-police-kettling-human-rights|title=Metropolitan police's 'kettling' tactic challenged in European court|newspaper=The Guardian|date=19 July 2009|accessdate=13 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2011/sep/14/kettling-student-european-court-lois|title=Kettled British woman takes case to European court of human rights|date=14 September 2011|accessdate=13 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 March 2011, around 500,000 protested against government public service cuts in London. At Oxford Circus, they clashed with [[riot police]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/gallery/2011/mar/26/thousands-march-against-cuts-in-pictures|title=Thousands march against spending cuts \u2013 in pictures|newspaper=The Guardian|date=26 March 2011|accessdate=13 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn [[Black Friday (shopping)|Black Friday]], 24 November 2017, police responded to a possible terrorist incident at Oxford Circus after receiving calls of gunfire on Oxford Street and the tube station. The area was busy and commuters and shoppers took refuge in shops. The Metropolitan Police later announced it would stand down the response.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/live/2017/nov/24/oxford-circus-police-london-tube-gunshots-live|title=Oxford Circus: police stood down after incident in central London \u2013 as it happened|newspaper=The Guardian|date=24 November 2017|accessdate=13 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, the environmental group [[Extinction Rebellion]] protested by blockading Oxford Circus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.brightonandhovenews.org/2020/01/28/green-councillor-in-court-over-extinction-rebellion-protests/|title=Green Councillor in Court over Extinction Rebellion Protests|date=28 January 2020|accessdate=11 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-bristol-51389053|title=Priest, 77, joined Extinction Rebellion protest 'to save human life'|date=5 February 2020|accessdate=11 February 2020}}</ref> Protesters chained themselves to the road, and The [[Metropolitan Police]] drafted additional police officers to help clear the area, who helped tear down a pink boat named after the environmental activist [[Berta C\u00e1ceres]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2019/apr/20/extinction-rebellion-protests-police-start-to-clear-oxford-circus|title=Extinction Rebellion: protest lawfully or go home, urges Met police chief|work=April 2019|accessdate=13 February 2020}}</ref> In October, protesters erected a giant wooden pyramid structure in the centre of the circus, which had to be dismantled by a JCB.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-50094594|title=Extinction Rebellion: Central London targeted despite ban|work=BBC News|date=18 October 2019|accessdate=12 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/extinction-rebellion-protests-london-oxford-circus-whitehall-red-hand-march-a9161936.html|title=Extinction Rebellion protests: Activists blockade Oxford Circus with wooden pyramid before \u2018red hand\u2019 march on Westminster|newspaper=The Independent|date=18 October 2019|accessdate=13 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2019, a protest against the imprisonment of far-right extremist [[Tommy Robinson (activist)|Tommy Robinson]] at the circus descended into violence. A man was arrested for [[actual bodily harm]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/tommy-robinson-protest-arrest-met-police-medic-attack-london-a9044696.html|title=Tommy Robinson: Man hands himself in after medic kicked in head at London protest|newspaper=The Independent|date=7 August 2019|accessdate=12 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n===Citations===\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|last=Day|first=John R|last2=Reed|first2=John|year=2010|origyear=1963|title=The Story of London's Underground|publisher=Capital Transport|isbn=978-1-85414-341-9|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Glinert|first=Ed|title=West End Chronicles: 300 Years of Glamour and Excess in the Heart of London|publisher=Penguin|year=2008|isbn=978-0-141-02464-6|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Horne |first=Mike |year=2001 |title=The Bakerloo Line: An Illustrated History |publisher=Capital Transport |location=Harrow |isbn=978-1-85414-248-1 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Wolmar |first=Christian |authorlink=Christian Wolmar |title=The Subterranean Railway: How the London Underground Was Built and How It Changed the City Forever |publisher=Atlantic Books |location=London |isbn=978-1-84354-023-6 |origyear=2004 |year=2005 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|title=Oxford Circus|work=Survey of London|author=Bartlett School of Architecture|url=https://www.ucl.ac.uk/bartlett/architecture/sites/bartlett/files/sol_oxfordst_chapter12.pdf|volume=Chapter 12|ref={{harvid|Bartlett}}}}\n{{london encyclopedia}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category-inline}}\n{{coord|51|30|55|N|00|08|31|W|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Oxford Street]]\n[[Category:Road junctions in London]]\n", "name_user": "Ham II", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:style", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oxford_Circus"}
{"title_page": "Briggs' Plan", "text_new": "[[File:New Village in Malaya, 1950s.jpg|thumb|alt=|Photograph of a model New Village internment camp, designed as part of the Briggs' Plan to segregate the largely ethnic [[Malaysian Chinese]] rural workers from communist guerrillas. ]]\nThe '''Briggs' Plan''' was a military plan devised by [[United Kingdom|British]] General Sir [[Harold Rawdon Briggs|Harold Briggs]] shortly after his appointment in 1950 as Director of Operations during the [[Malayan Emergency]] (1948-1960). The plan aimed to defeat the Malayan [[communist]] guerrillas by cutting them off from their sources of support amongst the rural population.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Massacre in Malaya: Exposing Britain's My Lai|last=Hale|first=Christopher|publisher=The History Press|year=2013|isbn=978-0-7524-8701-4|location=Brimscombe Port|pages=326}}</ref> To achieve this a large programme of [[forced resettlement]] of Malayan peasantry was undertaken, under which about 500,000 people (roughly ten percent of [[Federation of Malaya|Malaya's]] population) were forcefully removed from their land and imprisoned in internment camps called \"[[New Villages]]\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=British  Counterinsurgency|last=Newsinger|first=John|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|year=2015|isbn=978-0-230-29824-8|location=Basingstoke|pages=48}}</ref> During the Emergency there were over 400 of these guarded camps. Furthermore, 10,000 [[Malaysian Chinese]] people suspected of being communist sympathisers were deported to mainland China by 1949 where many were then executed.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Blood Never Dried: A People's History of the British Empire|last=Newsinger|first=John|publisher=Bookmarks Publications|year=2013|isbn=978-1-909026-29-2|location=London|pages=218}}</ref> The Malayan aboriginals, the [[Orang Asli]], were also targeted for forced relocation by the Briggs' Plan because the British believing that they were supporting the communists.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Violence and the Dream People: The Orang Asli in the Emergency 1948-1960|last=D. Leary|first=John|publisher=Ohio University Press|year=1995|isbn=0-89680-186-1|location=Athens|pages=42-43}}</ref>\n\nMany of the practices necessary for the Briggs' Plan were prohibited by the [[Geneva Conventions]] and [[customary international law]] which stated that the destruction of property must not happen unless rendered absolutely necessary by military operations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://digitalcommons.csbsju.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?referer=https://en.wikipedia.org/&httpsredir=1&article=1014&context=polsci_pubs|title=The Other Forgotten War: Understanding Atrocities during the Malayan Emergency Malayan Emergency|last=Siver|first=Christi|date=2009|url-status=live|access-date=25 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nBritish authority in Malaya's rural areas had only been tenuously reestablished following the withdrawal of [[Japan]] at the end of [[World War II]]. The British regarded a group of about 500,000 \"[[squatter]]s\", largely of [[Chinese Malaysian|Chinese]] descent, who practiced [[small-scale agriculture]], generally lacked legal title to their land, and were largely outside the reach of the colonial administration, as particularly problematic. Many of these Chinese people had been forced to live in isolated communities to avoid slaughter by the occupying Japanese.\n\nIn order to force rural workers off their land, the British military burned down rural villages, destroyed crops and killed livestock. Some villagers would later receive compensation but most would not.<ref>{{Cite book|title=British Counterinsurgency|last=Newsinger|first=John|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|year=2015|isbn=978-0-230-29824-8|location=Basingstoke|pages=52}}</ref> These communities formed the backbone of the [[Malayan Communist Party]] (MCP), their armed wing the [[Malayan National Liberation Army]] (MNLA), and their civilian supplies and intelligence network the 'Min Yuen'.<ref name=\":0\" /> Many rural workers were sympathetic to [[communism]] due to their role of the MCP as leaders of the WWII [[Anti-Japanese resistance]] movement. Other factors which led to support for the communists include; the desire for Malayan independence from Britain, the communist victory in China, the communist role in leading the Malayan trade union movement, economic inequality and poverty post-WWII and resentment towards the racism of British rule. Other rural workers who did not want to support the communist guerrillas did so anyway due to fear of backlash by their neighbours and the communist guerrillas.\n\nBy isolating this population in the \"new villages\", the British were able to stem the critical flow of food, information, and recruits from peasants to guerillas.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Alias Chin Peng: My Side of History|last=Peng|first=Chin|publisher=Media Masters|year=2003|isbn=981-04-8693-6|location=Singapore|pages=268}}</ref> The new settlements were guarded around-the-clock by police and many were partially fortified with barbed wire and sentry towers. This served the twofold purpose of preventing those who were so inclined from getting out and voluntarily aiding the guerrilla, and of preventing the guerrilla from getting in and extracting help via persuasion or intimidation. 450 new settlements were created in this process and it is estimated that 470,509 people, 400,000 of them Chinese, were involved in the program. The [[Malaysian Chinese Association]], (known then as the Malayan Chinese Association), played a crucial role in implementing the programme.<ref name=\"Gin2009\">{{cite book|author=Ooi Keat Gin|title=Historical Dictionary of Malaysia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=assDznc7EN4C|accessdate=16 February 2013|date=11 May 2009|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-6305-7|pages=lvii, 185}}</ref>\n\nThe British also tried to win the support of some of the internees by providing them with education and health services. Some New Villages were equipped with amenities such as electricity and piped water and surrounded with perimeter fencing and armed guards to keep the civilians from escaping\u2013 many of whom had formerly been in the MCP or had been forced to provide assistance. It was hoped that by providing the largely ethnic Chinese communities with such facilities, they would be converted from \"reservoirs of resentment into bastions of loyal Malayan citizenry\". However, critics argue that the homogenous nature of New Villages &mdash; with the few multiracial ones eventually failing or turning into [[ghetto]]es &mdash; worked against this goal, instead accentuating communalist fervour and causing [[racial polarisation]], especially in politics, as electoral constituencies would now be delineated more along racial lines.\n\nPreviously, the Chinese rural workers and peasants had been spread out geographically, but the Briggs' Plan would now bring together rural Chinese from all over the country and concentrate them in the New Villages. There was significant resentment towards the programme both among the Chinese and Malays. The Chinese frequently suffered from [[collective punishment]], [[preventive detention]] and [[summary deportation]] aimed at weeding out communist supporters, while the Malays were incensed at the infrastructure provided for the New Villages as their own settlements remained undeveloped.<ref>Ongkili, pp. 85&ndash;88.</ref> One example of this collective punishment comes from [[Tanjung Malim]] where the British put the civilian population on rice rations in order to stop them from supporting the communist guerrillas. When this did not work, [[Gerald Templer]] halfed the rice rations for civilians within the area and imposed a 22 hour curfew.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Small Wars Faraway Places: Global Insurrection and the Making of the Modern World 1945-1965|last=Michael|first=Burleigh|publisher=Viking - Penguin Group|year=2013|isbn=978-0-670-02545-9|location=New York|pages=178}}</ref>\n\n== Similar examples ==\nForcibly removing a population that might be sympathetic to guerrillas was a [[counter-insurgency]] (COIN) technique which the British had used before, [[Second Boer War#Concentration camps .281900.E2.80.931902.29|notably initiated]] by [[Herbert Kitchener, 1st Earl Kitchener|Kitchener]] against the [[Boer Commando]]s in the [[Second Boer War]] (1899\u20131902). \n\nThe Briggs' Plan and the New Village system became a model for British counterinsurgency efforts in Kenya during the [[Mau Mau Uprising]].\n\nUpon completion of the programme, the British initiated the [[Hunger Drive]] in an effort to flush out the communists from the jungle.{{citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\n\u201cFour cuts\u201d strategy against villages and insurgents of  [[Communist Party of Burma]] insurgents in [[Pegu Range]].   [https://www2.irrawaddy.com/opinion_story.php?art_id=15386 Generals Go Marching Down Memory Lane By AUNG ZAW in Irrawaddy Magazine]\n\n==See also==\n* [[New Village]] / Chinese New Village\n*[[Malayan Emergency]]\n*[[Malayan Communist Party]]\n*[[Internment]]\n*[[Malayan National Liberation Army]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n* \n\n{{Communism in Malaysia}}\n\n[[Category:Forced migration]]\n[[Category:Internments]]\n[[Category:Malayan Emergency]]\n[[Category:Internment camps]]\n[[Category:British war crimes]]\n[[Category:Anti-communism]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:New Village in Malaya, 1950s.jpg|thumb|alt=|Photograph of a model New Village internment camp, designed as part of the Briggs' Plan to segregate the largely ethnic [[Malaysian Chinese]] rural workers from communist guerrillas. ]]\nThe '''Briggs' Plan''' was a military plan devised by [[United Kingdom|British]] General Sir [[Harold Rawdon Briggs|Harold Briggs]] shortly after his appointment in 1950 as Director of Operations during the [[Malayan Emergency]] (1948-1960). The plan aimed to defeat the Malayan [[communist]] guerrillas by cutting them off from their sources of support amongst the rural population.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Massacre in Malaya: Exposing Britain's My Lai|last=Hale|first=Christopher|publisher=The History Press|year=2013|isbn=978-0-7524-8701-4|location=Brimscombe Port|pages=326}}</ref> To achieve this a large programme of [[forced resettlement]] of Malayan peasantry was undertaken, under which about 500,000 people (roughly ten percent of [[Federation of Malaya|Malaya's]] population) were forcefully removed from their land and imprisoned in internment camps called \"[[New Villages]]\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=British  Counterinsurgency|last=Newsinger|first=John|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|year=2015|isbn=978-0-230-29824-8|location=Basingstoke|pages=48}}</ref> During the Emergency there were over 400 of these guarded camps. Furthermore, 10,000 [[Malaysian Chinese]] people suspected of being communist sympathisers were deported to mainland China by 1949 where many were then executed.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Blood Never Dried: A People's History of the British Empire|last=Newsinger|first=John|publisher=Bookmarks Publications|year=2013|isbn=978-1-909026-29-2|location=London|pages=218}}</ref> The Malayan aboriginals, the [[Orang Asli]], were also targeted for forced relocation by the Briggs' Plan because the British believing that they were supporting the communists.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Violence and the Dream People: The Orang Asli in the Emergency 1948-1960|last=D. Leary|first=John|publisher=Ohio University Press|year=1995|isbn=0-89680-186-1|location=Athens|pages=42-43}}</ref>\n\nMany of the practices necessary for the Briggs' Plan were prohibited by the [[Geneva Conventions]] and [[customary international law]] which stated that the destruction of property must not happen unless rendered absolutely necessary by military operations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://digitalcommons.csbsju.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?referer=https://en.wikipedia.org/&httpsredir=1&article=1014&context=polsci_pubs|title=The Other Forgotten War: Understanding Atrocities during the Malayan Emergency Malayan Emergency|last=Siver|first=Christi|date=2009|url-status=live|access-date=25 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nBritish authority in Malaya's rural areas had only been tenuously reestablished following the withdrawal of [[Japan]] at the end of [[World War II]]. The British regarded a group of about 500,000 \"[[squatter]]s\", largely of [[Chinese Malaysian|Chinese]] descent, who practiced [[small-scale agriculture]], generally lacked legal title to their land, and were largely outside the reach of the colonial administration, as particularly problematic. Many of these Chinese people had been forced to live in isolated communities to avoid slaughter by the occupying Japanese.\n\nIn order to force rural workers off their land, the British military burned down rural villages, destroyed crops and killed livestock. Some villagers would later receive compensation but most would not.<ref>{{Cite book|title=British Counterinsurgency|last=Newsinger|first=John|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|year=2015|isbn=978-0-230-29824-8|location=Basingstoke|pages=52}}</ref> These communities formed the backbone of the [[Malayan Communist Party]] (MCP), their armed wing the [[Malayan National Liberation Army]] (MNLA), and their civilian supplies and intelligence network the 'Min Yuen'.<ref name=\":0\" /> Many rural workers were sympathetic to [[communism]] due to their role of the MCP as leaders of the WWII [[Anti-Japanese resistance]] movement. Other factors which led to support for the communists include; the desire for Malayan independence from Britain, the communist victory in China, the communist role in leading the Malayan trade union movement, economic inequality and poverty post-WWII and resentment towards the racism of British rule. Other rural workers who did not want to support the communist guerrillas did so anyway due to fear of backlash by their neighbours and the communist guerrillas.\n\nBy isolating this population in the \"new villages\", the British were able to stem the critical flow of food, information, and recruits from peasants to guerillas.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Alias Chin Peng: My Side of History|last=Peng|first=Chin|publisher=Media Masters|year=2003|isbn=981-04-8693-6|location=Singapore|pages=268}}</ref> The new settlements were guarded around-the-clock by police and many were partially fortified with barbed wire and sentry towers. This served the twofold purpose of preventing those who were so inclined from getting out and voluntarily aiding the guerrilla, and of preventing the guerrilla from getting in and extracting help via persuasion or intimidation. 450 new settlements were created in this process and it is estimated that 470,509 people, 400,000 of them Chinese, were involved in the program. The [[Malaysian Chinese Association]], (known then as the Malayan Chinese Association), played a crucial role in implementing the programme.<ref name=\"Gin2009\">{{cite book|author=Ooi Keat Gin|title=Historical Dictionary of Malaysia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=assDznc7EN4C|accessdate=16 February 2013|date=11 May 2009|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-6305-7|pages=lvii, 185}}</ref>\n\nThe British also tried to win the support of some of the internees by providing them with education and health services. Some New Villages were equipped with amenities such as electricity and piped water and surrounded with perimeter fencing and armed guards to keep the civilians from escaping\u2013 many of whom had formerly been in the MCP or had been forced to provide assistance. It was hoped that by providing the largely ethnic Chinese communities with such facilities, they would be converted from \"reservoirs of resentment into bastions of loyal Malayan citizenry\". However, critics argue that the homogenous nature of New Villages &mdash; with the few multiracial ones eventually failing or turning into [[ghetto]]es &mdash; worked against this goal, instead accentuating communalist fervour and causing [[racial polarisation]], especially in politics, as electoral constituencies would now be delineated more along racial lines.\n\nPreviously, the Chinese rural workers and peasants had been spread out geographically, but the Briggs' Plan would now bring together rural Chinese from all over the country and concentrate them in the New Villages. There was significant resentment towards the programme both among the Chinese and Malays. The Chinese frequently suffered from [[collective punishment]], [[preventive detention]] and [[summary deportation]] aimed at weeding out communist supporters, while the Malays were incensed at the infrastructure provided for the New Villages as their own settlements remained undeveloped.<ref>Ongkili, pp. 85&ndash;88.</ref> One example of this collective punishment comes from [[Tanjung Malim]] where the British put the civilian population on rice rations in order to stop them from supporting the communist guerrillas. When this did not work, [[Gerald Templer]] halfed the rice rations for civilians within the area and imposed a 22 hour curfew.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Small Wars Faraway Places: Global Insurrection and the Making of the Modern World 1945-1965|last=Michael|first=Burleigh|publisher=Viking - Penguin Group|year=2013|isbn=978-0-670-02545-9|location=New York|pages=178}}</ref>\n\n== Similar examples ==\nForcibly removing a population that might be sympathetic to guerrillas was a [[counter-insurgency]] (COIN) technique which the British had used before, [[Second Boer War#Concentration camps .281900.E2.80.931902.29|notably initiated]] by [[Herbert Kitchener, 1st Earl Kitchener|Kitchener]] against the [[Boer Commando]]s in the [[Second Boer War]] (1899\u20131902). \n\nThe Briggs' Plan and the New Village system became a model for British counterinsurgency efforts in Kenya during the [[Mau Mau Uprising]].\n\nUpon completion of the programme, the British initiated the [[Hunger Drive]] in an effort to flush out the communists from the jungle.{{citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\n\u201cFour cuts\u201d strategy against villages and insurgents of  [[Communist Party of Burma]] insurgents in [[Pegu Range]]  [https://www2.irrawaddy.com/opinion_story.php?art_id=15386 Generals Go Marching Down Memory Lane By AUNG ZAW in Irrawaddy Magazine]\n\n==See also==\n* [[New Village]] / Chinese New Village\n*[[Malayan Emergency]]\n*[[Malayan Communist Party]]\n*[[Internment]]\n*[[Malayan National Liberation Army]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n* \n\n{{Communism in Malaysia}}\n\n[[Category:Forced migration]]\n[[Category:Internments]]\n[[Category:Malayan Emergency]]\n[[Category:Internment camps]]\n[[Category:British war crimes]]\n[[Category:Anti-communism]]\n", "name_user": "Darz kkg", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSimilar examples:Putting 'full stop' only.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Briggs%27_Plan"}
{"title_page": "The Girl King", "text_new": "{{for|the 2002 film|Girl King}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Girl King\n| image          = Affiche 209 La reine-gar\u00e7on Fr.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = \n| director       = [[Mika Kaurism\u00e4ki]]\n| producer       = [[Arnie Gelbart]]<br>Mika Kaurism\u00e4ki\n| writer         = [[Michel Marc Bouchard]]\n| starring       = [[Malin Buska]]<br>[[Sarah Gadon]]<br>[[Michael Nyqvist]]<br>[[Lucas Bryant]]<br>[[Patrick Bauchau]]\n| music          = [[Anssi Tikanm\u00e4ki]]\n| cinematography = [[Guy Dufaux]]\n| editing        = [[Hans Funck]]\n| studio         = [[Marianna Films]]<br>[[Triptych Media]]\n| distributor    = \n| released       = {{Film date|2015|09|04|df=y|[[Montreal Film Festival]]}}\n| runtime        = 106 min\n| country        = Finland<br>Canada<br>Sweden<br>Germany<br>France\n| language       = English<br>French<br>German\n}}\n'''''The Girl King''''' is a 2015 biographical lesbien porn drama about [[Christina, Queen of Sweden]]. It was directed by [[Mika Kaurism\u00e4ki]] and written by [[Michel Marc Bouchard]] who, after writing the screenplay for the film, wrote his stage play ''Christine, La Reine-Gar\u00e7on'' which enjoyed a successful run in 2012 at Montreal's [[Th\u00e9\u00e2tre du Nouveau Monde]] and then in English at the [[Stratford Festival]] in 2014.  The film premiered at the [[Montreal World Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kilkenny|first1=Carmel|title=\u2018The Girl King\u2019 premieres at the Montreal World Film Festival|url=http://www.rcinet.ca/en/2015/09/04/the-girl-king-premieres-at-the-montreal-world-film-festival/}}</ref><ref>Michel Marc Bouchard, ''Christine, La Reine-Gar\u00e7on'' [2nd edition of the play] (Montreal, 2013). {{ISBN|9782760904309}}.</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Malin Buska]] as [[Christina, Queen of Sweden|Kristina]]\n* [[Sarah Gadon]] as Countess [[Ebba Sparre]]\n* [[Michael Nyqvist]] as Chancellor [[Axel Oxenstierna]]\n* [[Lucas Bryant]] as Count [[Johan Oxenstierna]]\n* [[Laura Birn]] as Countess Erika Erksein\n* [[Hippolyte Girardot]] as Ambassador [[Pierre Chanut|Pierre Hector Chanut]]\n* [[Peter Lohmeyer]] as Bishop Of Stockholm\n* [[Fran\u00e7ois Arnaud (actor)|Fran\u00e7ois Arnaud]] as [[Charles X Gustav of Sweden|Karl Gustav Kasimir]]\n* [[Martina Gedeck]] as [[Maria Eleonora of Brandenburg|Maria Eleonora]]\n* [[Patrick Bauchau]] as [[Ren\u00e9 Descartes]]\n\n== Reception ==\n\n=== Critical response ===\nThe film has received divided acclaim. At [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has a rating of 47%, based on 15 reviews and an average rating of 4.9/10.<ref name=\"Rotten Tomatoes\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/771431468/ | title=The Girl King (2015) | publisher=Rotten Tomatoes. |accessdate=12 February 2015}}</ref> \nDana Piccoli at ''AfterEllen'' stated: \"Anytime we get to see a story about queer women in history is a good thing, and The Girl King is certainly an interesting look at this enigmatic ruler. While I wish it could have been a bit stronger in its delivery, it\u2019s still a very watchable film.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afterellen.com/movies/453015-girl-king-tells-tale-swedens-queer-queen-christina-lady-love/ |title=\u201cThe Girl King\u201d tells the tale of Sweden\u2019s queer Queen Christina and her lady love |publisher=AfterEllen|accessdate=12 December 2015|date=16 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Awards ===\nThe film won two awards at the [[Montreal World Film Festival]], Best Actress to Malin Buska, and Most Popular Canadian Feature Film to director Mika Kaurism\u00e4ki. It also won best Best Film at the [[Valladolid International Film Festival]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|1254322|The Girl King}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Girl King, The}}\n[[Category:2015 films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Mika Kaurism\u00e4ki]]\n[[Category:Finnish drama films]]\n[[Category:Finnish LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:Canadian drama films]]\n[[Category:Canadian films]]\n[[Category:Canadian LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:Biographical films about Swedish royalty]]\n[[Category:2010s LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:LGBT-related drama films]]\n[[Category:Films set in Sweden]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 17th century]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Christina, Queen of Sweden]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Ren\u00e9 Descartes]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the 2002 film|Girl King}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Girl King\n| image          = Affiche 209 La reine-gar\u00e7on Fr.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = \n| director       = [[Mika Kaurism\u00e4ki]]\n| producer       = [[Arnie Gelbart]]<br>Mika Kaurism\u00e4ki\n| writer         = [[Michel Marc Bouchard]]\n| starring       = [[Malin Buska]]<br>[[Sarah Gadon]]<br>[[Michael Nyqvist]]<br>[[Lucas Bryant]]<br>[[Patrick Bauchau]]\n| music          = [[Anssi Tikanm\u00e4ki]]\n| cinematography = [[Guy Dufaux]]\n| editing        = [[Hans Funck]]\n| studio         = [[Marianna Films]]<br>[[Triptych Media]]\n| distributor    = \n| released       = {{Film date|2015|09|04|df=y|[[Montreal Film Festival]]}}\n| runtime        = 106 min\n| country        = Finland<br>Canada<br>Sweden<br>Germany<br>France\n| language       = English<br>French<br>German\n}}\n'''''The Girl King''''' is a 2015 biographical drama about [[Christina, Queen of Sweden]]. It was directed by [[Mika Kaurism\u00e4ki]] and written by [[Michel Marc Bouchard]] who, after writing the screenplay for the film, wrote his stage play ''Christine, La Reine-Gar\u00e7on'' which enjoyed a successful run in 2012 at Montreal's [[Th\u00e9\u00e2tre du Nouveau Monde]] and then in English at the [[Stratford Festival]] in 2014.  The film premiered at the [[Montreal World Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kilkenny|first1=Carmel|title=\u2018The Girl King\u2019 premieres at the Montreal World Film Festival|url=http://www.rcinet.ca/en/2015/09/04/the-girl-king-premieres-at-the-montreal-world-film-festival/}}</ref><ref>Michel Marc Bouchard, ''Christine, La Reine-Gar\u00e7on'' [2nd edition of the play] (Montreal, 2013). {{ISBN|9782760904309}}.</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Malin Buska]] as [[Christina, Queen of Sweden|Kristina]]\n* [[Sarah Gadon]] as Countess [[Ebba Sparre]]\n* [[Michael Nyqvist]] as Chancellor [[Axel Oxenstierna]]\n* [[Lucas Bryant]] as Count [[Johan Oxenstierna]]\n* [[Laura Birn]] as Countess Erika Erksein\n* [[Hippolyte Girardot]] as Ambassador [[Pierre Chanut|Pierre Hector Chanut]]\n* [[Peter Lohmeyer]] as Bishop Of Stockholm\n* [[Fran\u00e7ois Arnaud (actor)|Fran\u00e7ois Arnaud]] as [[Charles X Gustav of Sweden|Karl Gustav Kasimir]]\n* [[Martina Gedeck]] as [[Maria Eleonora of Brandenburg|Maria Eleonora]]\n* [[Patrick Bauchau]] as [[Ren\u00e9 Descartes]]\n\n== Reception ==\n\n=== Critical response ===\nThe film has received divided acclaim. At [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has a rating of 47%, based on 15 reviews and an average rating of 4.9/10.<ref name=\"Rotten Tomatoes\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/771431468/ | title=The Girl King (2015) | publisher=Rotten Tomatoes. |accessdate=12 February 2015}}</ref> \nDana Piccoli at ''AfterEllen'' stated: \"Anytime we get to see a story about queer women in history is a good thing, and The Girl King is certainly an interesting look at this enigmatic ruler. While I wish it could have been a bit stronger in its delivery, it\u2019s still a very watchable film.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afterellen.com/movies/453015-girl-king-tells-tale-swedens-queer-queen-christina-lady-love/ |title=\u201cThe Girl King\u201d tells the tale of Sweden\u2019s queer Queen Christina and her lady love |publisher=AfterEllen|accessdate=12 December 2015|date=16 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Awards ===\nThe film won two awards at the [[Montreal World Film Festival]], Best Actress to Malin Buska, and Most Popular Canadian Feature Film to director Mika Kaurism\u00e4ki. It also won best Best Film at the [[Valladolid International Film Festival]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|1254322|The Girl King}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Girl King, The}}\n[[Category:2015 films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Mika Kaurism\u00e4ki]]\n[[Category:Finnish drama films]]\n[[Category:Finnish LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:Canadian drama films]]\n[[Category:Canadian films]]\n[[Category:Canadian LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:Biographical films about Swedish royalty]]\n[[Category:2010s LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:LGBT-related drama films]]\n[[Category:Films set in Sweden]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 17th century]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Christina, Queen of Sweden]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Ren\u00e9 Descartes]]\n", "name_user": "39.41.192.210", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Girl_King"}
