{"title_page": "Elizabeth", "text_new": "{{wiktionary|Elizabeth|Al\u017ebeta|Elisabeth|Elizabeta|\u00c9lisabeth}}\n'''Elizabeth''' or '''Elisabeth''' may refer to:\n{{TOC right}}\n==People==\n* [[Elizabeth (given name)]], a female given name (including people with that name)\nLiz is the most beautiful woman known to all mankind and I love her with all my heart.\n\n==Ships==\n* [[HMS Elizabeth|HMS ''Elizabeth'']], several ships\n* [[Elisabeth (schooner)|''Elisabeth'' (schooner)]], several ships\n* [[Elizabeth (freighter)|''Elizabeth'' (freighter)]], [[Margaret Fuller]] died aboard this ship, when it was wrecked off New York harbor in 1850\n\n==Places==\n\n===Australia===\n* [[City of Elizabeth]]\n** [[Elizabeth, South Australia]]\n* [[Elizabeth Reef]], a coral reef in the Tasman Sea\n\n===United States===\n* [[Elizabeth, Arkansas]]\n* [[Elizabeth, Colorado]]\n* [[Elizabeth, Georgia]]\n* [[Elizabeth, Illinois]]\n* [[Elizabeth, Indiana]]\n* [[Hopkinsville, Kentucky]], originally known as Elizabeth\n* [[Elizabeth, Louisiana]]\n* [[Elizabeth Islands]], Massachusetts\n* [[Elizabeth, Minnesota]]\n* [[Elizabeth, New Jersey]], largest city with the name in the U.S.\n* [[Elizabeth City, North Carolina]]\n* [[Elizabeth, Pennsylvania]]\n* [[Elizabeth Township, Pennsylvania (disambiguation)]]\n* [[Elizabeth, West Virginia]]\n\n==Film and television==\n* ''[[Elizabeth R]]'', 1971\n* [[Elizabeth (TV series)|''Elizabeth'' (TV series)]], 1980\n* [[Elizabeth (film)|''Elizabeth'' (film)]], 1998\n* ''[[Elizabeth: The Golden Age]]'', 2007\n\n==Music==\n* [[Elisabeth (album)|''Elisabeth'' (album)]], a 1990 album by Elisabeth Andreassen\n* ''Elizabeth'' by [[Killah Priest]]\n* [[Elizabeth (Ghost song)]]\n* [[Elizabeth (The Statler Brothers song)|\"Elizabeth\" (The Statler Brothers song)]]\n* [[Elizabeth (band)]], an American psychedelic rock/progressive rock band active from 1967 to 1970\n\n==Other uses==\n* \"Elizabeth\", a poem by [[Edgar Allan Poe]]\n* [[Elisabeth (musical)|''Elisabeth'' (musical)]], a 1992 Viennese German-language musical written by Michael Kunze and composed by Sylvester Levay, about the life of Elisabeth of Bavaria\n* [[Elizabeth (BioShock)|Elizabeth (''BioShock'')]], a fictional character in ''BioShock''\n* [[Elisabeth (Antwerp premetro station)]]\n\n==See also==\n* {{in title|Elizabeth}}\n* [[Elizabeth Cup (disambiguation)]]\n* [[Elizabeth Stakes (disambiguation)]]\n* [[Elizaveta (disambiguation)]]\n* [[Elisaveta (disambiguation)]]\n* [[Jelisaveta (disambiguation)]]\n\n{{disambiguation|geo}}\n", "text_old": "{{wiktionary|Elizabeth|Al\u017ebeta|Elisabeth|Elizabeta|\u00c9lisabeth}}\n'''Elizabeth''' or '''Elisabeth''' may refer to:\n{{TOC right}}\n==People==\n* [[Elizabeth (given name)]], a female given name (including people with that name)\n\n==Ships==\n* [[HMS Elizabeth|HMS ''Elizabeth'']], several ships\n* [[Elisabeth (schooner)|''Elisabeth'' (schooner)]], several ships\n* [[Elizabeth (freighter)|''Elizabeth'' (freighter)]], [[Margaret Fuller]] died aboard this ship, when it was wrecked off New York harbor in 1850\n\n==Places==\n\n===Australia===\n* [[City of Elizabeth]]\n** [[Elizabeth, South Australia]]\n* [[Elizabeth Reef]], a coral reef in the Tasman Sea\n\n===United States===\n* [[Elizabeth, Arkansas]]\n* [[Elizabeth, Colorado]]\n* [[Elizabeth, Georgia]]\n* [[Elizabeth, Illinois]]\n* [[Elizabeth, Indiana]]\n* [[Hopkinsville, Kentucky]], originally known as Elizabeth\n* [[Elizabeth, Louisiana]]\n* [[Elizabeth Islands]], Massachusetts\n* [[Elizabeth, Minnesota]]\n* [[Elizabeth, New Jersey]], largest city with the name in the U.S.\n* [[Elizabeth City, North Carolina]]\n* [[Elizabeth, Pennsylvania]]\n* [[Elizabeth Township, Pennsylvania (disambiguation)]]\n* [[Elizabeth, West Virginia]]\n\n==Film and television==\n* ''[[Elizabeth R]]'', 1971\n* [[Elizabeth (TV series)|''Elizabeth'' (TV series)]], 1980\n* [[Elizabeth (film)|''Elizabeth'' (film)]], 1998\n* ''[[Elizabeth: The Golden Age]]'', 2007\n\n==Music==\n* [[Elisabeth (album)|''Elisabeth'' (album)]], a 1990 album by Elisabeth Andreassen\n* ''Elizabeth'' by [[Killah Priest]]\n* [[Elizabeth (Ghost song)]]\n* [[Elizabeth (The Statler Brothers song)|\"Elizabeth\" (The Statler Brothers song)]]\n* [[Elizabeth (band)]], an American psychedelic rock/progressive rock band active from 1967 to 1970\n\n==Other uses==\n* \"Elizabeth\", a poem by [[Edgar Allan Poe]]\n* [[Elisabeth (musical)|''Elisabeth'' (musical)]], a 1992 Viennese German-language musical written by Michael Kunze and composed by Sylvester Levay, about the life of Elisabeth of Bavaria\n* [[Elizabeth (BioShock)|Elizabeth (''BioShock'')]], a fictional character in ''BioShock''\n* [[Elisabeth (Antwerp premetro station)]]\n\n==See also==\n* {{in title|Elizabeth}}\n* [[Elizabeth Cup (disambiguation)]]\n* [[Elizabeth Stakes (disambiguation)]]\n* [[Elizaveta (disambiguation)]]\n* [[Elisaveta (disambiguation)]]\n* [[Jelisaveta (disambiguation)]]\n\n{{disambiguation|geo}}\n", "name_user": "2600:8800:b100:bf00:dd5:ddb8:bcc1:1ba7", "label": "vandal", "comment": "(\u2192\u200ePeople:Further explained the origin of the name)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elizabeth"}
{"title_page": "Johnny Clegg", "text_new": "{{redirect|Jonathan Clegg|the British rower|Jono Clegg}}\n{{similar names|John Clegg (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|South African musician and anti-apartheid icon}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name             = Johnny Clegg<br><small>[[Order of the British Empire|OBE]], [[Order of Ikhamanga|OIS]]</small>\n| image            = Johnny-clegg-valenciennes-davidata-14 07 2009.jpg\n| alt = Clegg singing and playing concertina\n| landscape        =\n| caption          = Clegg performing live in 2009\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = Jonathan Paul Clegg\n| alias            = ''Le Zoulou Blanc''\n| birth_date       = {{birth date|df=yes|1953|6|7}}\n| birth_place      = [[Bacup]], Lancashire, England\n| death_date       = {{death date and age|2019|7|16|1953|6|7|df=yes}}\n| death_place      = [[Johannesburg]], [[South Africa]]\n| origin           = \n| instrument       = Vocals, guitar, [[concertina]]\n| genre            = [[Mbaqanga]], [[African popular music|Afro-pop]] <ref>{{cite web |last=Nobanda |first=Chuma |date=16 July 2019 |title=Legendary musician Johnny Clegg has died |url=http://www.sabcnews.com/sabcnews/legendary-musician-johnny-clegg-has-died/ |website=SABC Africa |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190716201007/http://www.sabcnews.com/sabcnews/legendary-musician-johnny-clegg-has-died/ |archive-date=16 July 2019 |access-date=8 October 2019}}</ref>\n| occupation       =  [[Musician]], [[Anthropologist]]\n| years_active     = 1976\u20132018\n| label            = [[Capitol Records]]<ref name=Lewis-Aug2017>{{cite web |last=Lewis |first=Randy |date=26 August 2017 |title=South Africa's Johnny Clegg, with cancer in remission, to embark the Final Journey U.S. tour |url=https://www.mcall.com/la-et-ms-johnny-clegg-cancer-final-journey-us-tour-20170816-story.html |website=The Morning Call |location=Allentown, PA |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191008043316/https://www.mcall.com/la-et-ms-johnny-clegg-cancer-final-journey-us-tour-20170816-story.html |archive-date=8 October 2019 |access-date=8 October 2019}}</ref>\n| associated_acts  = [[Juluka]], [[Savuka]]\n| website          = [http://www.johnnyclegg.com johnnyclegg.com]\n}}\n\n'''Jonathan Paul Clegg''', [[Order of the British Empire|OBE]], [[Order of Ikhamanga|OIS]] (7 June 1953 \u2013 16 July 2019) was a South African musician and [[anthropologist]], some of whose work was in musicology focused on the music of indigenous South African peoples.<ref name=sexton/> His band [[Juluka]] began as a duo with [[Sipho Mchunu]], and was the first group in the South African [[apartheid]]-era with a white man and a black man. The pair performed and recorded, later with an expanded lineup.\n\nIn 1986 Clegg founded the band [[Savuka]], and also recorded as a solo act, occasionally reuniting with his earlier band partners. Sometimes called ''Le Zoulou Blanc'' ({{IPA-fr|l\u0259 zulu bl\u0251\u0303|lang}}, for \"The White [[Zulu people|Zulu]]\"), he was an important figure in South African popular music and one of the most prominent white activists in [[Internal resistance to apartheid|resistance to apartheid]],<ref name=LeMonde-Jul2019>{{cite web |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=16 July 2019 |title=Mort du chanteur sud-africain Johnny Clegg, \u00ab&nbsp;le Zoulou blanc&nbsp;\u00bb qui combattait l\u2019apartheid |url=https://www.lemonde.fr/disparitions/article/2019/07/16/mort-du-chanteur-sud-africain-johnny-clegg-le-zoulou-blanc-qui-combattait-l-apartheid_5490110_3382.html |website=Le Monde |location=Paris |trans-title=Death of South African singer Johnny Clegg, the \"white Zulu\" who fought apartheid |language=fr |agency=AFP |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190716212749/https://www.lemonde.fr/disparitions/article/2019/07/16/mort-du-chanteur-sud-africain-johnny-clegg-le-zoulou-blanc-qui-combattait-l-apartheid_5490110_3382.html |archive-date=16 July 2019 |access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref> with songs that mixed [[Zulu language|Zulu]] and English lyrics, also combining [[Music of Africa|African music]] with various Western styles.<ref name=Cartwright-Jul2019>{{cite web |last=Cartwright |first=Gareth |date=24 July 2019 |title=Johnny Clegg: South African singer whose cross-cultural music was a direct challenge to apartheid |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/johnny-clegg-death-singer-south-africa-apartheid-nelson-mandela-obituary-a9008716.html |website=The Independent |location=London |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190725142755/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/johnny-clegg-death-singer-south-africa-apartheid-nelson-mandela-obituary-a9008716.html |archive-date=25 July 2019 |access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and career==\nClegg was born on 7 June 1953 in [[Bacup]], [[Lancashire]],<ref name=\"official\">{{cite web|url=http://www.johnnyclegg.com/biog.html|title=JOHNNY CLEGG BIOGRAPHY AND AWARDS|publisher=JohnnyClegg.com|accessdate=2 July 2015}}</ref> to an English father of Scottish descent, Dennis Clegg, and a Rhodesian mother, Muriel (Braudo).<ref>{{cite web |author=<!--Not stated-->|date=22 July 2006 |title=White Zulu is making a comeback |url=https://www.iol.co.za/entertainment/celebrity-news/white-zulu-is-making-a-comeback-940896 |website=Independent Online (IOL) |location=Cape Town |access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=Cowell-Jul2019>{{cite web |last=Cowell |first=Alan |date=16 July 2019 |title=Johnny Clegg, South African Singer Who Battled Apartheid With Music, Is Dead at 66|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/16/arts/music/johnny-clegg-dead.html |website=The New York Times |access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref> Clegg's mother's family were [[Jews|Jewish]] immigrants from [[Lithuania]], and Clegg had a secular Jewish upbringing, learning about the [[Ten Commandments]] but refusing to have a ''[[bar mitzvah]]'' or even associate with other Jewish children at school.<ref name=Bernarde-2003>{{cite book |last=Benarde |first=Scott R. |date=2003 |title=Stars of David: Rock'n'roll's Jewish Stories |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XI4-VnSrEcAC&pg=PA3 |publisher=Brandeis University Press |location=Waltham, MA |pages=3,279\u2013283 |isbn=1584653035 |access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref> His parents divorced when he was still an infant, and he moved with his mother to Rhodesia (now [[Zimbabwe]]) and then, at the age of six, to South Africa,<ref name=\"people\">{{cite web |last1=Freeman |first1=Patricia |last2=McCoy |first2=Melissa |date=24 October 1988 |title=Black and White and Heard All Over, Johnny Clegg and Savuka Cross South Africa's Color Barrier |url=https://people.com/archive/black-and-white-and-heard-all-over-johnny-clegg-and-savuka-cross-south-africas-color-barrier-vol-30-no-17/ |website=People |location=New York |volume=30 |issue=17 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170610105846/https://people.com/archive/black-and-white-and-heard-all-over-johnny-clegg-and-savuka-cross-south-africas-color-barrier-vol-30-no-17/ |archive-date=10 June 2017 |access-date=17 April 2020}}</ref> also spending part of a year in [[Israel]] during his childhood.<ref name=Bernarde-2003/>\n\nAs an adolescent in [[Johannesburg]]'s northern suburbs, he encountered the demi-monde of the city's Zulu migrant workers' music and dance. Under the tutelage of Charlie Mzila, a flat cleaner by day and musician by night, Clegg mastered both the [[Zulu language]] and the [[maskandi]] guitar and the isishameni dance styles of the migrants.<ref name=Wits-2019>{{cite web |date=18 July 2019 |url=https://www.wits.ac.za/news/sources/alumni-news/2019/johnny-clegg-1953-2019.html |title=Johnny Clegg (1953\u20132019) |publisher=University of the Witwatersrand |location=Johannesburg |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190718104727/https://www.wits.ac.za/news/sources/alumni-news/2019/johnny-clegg-1953-2019.html |archive-date=18 July 2019 |access-date=17 April 2020}}</ref> Clegg's involvement with black musicians often led to arrests for trespassing on government property and for contravening the [[Group Areas Act]]. He was first arrested at the age of 15 for violating [[apartheid]]-era laws in South Africa banning people of different races from congregating together after curfew hours.<ref name=\"sassen\">{{cite news|url=http://www.popmatters.com/column/sassen021002/|first=Robyn|last=Sassen|date=16 October 2002|accessdate=2 July 2015|agency=PopMatters|title=Johnny Clegg: A South African Story}}</ref>\n\nAt the age of 17, he met [[Sipho Mchunu]], a Zulu migrant worker with whom he began performing music.<ref name=\"people\"/> The partnership, which they named [[Juluka]], was profiled in the 1970s television documentary ''[[Beats of the Heart: Rhythm of Resistance]]''.<ref name=\"beats\">''Beats of the Heart: Rhythm of Resistance'' (1979), dir. Jeremy Marre</ref>\n\nAfter graduating with a [[BA(Hons)]] in [[Social Anthropology]] from the [[University of Witwatersrand]], Clegg pursued an academic career for four years where he lectured and wrote several seminal scholarly papers on [[Zulu music]] and dance.<ref name=Wits-2019/> In the early stages of his musical career, Clegg combined his music with the study of [[anthropology]]<ref name=\"beats\"/> at Wits, where he was influenced, among others, by the work of [[David Webster (anthropologist)|David Webster]], a [[social anthropology|social anthropologist]] who was later assassinated in 1989.<ref name=\"sassen\" /><ref name=\"wbur\">{{cite news|url=http://hereandnow.wbur.org/2014/04/28/johnny-clegg-music|title=Johnny Clegg On South Africa, Post-Mandela|date=28 April 2014|accessdate=2 July 2015|agency=WBUR}}</ref><ref name=\"latimes\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1993-08-12/entertainment/ca-23042_1_south-africa|title=South Africa's Johnny Clegg: A Witness to History|first=Randy|last=Lewis|date=12 August 1993|accessdate=2 July 2015|work=Los Angeles Times}}</ref>\n\nHe preceded each song with snippets of Zulu culture, information, commentary, humor and personal anecdotes relevant and unique to that song,<ref name=Wits-2019/> occasionally also incorporating aspects of his Jewish roots in songs such as \"Jericho\", \"Jarusalema\" and \"Warsaw 1943\".<ref name=Bernarde-2003/>\n\n==Juluka==\nJuluka was an unusual musical partnership for the time in South Africa, with a white man (Clegg) and a black man (Mchunu) performing together. The band, which grew to a six-member group (with three white musicians and three black musicians) by the time it released its first album ''[[Universal Men]]'' in 1979, faced harassment and censorship, with Clegg later remarking that it was \"impossible\" to perform in public in South Africa.<ref name=\"carnival\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1996-07-18/entertainment/1996200008_1_juluka-johnny-clegg-south-africa|title=Clegg leads carnival of creativity|work=The Baltimore Sun|date=18 July 1996|accessdate=2 July 2015|first=Brian|last=Byrnes}}</ref> The group tested the apartheid-era laws, touring and performing in private venues, including universities, churches, hostels, and even private homes in order to attract an audience, as national broadcasters would not play their music.<ref name=\"official\"/>\n\nJust as unusually, the band's music combined Zulu, Celtic, and rock elements, with both [[English language|English]] and [[Zulu language|Zulu]] lyrics.<ref name=\"carnival\"/> Those lyrics often contained coded political messages and references to the battle against apartheid,<ref name=\"Korpe2004\">{{cite book|last=Korpe|first=Marie |title=Shoot the Singer!: Music Censorship Today|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-Yc0xnSfS8EC&pg=PA89|year=2004|publisher=Zed Books|isbn=978-1-84277-505-9|p=89}}</ref> although Clegg maintained that Juluka was not originally intended to be a political band. \"Politics found us,\" he told ''[[The Baltimore Sun]]'' in 1996.<ref name=\"carnival\"/> In a 1989 interview with the ''[[Sunday Times (South Africa)|Sunday Times]]'', Clegg denied the label of \"political activist.\" \"For me a political activist is someone who has committed himself to a particular ideology. I don\u2019t belong to any political party. I stand for human rights.\"<ref>[[Jani Allan|Allan, Jani]]. Vive le Zoulou Blanc! That\u2019s how the French laud Johnny and make him top of their pops. ''Sunday Times'' (South Africa). 3 July 1988</ref>\n\nJuluka's music was both implicitly and explicitly political; not only was the fact of the success of the band (which openly celebrated African culture in a bi-racial band) a thorn in the flesh of a political system based on racial separation, the band also produced some explicitly political songs. For example, the album ''[[Work for All]]'' (which includes a song with the same title) picked up on [[Trade unions in South Africa|South African trade union]] slogans in the mid-1980s.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://host.madison.com/news/opinion/column/john_nichols/john-nichols-the-singer-who-danced-with-mandela-returning-to/article_c6c8e086-6da9-54bc-af9b-dd2712cfbf4d.html|title=The singer who danced with Mandela returning to Madison|date=16 April 2014|accessdate=2 July 2015|work=The Cap Times|first=John|last=Nichols}}</ref> As a result of their political messages and racial integration, Clegg and other band members were arrested several times and concerts routinely broken up.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mg.co.za/article/2010-11-07-white-father-of-african-rock-marks-anniversary |title=White father of African rock marks anniversary|work=Mail & Guardian Online  |date= |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nDespite being ignored and often harassed by the South African government at home, Juluka were able to tour internationally, playing in [[Europe]], [[Canada]], and the [[United States]],<ref name=\"official\"/> and had two [[platinum album|platinum]] and five [[gold album]]s,<ref name=\"carnival\"/> becoming an international success. The group was disbanded in 1985, when Mchunu retired from music and went back to his family farm to return to his people's traditional life of raising cattle.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/jul/16/johnny-clegg-south-african-singer-and-activist-dies-aged-66|title=Johnny Clegg, South African singer and activist, dies aged 66|date=July 16, 2019|accessdate=July 17, 2019|work=The Guardian}}</ref> It was briefly reconstituted when Mchunu and Clegg reunited in the mid-1990s, releasing [[Crocodile Love|one final album]] in 1997 before breaking up for good.<ref name=LeMonde-Jul2019/>\n\n==Savuka==\nTogether with the black musician and dancer [[Dudu Mntowaziwayo Ndlovu|Dudu Zulu]], Clegg went on to form his second inter-racial band, [[Savuka]], in 1986, continuing to blend African music with European influences.<ref name=\"people\"/><ref name=\"sassen\"/><ref name=\"carnival\"/> The group's first album, ''[[Third World Child]]'', broke international sales records in several European countries, including [[France]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.wingate.edu/about-wingate/news/south-africas-johnny-clegg-brings-high-energy-music-to-wingate-university |title=South Africa's Johnny Clegg brings high-energy music to Wingate University |agency=Wingate University |date=17 March 2014 |accessdate=2 July 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150703120739/http://www.wingate.edu/about-wingate/news/south-africas-johnny-clegg-brings-high-energy-music-to-wingate-university |archivedate=3 July 2015 }}</ref> The band went on to record several more albums, including ''[[Heat, Dust and Dreams]]'', which received a [[Grammy Award for Best World Music Album|Grammy Award]] nomination.<ref name=\"appleseed\">{{cite web|url=http://www.appleseedmusic.com/johnnyclegg/|title=Johnny Clegg|publisher=Appleseed Music|accessdate=2 July 2015}}</ref> Johnny Clegg and Savuka played both at home and abroad, even though Clegg's refusal to stop performing in apartheid-era South Africa created tensions with the international anti-apartheid movement. Despite his high-profile (and personally hazardous) opposition to the South African regime, this led to Clegg's expulsion from the [[Musicians' Union (UK)|British Musicians' Union]],<ref name=\"people\"/> in what one writer has since called \"a fit of pique\".<ref name=Cartwright-Jul2019/> In one instance, the band drew such a large crowd in [[Lyon]] that [[Michael Jackson]] cancelled a concert there, complaining that Clegg and his group had \"stole[n] all his fans\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.networkmedien.de/119-0-South-Africa-Cologne-Zulu-Festival-CD.html|title=Cologne Zulu Festival|agency=Works of Music - Network Medien|accessdate=2 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150702220115/http://www.networkmedien.de/119-0-South-Africa-Cologne-Zulu-Festival-CD.html|archive-date=2 July 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> In 1993, the band dissolved after Dudu Zulu was shot and killed while attempting to mediate a [[Taxi wars in South Africa|taxi war]].<ref name=\"sassen\"/><ref name=\"wbur\"/><ref name=\"carnival\"/>\n\n==Juluka reunion and solo career==\n[[File:JohnnyClegg Huma.jpg|thumb|Johnny Clegg at ''la f\u00eate de l'Humanit\u00e9'', France, 2007]]\nBriefly reunited in the mid-1990s, Clegg and Mchunu reformed Juluka, released [[Crocodile Love|a new album]],<ref name=\"appleseed\"/> and toured throughout the world in 1996 with [[King Sunny Ad\u00e9]].<ref name=\"tour\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1996-08-01/entertainment/ca-29967_1_political-situation|title=Band, in Tune With Politics, Back on Tour|date=1 August 1996|accessdate=2 July 2015|work=Los Angeles Times|first=Bill|last=Locey}}</ref> In the following years, Clegg recorded several solo albums.  His touring schedule was abbreviated in 2017 after undergoing surgery for pancreatic cancer, and Clegg performed his last scheduled tour date in Mauritius in October 2018.<ref name=\"official\"/><ref name=\"wbur\"/>\n\nDuring one concert in 1999, he was joined onstage by South African President [[Nelson Mandela]], who danced as Johnny Clegg sang the protest song Savuka had dedicated to him, \"[[Asimbonanga]]\". Asimbonanga became an anthem of protest for the Mass Democratic Movement's umbrella organisation, the [[United Democratic Front (South Africa)|United Democratic Front]]. During Mandela's illness and death in 2013, the video of the concert attracted considerable media attention outside South Africa.<ref name=\"wbur\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2013/06/25/195472719/video-for-nelson-mandela-johnny-cleggs-asimbonanga|title=VIDEO For Nelson Mandela: Johnny Clegg's 'Asimbonanga'|date=25 June 2013|accessdate=2 July 2015|agency=[[National Public Radio]]}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nClegg's song \"Scatterlings of Africa\" gave him his only entries in the [[UK Singles Chart]] to date, reaching No. 44 in February 1983 with Juluka and No. 75 in May 1987 as Johnny Clegg and Savuka. The following year the song was featured on the soundtrack to the 1988 [[Academy Award|Oscar]]-winning film ''[[Rain Man]]''.<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\">{{cite book\n\n| first= David\n| last= Roberts\n| year= 2006\n| title= British Hit Singles & Albums\n| edition= 19th\n| publisher= Guinness World Records Limited \n| location= London\n| isbn= 1-904994-10-5\n| page= 110}}</ref>\n\nHis song \"Life is a Magic Thing\" was featured in ''[[FernGully: The Last Rainforest]]''.<ref name=\"syracuse071719\">{{cite news|url=https://www.syracuse.com/celebrity-news/2019/07/johnny-clegg-dead-south-african-singer-heard-in-george-of-the-jungle-ferngully-was-66.html|agency=syracuse.com|title=Johnny Clegg dead: South African singer heard in 'George of the Jungle,' 'FernGully' was 66|date=July 17, 2019|accessdate=July 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\nSavuka's song \"Dela\" was featured on the soundtrack of the 1997 film ''[[George of the Jungle (film)|George of the Jungle]]'' and its 2003 sequel,<ref name=\"syracuse071719\"/> while \"Great Heart\" was the title song for the 1986 film ''[[Jock of the Bushveld]]''. \"Cruel, Crazy, Beautiful World\" was featured in the 1990 film ''[[Opportunity Knocks (film)|Opportunity Knocks]]'' and 1991 film ''[[Career Opportunities (film)|Career Opportunities]]''.<ref name=\"syracuse071719\"/>\n\n[[Jimmy Buffett]] recorded \"Great Heart\" for his 1988 album, ''[[Hot Water (Jimmy Buffett album)|Hot Water]]''.<ref name=sexton>{{cite news|last=Sexton|first=Paul|url=https://www.udiscovermusic.com/news/johnny-clegg-dies-at-66/|agency=uDiscover Music|title=Johnny Clegg, South African Musical Hero And Anthropologist, Dies At 66|date=July 17, 2019|accessdate=July 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Recognition==\n* 1991: awarded the ''[[Legion d'Honneur|Chevalier des Arts et Lettres]]'' (Knight of Arts and Letters) by the [[Cabinet of France|French Government]].<ref name=\"Benselow\">{{cite web|last=Benselow|first=Robin|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/jul/19/johnny-clegg-obituary |title=Johnny Clegg obituary / Singer-songwriter who used music to defy apartheid in South Africa |work=[[The Guardian]] |date= 19 July 2019 |accessdate=21 July 2019}}</ref>\n* 2004: voted 23rd in the [[SABC3's Great South Africans]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bizcommunity.com/Article/196/423/4673.html|title=The 10 Greatest South Africans of all time|publisher=BizCommunity|date=27 September 2004|accessdate=31 March 2017}}</ref>\n* 2007: received an [[Honorary degree|honorary doctorate]] in music from the [[University of the Witwatersrand]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://web.wits.ac.za/NewsRoom/NewsItems/clegg.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-10-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080601024958/http://web.wits.ac.za/NewsRoom/NewsItems/clegg.htm |archivedate=1 June 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* 2011: received an honorary Doctor of Laws degree from [[City University of New York]] School of Law.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.cuny.edu/mu/law/2011/04/15/human-rights-activist-jonathan-johnny-clegg-recieves-honorary-degree/ |title=Human Rights Activist, Jonathan \"Johnny\" Clegg {{sic|Recieves|nolink=y}} Honorary Degree \u2013 CUNY School of Law |publisher=.cuny.edu |date=15 April 2011 |accessdate=14 July 2014}}</ref>\n* 2012: received the [[Order of Ikhamanga]], Silver as part of the National Orders ceremony. This award is the highest honour a citizen can receive in South Africa. It was presented by President Jacob Zuma.<ref name=\"Benselow\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.news24.com/news24/SouthAfrica/Politics/National-orders-to-be-awarded-20120423 |title=National orders to be awarded &#124; News24 |publisher=M.news24.com |date=24 April 2012 |accessdate=14 July 2014}}</ref>\n* 2012: received an honorary Doctor of Humane Letters degree from [[Dartmouth College]], Hanover, NH, USA.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dartmouth.edu/~commence/news/speeches/2012/clegg.html |title=Dartmouth Commencement 2012 \u2013 Johnny Clegg, Doctor of Humane Letters |publisher=Dartmouth.edu |date=10 June 2012 |accessdate=14 July 2014}}</ref>\n* 2013: received an honorary Doctorate in Music from the [[University of KwaZulu-Natal]], South Africa.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ukzn.ac.za/news//2013/04/17/-cultural-handyman-johnny-clegg-receives-honorary-doctorate |title='Music Legend' Johnny Clegg Receives Honorary Doctorate |publisher=Ukzn.ac.za |date=17 April 2013 |accessdate=14 July 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116084448/http://www.ukzn.ac.za/news//2013/04/17/-cultural-handyman-johnny-clegg-receives-honorary-doctorate |archivedate=16 January 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Honorary awards for their courageous contributions|url=http://www.iol.co.za/dailynews/news/honorary-awards-for-their-courageous-contributions-1.1501617#.VXxO0KFZ6PQ|accessdate=13 June 2015|work=Daily News|publisher=Independent Online|date=17 April 2013}}</ref>\n* 2015: was made an [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]].<ref name=\"sape_John\">{{Cite web | title = Johnny Clegg Receives OBE for Services to South African Democracy  | author =  | work = SAPeople news | date = 27 November 2015 | accessdate = 2015-11-27 | url = http://www.sapeople.com/2015/11/26/johnny-clegg-receives-obe-for-services-to-south-african-democracy/ | quote = }}</ref><ref name=\"gov._HerM\">{{Cite web | title = Her Majesty Queen Elizabeth II Birthday Honours 2015 \u2013 South Africa  | author =  | work = gov.uk | date = 13 June 2015 | accessdate = 2015-12-02 | url = https://www.gov.uk/government/world-location-news/her-majesty-queen-elizabeth-ii-birthday-honours-2015-south-africa | quote =  }}</ref>\n* 2018: received an Honorary Doctorate of Philosophy Degree in Visual and Performing Arts from the [[Durban University of Technology]] alongside his Juluka bandmate, Sipho Mchunu.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dut.ac.za/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/johnny-speech-edited.pdf|title=The Durban University of Technology : 7 September 2018 : Mr Johnny Clegg|website=Dut.ac.za|accessdate=16 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Illness and death==\nJohnny Clegg was diagnosed with pancreatic cancer in 2015,<ref name=Lewis-2017>{{cite web |last=Lewis |first=Randy |date=16 August 2017 |title=South Africa's Johnny Clegg, with cancer in remission, to embark the Final Journey U.S. tour |url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-et-ms-johnny-clegg-cancer-final-journey-us-tour-20170816-story.html |website=Los Angeles Times |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170816205243/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-et-ms-johnny-clegg-cancer-final-journey-us-tour-20170816-story.html |archive-date=16 August 2017 |access-date=14 November 2017}}</ref> which ultimately led to his death on 16 July 2019. He died in his Johannesburg home surrounded by loved ones and was laid to rest the following day in [[Westpark Cemetery]] in Johannesburg.<ref>{{cite web |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=16 July 2019 |title=Legendary artist Johnny Clegg dies at 66 |url= https://www.iol.co.za/news/south-africa/gauteng/legendary-artist-johnny-clegg-dies-at-66-29321787\n|website=Independent Online (IOL) |location=Cape Town |access-date=17 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Remembering a legend: 9 of Johnny Clegg's biggest hits |url=https://www.channel24.co.za/Music/News/remembering-a-legend-9-of-johnny-cleggs-biggest-hits-20190716? |accessdate=16 July 2019 |work=Channel |date=16 July 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Clegg is survived by his wife, Jenny, and his two sons, Jesse and Jaron.\n\n==Academic publications==\n*{{cite journal|last=Clegg|first=Jonathan|year=1981|title=Ukubuyisa Isidumbu \u2013 \"Bringing back the body\": An examination into the ideology of vengeance in the Msinga and Mpofana rural locations(1882\u20131944)|journal=African Studies Seminar Series|publisher=African Studies Institute|location=Johannesburg|hdl=10539/8496}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Clegg|first=Jonathan|year=1981|title=The Music of Zulu Immigrant Workers in Johannesburg: A Focus on Concertina and Guitar|journal=Papers Presented at the Symposium on Ethnomusicology|publisher=[[International Library of African Music]]|location=[[Grahamstown]]|editor-link=Andrew Tracey|editor-first=Andrew |editor-last=Tracey}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Clegg|first=Jonathan|year=1982|title=Towards an understanding of African Dance: The Zulu Isishameni Style|journal=Papers Read at Second Symposium on Ethnomusicology, 24\u201326 September 1981, Rhodes University, Grahamstown, South Africa|publisher=Institute of Social and Economic Research|location=[[Grahamstown]]|editor-link=Andrew Tracey|editor-first=Andrew |editor-last=Tracey}}\n*{{cite conference |last=Clegg |first=Jonathan |date=1984 |title=Examination of the Umzansi dance style |book-title=Papers presented at the Third and Fourth symposia on Ethnomusicology: Music Department, University of Natal, Durban, 16th to 19th September 1982; Music Department, Rhodes University, 7th to 8th October 1983 |publisher=Institute of Social and Economic Research |location=Grahamstown |editor-link=Andrew Tracey |editor-first=Andrew |editor-last=Tracey |oclc=13658380 |isbn=086810096X}}\n\n==Discography==\n{{See also|Juluka#Discography|Savuka#Selected music}}\n\n===Albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center; width:10px;\"|Year\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center; width:320px;\"|Album\n!  style=\"text-align:center; width:20px;\"|Peak positions\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\" | [[SNEP|FRA]]<br><ref name=\"fr\">{{cite web | url=http://lescharts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Johnny+Clegg | title=Johnny Clegg discography | publisher=Hung Medien | work=lescharts.com |accessdate=21 December 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1985\n| ''Third World Child (Johnny Clegg solo album)''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2002\n|''New World Survivor''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2006\n|''[[One Life (Johnny Clegg album)|One Life]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|150\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2010\n|''Human''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|109\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2017\n|''King of Time''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|}\n\n===Live albums===\n* 2003: ''[[A South African Story - Live at the Nelson Mandela Theatre]]''<ref>{{cite web\n| url = https://www.allmusic.com/album/a-south-african-story-live-at-the-nelson-mandela-theatre-mw0001439624\n| title =  Johnny Clegg / A South African Story: Live at the Nelson Mandela Theatre \n| website = [[AllMusic]]\n| accessdate = 21 July 2019\n}}</ref>\n* 2003: ''[[Best of Live (Johnny Clegg)|Best of Live]]''<ref>{{cite web\n| url = https://www.allmusic.com/album/best-of-live-at-the-nelson-mandela-theather-mw0000468276\n| title = Best of Live\n| website = [[AllMusic]]\n| accessdate = 21 July 2019\n}}</ref>\n* 2014: ''[[Best, Live & Unplugged At The Baxter Theatre Cape Town]]''<ref>{{cite web\n| last = Leggett\n| first = Steve\n| url = https://www.allmusic.com/album/best-live-unplugged-at-the-baxter-theatre-cape-town-mw0002636199\n| title = Best, Live & Unplugged: At the Baxter Theatre Cape Town\n| website = [[AllMusic]]\n| accessdate = 21 July 2019\n}}</ref>\n\n===DVD===\n* 2004: ''[[Live! and more...]]''<ref>{{cite book\n| last = Larkin\n| first = Colin\n| url = https://books.google.de/books?id=_NNmFiUnSmUC&pg=PA183\n| title = Clegg, Johnny\n| work = The Encyclopedia of Popular Music\n| publisher = Omnibus Press\n| year = 2011\n| pages = 183\u2013185\n| isbn = 978-0-85-712595-8\n}}</ref>\n<!--* 2006: ''[[Johnny Clegg Live at the Nelson Mandela Theatre]]''{{cn|date=October 2018}} - getting tired, may be 2007 {{cn|date=October 2018}}-->\n* 2010: ''[[Johnny Clegg 30th Anniversary Concert at Emmarentia Dam]]''<ref name=\"fr\" />\n\n===Soundtracks===\n* 1992: ''[[The Power of One (soundtrack)|The Power of One]]''<ref>{{cite web|title=The Power of One (1992)|url=http://www.soundtrackinfo.com/title/powerofone.asp|work=soundtrackinfo.com|publisher=The Soundtrack Info Project|accessdate=15 March 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title= Remembering Johnny Clegg's Powerful Mission / South Africa's best-known musician has dedicated his life to crossing the lines separating white and black|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/johnny-clegg-apartheid-south-africa-860407/|work=rollingstone.com|publisher=RollingStone|accessdate=21 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official}}\n* [http://inmyafricandream.free.fr/ In My African Dream: the Johnny Clegg Discography] inmyafricandream.free.fr\n* Greg Kot: [https://web.archive.org/web/20050913023809/http://www.talkingleaves.com/articles/worlds.html Worlds Apart: Johnny Clegg Has Been / Molded by South Africa] [[Chicago Tribune]] April 29, 1990\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070927191703/http://www.talkingleaves.com/pithouse.html A National Treasure Turns 21] talkingleaves.com October 25, 2000\n* Jeremy Cooper: [https://web.archive.org/web/20070223235202/http://www.chico.mweb.co.za/art/2006/2006dec/061215-zulu.html The return of the white Zulu] chico.mweb.co 15 December 2006\n* {{discogs artist}}\n* {{Find a Grave|201345469}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Clegg, Johnny}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:Jewish South African anti-apartheid activists]]\n[[Category:White South African anti-apartheid activists]]\n[[Category:British emigrants to Rhodesia]]\n[[Category:Rhodesian emigrants to South Africa]]\n[[Category:Capitol Records artists]]\n[[Category:Concertina players]]\n[[Category:Jewish English musicians]]\n[[Category:People from Bacup]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Ikhamanga]]\n[[Category:South African anthropologists]]\n[[Category:South African musicians]]\n[[Category:Secular Jews]]\n[[Category:English emigrants to South Africa]]\n[[Category:South African people of English-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:South African people of Lithuanian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:South African people of Polish-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:South African people of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:South African people of Zimbabwean descent]]\n[[Category:South African pop singers]]\n[[Category:University of the Witwatersrand alumni]]\n[[Category:Juluka members]]\n[[Category:Savuka members]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in South Africa]]\n[[Category:Deaths from pancreatic cancer]]\n[[Category:English people of Polish-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:English people of Lithuanian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:English people of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:English people of Zimbabwean descent]]\n[[Category:Burials at Westpark Cemetery]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|Jonathan Clegg|the British rower|Jono Clegg}}\n{{similar names|John Clegg (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|South African musician and anti-apartheid icon}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name             = Johnny Clegg<br><small>[[Order of the British Empire|OBE]], [[Order of Ikhamanga|OIS]]</small>\n| image            = Johnny-clegg-valenciennes-davidata-14 07 2009.jpg\n| alt = Clegg singing and playing concertina\n| landscape        =\n| caption          = Clegg performing live in 2009\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = Jonathan Paul Clegg\n| alias            = ''Le Zoulou Blanc''\n| birth_date       = {{birth date|df=yes|1953|6|7}}\n| birth_place      = [[Bacup]], Lancashire, England\n| death_date       = {{death date and age|2019|7|16|1953|6|7|df=yes}}\n| death_place      = [[Johannesburg]], [[South Africa]]\n| origin           = \n| instrument       = Vocals, guitar, [[concertina]]\n| genre            = [[Mbaqanga]], [[African popular music|Afro-pop]] <ref>{{cite web |last=Nobanda |first=Chuma |date=16 July 2019 |title=Legendary musician Johnny Clegg has died |url=http://www.sabcnews.com/sabcnews/legendary-musician-johnny-clegg-has-died/ |website=SABC Africa |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190716201007/http://www.sabcnews.com/sabcnews/legendary-musician-johnny-clegg-has-died/ |archive-date=16 July 2019 |access-date=8 October 2019}}</ref>\n| occupation       =  [[Musician]], [[Anthropologist]]\n| years_active     = 1976\u20132018\n| label            = [[Capitol Records]]<ref>{{cite web |title=South Africa's Johnny Clegg, with cancer in remission, to embark the Final Journey U.S. tour |url=https://www.mcall.com/la-et-ms-johnny-clegg-cancer-final-journey-us-tour-20170816-story.html |website=The Morning Call |accessdate=8 October 2019}}</ref>\n| associated_acts  = [[Juluka]], [[Savuka]]\n| website          = [http://www.johnnyclegg.com johnnyclegg.com]\n}}\n\n'''Jonathan Paul Clegg''', [[Order of the British Empire|OBE]], [[Order of Ikhamanga|OIS]] (7 June 1953 \u2013 16 July 2019) was a South African musician and [[anthropologist]], some of whose work was in musicology focused on the music of indigenous South African peoples.<ref name=sexton/> His band [[Juluka]] began as a duo with [[Sipho Mchunu]], and was the first group in the South African [[apartheid]]-era with a white man and a black man. The pair performed and recorded, later with an expanded lineup.\n\nIn 1986 Clegg founded the band [[Savuka]], and also recorded as a solo act, occasionally reuniting with his earlier band partners. Sometimes called ''Le Zoulou Blanc'' ({{IPA-fr|l\u0259 zulu bl\u0251\u0303|lang}}, for \"The White [[Zulu people|Zulu]]\"), he was an important figure in South African popular music and one of the most prominent white activists in [[Internal resistance to apartheid|resistance to apartheid]],<ref name=LeMonde-Jul2019>{{cite web |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=16 July 2019 |title=Mort du chanteur sud-africain Johnny Clegg, \u00ab&nbsp;le Zoulou blanc&nbsp;\u00bb qui combattait l\u2019apartheid |url=https://www.lemonde.fr/disparitions/article/2019/07/16/mort-du-chanteur-sud-africain-johnny-clegg-le-zoulou-blanc-qui-combattait-l-apartheid_5490110_3382.html |website=Le Monde |location=Paris |trans-title=Death of South African singer Johnny Clegg, the \"white Zulu\" who fought apartheid |language=fr |agency=AFP |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190716212749/https://www.lemonde.fr/disparitions/article/2019/07/16/mort-du-chanteur-sud-africain-johnny-clegg-le-zoulou-blanc-qui-combattait-l-apartheid_5490110_3382.html |archive-date=16 July 2019 |access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref> with songs that mixed [[Zulu language|Zulu]] and English lyrics, also combining [[Music of Africa|African music]] with various Western styles.<ref name=Cartwright-Jul2019>{{cite web |last=Cartwright |first=Gareth |date=24 July 2019 |title=Johnny Clegg: South African singer whose cross-cultural music was a direct challenge to apartheid |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/johnny-clegg-death-singer-south-africa-apartheid-nelson-mandela-obituary-a9008716.html |website=The Independent |location=London |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190725142755/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/johnny-clegg-death-singer-south-africa-apartheid-nelson-mandela-obituary-a9008716.html |archive-date=25 July 2019 |access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and career==\nClegg was born on 7 June 1953 in [[Bacup]], [[Lancashire]],<ref name=\"official\">{{cite web|url=http://www.johnnyclegg.com/biog.html|title=JOHNNY CLEGG BIOGRAPHY AND AWARDS|publisher=JohnnyClegg.com|accessdate=2 July 2015}}</ref> to an English father of Scottish descent, Dennis Clegg, and a Rhodesian mother, Muriel (Braudo).<ref>{{cite web |author=<!--Not stated-->|date=22 July 2006 |title=White Zulu is making a comeback |url=https://www.iol.co.za/entertainment/celebrity-news/white-zulu-is-making-a-comeback-940896 |website=Independent Online (IOL) |location=Cape Town |access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=Cowell-Jul2019>{{cite web |last=Cowell |first=Alan |date=16 July 2019 |title=Johnny Clegg, South African Singer Who Battled Apartheid With Music, Is Dead at 66|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/16/arts/music/johnny-clegg-dead.html |website=The New York Times |access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref> Clegg's mother's family were [[Jews|Jewish]] immigrants from [[Lithuania]], and Clegg had a secular Jewish upbringing, learning about the [[Ten Commandments]] but refusing to have a ''[[bar mitzvah]]'' or even associate with other Jewish children at school.<ref name=Bernarde-2003>{{cite book |last=Benarde |first=Scott R. |date=2003 |title=Stars of David: Rock'n'roll's Jewish Stories |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XI4-VnSrEcAC&pg=PA3 |publisher=Brandeis University Press |location=Waltham, MA |pages=3,279\u2013283 |isbn=1584653035 |access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref> His parents divorced when he was still an infant, and he moved with his mother to Rhodesia (now [[Zimbabwe]]) and then, at the age of six, to South Africa,<ref name=\"people\">{{cite web |last1=Freeman |first1=Patricia |last2=McCoy |first2=Melissa |date=24 October 1988 |title=Black and White and Heard All Over, Johnny Clegg and Savuka Cross South Africa's Color Barrier |url=https://people.com/archive/black-and-white-and-heard-all-over-johnny-clegg-and-savuka-cross-south-africas-color-barrier-vol-30-no-17/ |website=People |location=New York |volume=30 |issue=17 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170610105846/https://people.com/archive/black-and-white-and-heard-all-over-johnny-clegg-and-savuka-cross-south-africas-color-barrier-vol-30-no-17/ |archive-date=10 June 2017 |access-date=17 April 2020}}</ref> also spending part of a year in [[Israel]] during his childhood.<ref name=Bernarde-2003/>\n\nAs an adolescent in [[Johannesburg]]'s northern suburbs, he encountered the demi-monde of the city's Zulu migrant workers' music and dance. Under the tutelage of Charlie Mzila, a flat cleaner by day and musician by night, Clegg mastered both the [[Zulu language]] and the [[maskandi]] guitar and the isishameni dance styles of the migrants.<ref name=Wits-2019>{{cite web |date=18 July 2019 |url=https://www.wits.ac.za/news/sources/alumni-news/2019/johnny-clegg-1953-2019.html |title=Johnny Clegg (1953\u20132019) |publisher=University of the Witwatersrand |location=Johannesburg |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190718104727/https://www.wits.ac.za/news/sources/alumni-news/2019/johnny-clegg-1953-2019.html |archive-date=18 July 2019 |access-date=17 April 2020}}</ref> Clegg's involvement with black musicians often led to arrests for trespassing on government property and for contravening the [[Group Areas Act]]. He was first arrested at the age of 15 for violating [[apartheid]]-era laws in South Africa banning people of different races from congregating together after curfew hours.<ref name=\"sassen\">{{cite news|url=http://www.popmatters.com/column/sassen021002/|first=Robyn|last=Sassen|date=16 October 2002|accessdate=2 July 2015|agency=PopMatters|title=Johnny Clegg: A South African Story}}</ref>\n\nAt the age of 17, he met [[Sipho Mchunu]], a Zulu migrant worker with whom he began performing music.<ref name=\"people\"/> The partnership, which they named [[Juluka]], was profiled in the 1970s television documentary ''[[Beats of the Heart: Rhythm of Resistance]]''.<ref name=\"beats\">''Beats of the Heart: Rhythm of Resistance'' (1979), dir. Jeremy Marre</ref>\n\nAfter graduating with a [[BA(Hons)]] in [[Social Anthropology]] from the [[University of Witwatersrand]], Clegg pursued an academic career for four years where he lectured and wrote several seminal scholarly papers on [[Zulu music]] and dance.<ref name=Wits-2019/> In the early stages of his musical career, Clegg combined his music with the study of [[anthropology]]<ref name=\"beats\"/> at Wits, where he was influenced, among others, by the work of [[David Webster (anthropologist)|David Webster]], a [[social anthropology|social anthropologist]] who was later assassinated in 1989.<ref name=\"sassen\" /><ref name=\"wbur\">{{cite news|url=http://hereandnow.wbur.org/2014/04/28/johnny-clegg-music|title=Johnny Clegg On South Africa, Post-Mandela|date=28 April 2014|accessdate=2 July 2015|agency=WBUR}}</ref><ref name=\"latimes\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1993-08-12/entertainment/ca-23042_1_south-africa|title=South Africa's Johnny Clegg: A Witness to History|first=Randy|last=Lewis|date=12 August 1993|accessdate=2 July 2015|work=Los Angeles Times}}</ref>\n\nHe preceded each song with snippets of Zulu culture, information, commentary, humor and personal anecdotes relevant and unique to that song,<ref name=Wits-2019/> occasionally also incorporating aspects of his Jewish roots in songs such as \"Jericho\", \"Jarusalema\" and \"Warsaw 1943\".<ref name=Bernarde-2003/>\n\n==Juluka==\nJuluka was an unusual musical partnership for the time in South Africa, with a white man (Clegg) and a black man (Mchunu) performing together. The band, which grew to a six-member group (with three white musicians and three black musicians) by the time it released its first album ''[[Universal Men]]'' in 1979, faced harassment and censorship, with Clegg later remarking that it was \"impossible\" to perform in public in South Africa.<ref name=\"carnival\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1996-07-18/entertainment/1996200008_1_juluka-johnny-clegg-south-africa|title=Clegg leads carnival of creativity|work=The Baltimore Sun|date=18 July 1996|accessdate=2 July 2015|first=Brian|last=Byrnes}}</ref> The group tested the apartheid-era laws, touring and performing in private venues, including universities, churches, hostels, and even private homes in order to attract an audience, as national broadcasters would not play their music.<ref name=\"official\"/>\n\nJust as unusually, the band's music combined Zulu, Celtic, and rock elements, with both [[English language|English]] and [[Zulu language|Zulu]] lyrics.<ref name=\"carnival\"/> Those lyrics often contained coded political messages and references to the battle against apartheid,<ref name=\"Korpe2004\">{{cite book|last=Korpe|first=Marie |title=Shoot the Singer!: Music Censorship Today|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-Yc0xnSfS8EC&pg=PA89|year=2004|publisher=Zed Books|isbn=978-1-84277-505-9|p=89}}</ref> although Clegg maintained that Juluka was not originally intended to be a political band. \"Politics found us,\" he told ''[[The Baltimore Sun]]'' in 1996.<ref name=\"carnival\"/> In a 1989 interview with the ''[[Sunday Times (South Africa)|Sunday Times]]'', Clegg denied the label of \"political activist.\" \"For me a political activist is someone who has committed himself to a particular ideology. I don\u2019t belong to any political party. I stand for human rights.\"<ref>[[Jani Allan|Allan, Jani]]. Vive le Zoulou Blanc! That\u2019s how the French laud Johnny and make him top of their pops. ''Sunday Times'' (South Africa). 3 July 1988</ref>\n\nJuluka's music was both implicitly and explicitly political; not only was the fact of the success of the band (which openly celebrated African culture in a bi-racial band) a thorn in the flesh of a political system based on racial separation, the band also produced some explicitly political songs. For example, the album ''[[Work for All]]'' (which includes a song with the same title) picked up on [[Trade unions in South Africa|South African trade union]] slogans in the mid-1980s.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://host.madison.com/news/opinion/column/john_nichols/john-nichols-the-singer-who-danced-with-mandela-returning-to/article_c6c8e086-6da9-54bc-af9b-dd2712cfbf4d.html|title=The singer who danced with Mandela returning to Madison|date=16 April 2014|accessdate=2 July 2015|work=The Cap Times|first=John|last=Nichols}}</ref> As a result of their political messages and racial integration, Clegg and other band members were arrested several times and concerts routinely broken up.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mg.co.za/article/2010-11-07-white-father-of-african-rock-marks-anniversary |title=White father of African rock marks anniversary|work=Mail & Guardian Online  |date= |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nDespite being ignored and often harassed by the South African government at home, Juluka were able to tour internationally, playing in [[Europe]], [[Canada]], and the [[United States]],<ref name=\"official\"/> and had two [[platinum album|platinum]] and five [[gold album]]s,<ref name=\"carnival\"/> becoming an international success. The group was disbanded in 1985, when Mchunu retired from music and went back to his family farm to return to his people's traditional life of raising cattle.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/jul/16/johnny-clegg-south-african-singer-and-activist-dies-aged-66|title=Johnny Clegg, South African singer and activist, dies aged 66|date=July 16, 2019|accessdate=July 17, 2019|work=The Guardian}}</ref> It was briefly reconstituted when Mchunu and Clegg reunited in the mid-1990s, releasing [[Crocodile Love|one final album]] in 1997 before breaking up for good.<ref name=LeMonde-Jul2019/>\n\n==Savuka==\nTogether with the black musician and dancer [[Dudu Mntowaziwayo Ndlovu|Dudu Zulu]], Clegg went on to form his second inter-racial band, [[Savuka]], in 1986, continuing to blend African music with European influences.<ref name=\"people\"/><ref name=\"sassen\"/><ref name=\"carnival\"/> The group's first album, ''[[Third World Child]]'', broke international sales records in several European countries, including [[France]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.wingate.edu/about-wingate/news/south-africas-johnny-clegg-brings-high-energy-music-to-wingate-university |title=South Africa's Johnny Clegg brings high-energy music to Wingate University |agency=Wingate University |date=17 March 2014 |accessdate=2 July 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150703120739/http://www.wingate.edu/about-wingate/news/south-africas-johnny-clegg-brings-high-energy-music-to-wingate-university |archivedate=3 July 2015 }}</ref> The band went on to record several more albums, including ''[[Heat, Dust and Dreams]]'', which received a [[Grammy Award for Best World Music Album|Grammy Award]] nomination.<ref name=\"appleseed\">{{cite web|url=http://www.appleseedmusic.com/johnnyclegg/|title=Johnny Clegg|publisher=Appleseed Music|accessdate=2 July 2015}}</ref> Johnny Clegg and Savuka played both at home and abroad, even though Clegg's refusal to stop performing in apartheid-era South Africa created tensions with the international anti-apartheid movement. Despite his high-profile (and personally hazardous) opposition to the South African regime, this led to Clegg's expulsion from the [[Musicians' Union (UK)|British Musicians' Union]],<ref name=\"people\"/> in what one writer has since called \"a fit of pique\".<ref name=Cartwright-Jul2019/> In one instance, the band drew such a large crowd in [[Lyon]] that [[Michael Jackson]] cancelled a concert there, complaining that Clegg and his group had \"stole[n] all his fans\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.networkmedien.de/119-0-South-Africa-Cologne-Zulu-Festival-CD.html|title=Cologne Zulu Festival|agency=Works of Music - Network Medien|accessdate=2 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150702220115/http://www.networkmedien.de/119-0-South-Africa-Cologne-Zulu-Festival-CD.html|archive-date=2 July 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> In 1993, the band dissolved after Dudu Zulu was shot and killed while attempting to mediate a [[Taxi wars in South Africa|taxi war]].<ref name=\"sassen\"/><ref name=\"wbur\"/><ref name=\"carnival\"/>\n\n==Juluka reunion and solo career==\n[[File:JohnnyClegg Huma.jpg|thumb|Johnny Clegg at ''la f\u00eate de l'Humanit\u00e9'', France, 2007]]\nBriefly reunited in the mid-1990s, Clegg and Mchunu reformed Juluka, released [[Crocodile Love|a new album]],<ref name=\"appleseed\"/> and toured throughout the world in 1996 with [[King Sunny Ad\u00e9]].<ref name=\"tour\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1996-08-01/entertainment/ca-29967_1_political-situation|title=Band, in Tune With Politics, Back on Tour|date=1 August 1996|accessdate=2 July 2015|work=Los Angeles Times|first=Bill|last=Locey}}</ref> In the following years, Clegg recorded several solo albums.  His touring schedule was abbreviated in 2017 after undergoing surgery for pancreatic cancer, and Clegg performed his last scheduled tour date in Mauritius in October 2018.<ref name=\"official\"/><ref name=\"wbur\"/>\n\nDuring one concert in 1999, he was joined onstage by South African President [[Nelson Mandela]], who danced as Johnny Clegg sang the protest song Savuka had dedicated to him, \"[[Asimbonanga]]\". Asimbonanga became an anthem of protest for the Mass Democratic Movement's umbrella organisation, the [[United Democratic Front (South Africa)|United Democratic Front]]. During Mandela's illness and death in 2013, the video of the concert attracted considerable media attention outside South Africa.<ref name=\"wbur\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2013/06/25/195472719/video-for-nelson-mandela-johnny-cleggs-asimbonanga|title=VIDEO For Nelson Mandela: Johnny Clegg's 'Asimbonanga'|date=25 June 2013|accessdate=2 July 2015|agency=[[National Public Radio]]}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nClegg's song \"Scatterlings of Africa\" gave him his only entries in the [[UK Singles Chart]] to date, reaching No. 44 in February 1983 with Juluka and No. 75 in May 1987 as Johnny Clegg and Savuka. The following year the song was featured on the soundtrack to the 1988 [[Academy Award|Oscar]]-winning film ''[[Rain Man]]''.<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\">{{cite book\n\n| first= David\n| last= Roberts\n| year= 2006\n| title= British Hit Singles & Albums\n| edition= 19th\n| publisher= Guinness World Records Limited \n| location= London\n| isbn= 1-904994-10-5\n| page= 110}}</ref>\n\nHis song \"Life is a Magic Thing\" was featured in ''[[FernGully: The Last Rainforest]]''.<ref name=\"syracuse071719\">{{cite news|url=https://www.syracuse.com/celebrity-news/2019/07/johnny-clegg-dead-south-african-singer-heard-in-george-of-the-jungle-ferngully-was-66.html|agency=syracuse.com|title=Johnny Clegg dead: South African singer heard in 'George of the Jungle,' 'FernGully' was 66|date=July 17, 2019|accessdate=July 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\nSavuka's song \"Dela\" was featured on the soundtrack of the 1997 film ''[[George of the Jungle (film)|George of the Jungle]]'' and its 2003 sequel,<ref name=\"syracuse071719\"/> while \"Great Heart\" was the title song for the 1986 film ''[[Jock of the Bushveld]]''. \"Cruel, Crazy, Beautiful World\" was featured in the 1990 film ''[[Opportunity Knocks (film)|Opportunity Knocks]]'' and 1991 film ''[[Career Opportunities (film)|Career Opportunities]]''.<ref name=\"syracuse071719\"/>\n\n[[Jimmy Buffett]] recorded \"Great Heart\" for his 1988 album, ''[[Hot Water (Jimmy Buffett album)|Hot Water]]''.<ref name=sexton>{{cite news|last=Sexton|first=Paul|url=https://www.udiscovermusic.com/news/johnny-clegg-dies-at-66/|agency=uDiscover Music|title=Johnny Clegg, South African Musical Hero And Anthropologist, Dies At 66|date=July 17, 2019|accessdate=July 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Recognition==\n* 1991: awarded the ''[[Legion d'Honneur|Chevalier des Arts et Lettres]]'' (Knight of Arts and Letters) by the [[Cabinet of France|French Government]].<ref name=\"Benselow\">{{cite web|last=Benselow|first=Robin|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/jul/19/johnny-clegg-obituary |title=Johnny Clegg obituary / Singer-songwriter who used music to defy apartheid in South Africa |work=[[The Guardian]] |date= 19 July 2019 |accessdate=21 July 2019}}</ref>\n* 2004: voted 23rd in the [[SABC3's Great South Africans]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bizcommunity.com/Article/196/423/4673.html|title=The 10 Greatest South Africans of all time|publisher=BizCommunity|date=27 September 2004|accessdate=31 March 2017}}</ref>\n* 2007: received an [[Honorary degree|honorary doctorate]] in music from the [[University of the Witwatersrand]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://web.wits.ac.za/NewsRoom/NewsItems/clegg.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-10-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080601024958/http://web.wits.ac.za/NewsRoom/NewsItems/clegg.htm |archivedate=1 June 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* 2011: received an honorary Doctor of Laws degree from [[City University of New York]] School of Law.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.cuny.edu/mu/law/2011/04/15/human-rights-activist-jonathan-johnny-clegg-recieves-honorary-degree/ |title=Human Rights Activist, Jonathan \"Johnny\" Clegg {{sic|Recieves|nolink=y}} Honorary Degree \u2013 CUNY School of Law |publisher=.cuny.edu |date=15 April 2011 |accessdate=14 July 2014}}</ref>\n* 2012: received the [[Order of Ikhamanga]], Silver as part of the National Orders ceremony. This award is the highest honour a citizen can receive in South Africa. It was presented by President Jacob Zuma.<ref name=\"Benselow\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.news24.com/news24/SouthAfrica/Politics/National-orders-to-be-awarded-20120423 |title=National orders to be awarded &#124; News24 |publisher=M.news24.com |date=24 April 2012 |accessdate=14 July 2014}}</ref>\n* 2012: received an honorary Doctor of Humane Letters degree from [[Dartmouth College]], Hanover, NH, USA.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dartmouth.edu/~commence/news/speeches/2012/clegg.html |title=Dartmouth Commencement 2012 \u2013 Johnny Clegg, Doctor of Humane Letters |publisher=Dartmouth.edu |date=10 June 2012 |accessdate=14 July 2014}}</ref>\n* 2013: received an honorary Doctorate in Music from the [[University of KwaZulu-Natal]], South Africa.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ukzn.ac.za/news//2013/04/17/-cultural-handyman-johnny-clegg-receives-honorary-doctorate |title='Music Legend' Johnny Clegg Receives Honorary Doctorate |publisher=Ukzn.ac.za |date=17 April 2013 |accessdate=14 July 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116084448/http://www.ukzn.ac.za/news//2013/04/17/-cultural-handyman-johnny-clegg-receives-honorary-doctorate |archivedate=16 January 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Honorary awards for their courageous contributions|url=http://www.iol.co.za/dailynews/news/honorary-awards-for-their-courageous-contributions-1.1501617#.VXxO0KFZ6PQ|accessdate=13 June 2015|work=Daily News|publisher=Independent Online|date=17 April 2013}}</ref>\n* 2015: was made an [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]].<ref name=\"sape_John\">{{Cite web | title = Johnny Clegg Receives OBE for Services to South African Democracy  | author =  | work = SAPeople news | date = 27 November 2015 | accessdate = 2015-11-27 | url = http://www.sapeople.com/2015/11/26/johnny-clegg-receives-obe-for-services-to-south-african-democracy/ | quote = }}</ref><ref name=\"gov._HerM\">{{Cite web | title = Her Majesty Queen Elizabeth II Birthday Honours 2015 \u2013 South Africa  | author =  | work = gov.uk | date = 13 June 2015 | accessdate = 2015-12-02 | url = https://www.gov.uk/government/world-location-news/her-majesty-queen-elizabeth-ii-birthday-honours-2015-south-africa | quote =  }}</ref>\n* 2018: received an Honorary Doctorate of Philosophy Degree in Visual and Performing Arts from the [[Durban University of Technology]] alongside his Juluka bandmate, Sipho Mchunu.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dut.ac.za/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/johnny-speech-edited.pdf|title=The Durban University of Technology : 7 September 2018 : Mr Johnny Clegg|website=Dut.ac.za|accessdate=16 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Illness and death==\nJohnny Clegg was diagnosed with pancreatic cancer in 2015,<ref name=Lewis-2017>{{cite web |last=Lewis |first=Randy |date=16 August 2017 |title=South Africa's Johnny Clegg, with cancer in remission, to embark the Final Journey U.S. tour |url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-et-ms-johnny-clegg-cancer-final-journey-us-tour-20170816-story.html |website=Los Angeles Times |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170816205243/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-et-ms-johnny-clegg-cancer-final-journey-us-tour-20170816-story.html |archive-date=16 August 2017 |access-date=14 November 2017}}</ref> which ultimately led to his death on 16 July 2019. He died in his Johannesburg home surrounded by loved ones and was laid to rest the following day in [[Westpark Cemetery]] in Johannesburg.<ref>{{cite web |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=16 July 2019 |title=Legendary artist Johnny Clegg dies at 66 |url= https://www.iol.co.za/news/south-africa/gauteng/legendary-artist-johnny-clegg-dies-at-66-29321787\n|website=Independent Online (IOL) |location=Cape Town |access-date=17 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Remembering a legend: 9 of Johnny Clegg's biggest hits |url=https://www.channel24.co.za/Music/News/remembering-a-legend-9-of-johnny-cleggs-biggest-hits-20190716? |accessdate=16 July 2019 |work=Channel |date=16 July 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Clegg is survived by his wife, Jenny, and his two sons, Jesse and Jaron.\n\n==Academic publications==\n*{{cite journal|last=Clegg|first=Jonathan|year=1981|title=Ukubuyisa Isidumbu \u2013 \"Bringing back the body\": An examination into the ideology of vengeance in the Msinga and Mpofana rural locations(1882\u20131944)|journal=African Studies Seminar Series|publisher=African Studies Institute|location=Johannesburg|hdl=10539/8496}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Clegg|first=Jonathan|year=1981|title=The Music of Zulu Immigrant Workers in Johannesburg: A Focus on Concertina and Guitar|journal=Papers Presented at the Symposium on Ethnomusicology|publisher=[[International Library of African Music]]|location=[[Grahamstown]]|editor-link=Andrew Tracey|editor-first=Andrew |editor-last=Tracey}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Clegg|first=Jonathan|year=1982|title=Towards an understanding of African Dance: The Zulu Isishameni Style|journal=Papers Read at Second Symposium on Ethnomusicology, 24\u201326 September 1981, Rhodes University, Grahamstown, South Africa|publisher=Institute of Social and Economic Research|location=[[Grahamstown]]|editor-link=Andrew Tracey|editor-first=Andrew |editor-last=Tracey}}\n*{{cite conference |last=Clegg |first=Jonathan |date=1984 |title=Examination of the Umzansi dance style |book-title=Papers presented at the Third and Fourth symposia on Ethnomusicology: Music Department, University of Natal, Durban, 16th to 19th September 1982; Music Department, Rhodes University, 7th to 8th October 1983 |publisher=Institute of Social and Economic Research |location=Grahamstown |editor-link=Andrew Tracey |editor-first=Andrew |editor-last=Tracey |oclc=13658380 |isbn=086810096X}}\n\n==Discography==\n{{See also|Juluka#Discography|Savuka#Selected music}}\n\n===Albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center; width:10px;\"|Year\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center; width:320px;\"|Album\n!  style=\"text-align:center; width:20px;\"|Peak positions\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\" | [[SNEP|FRA]]<br><ref name=\"fr\">{{cite web | url=http://lescharts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Johnny+Clegg | title=Johnny Clegg discography | publisher=Hung Medien | work=lescharts.com |accessdate=21 December 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1985\n| ''Third World Child (Johnny Clegg solo album)''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2002\n|''New World Survivor''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2006\n|''[[One Life (Johnny Clegg album)|One Life]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|150\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2010\n|''Human''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|109\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2017\n|''King of Time''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|}\n\n===Live albums===\n* 2003: ''[[A South African Story - Live at the Nelson Mandela Theatre]]''<ref>{{cite web\n| url = https://www.allmusic.com/album/a-south-african-story-live-at-the-nelson-mandela-theatre-mw0001439624\n| title =  Johnny Clegg / A South African Story: Live at the Nelson Mandela Theatre \n| website = [[AllMusic]]\n| accessdate = 21 July 2019\n}}</ref>\n* 2003: ''[[Best of Live (Johnny Clegg)|Best of Live]]''<ref>{{cite web\n| url = https://www.allmusic.com/album/best-of-live-at-the-nelson-mandela-theather-mw0000468276\n| title = Best of Live\n| website = [[AllMusic]]\n| accessdate = 21 July 2019\n}}</ref>\n* 2014: ''[[Best, Live & Unplugged At The Baxter Theatre Cape Town]]''<ref>{{cite web\n| last = Leggett\n| first = Steve\n| url = https://www.allmusic.com/album/best-live-unplugged-at-the-baxter-theatre-cape-town-mw0002636199\n| title = Best, Live & Unplugged: At the Baxter Theatre Cape Town\n| website = [[AllMusic]]\n| accessdate = 21 July 2019\n}}</ref>\n\n===DVD===\n* 2004: ''[[Live! and more...]]''<ref>{{cite book\n| last = Larkin\n| first = Colin\n| url = https://books.google.de/books?id=_NNmFiUnSmUC&pg=PA183\n| title = Clegg, Johnny\n| work = The Encyclopedia of Popular Music\n| publisher = Omnibus Press\n| year = 2011\n| pages = 183\u2013185\n| isbn = 978-0-85-712595-8\n}}</ref>\n<!--* 2006: ''[[Johnny Clegg Live at the Nelson Mandela Theatre]]''{{cn|date=October 2018}} - getting tired, may be 2007 {{cn|date=October 2018}}-->\n* 2010: ''[[Johnny Clegg 30th Anniversary Concert at Emmarentia Dam]]''<ref name=\"fr\" />\n\n===Soundtracks===\n* 1992: ''[[The Power of One (soundtrack)|The Power of One]]''<ref>{{cite web|title=The Power of One (1992)|url=http://www.soundtrackinfo.com/title/powerofone.asp|work=soundtrackinfo.com|publisher=The Soundtrack Info Project|accessdate=15 March 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title= Remembering Johnny Clegg's Powerful Mission / South Africa's best-known musician has dedicated his life to crossing the lines separating white and black|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/johnny-clegg-apartheid-south-africa-860407/|work=rollingstone.com|publisher=RollingStone|accessdate=21 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official}}\n* [http://inmyafricandream.free.fr/ In My African Dream: the Johnny Clegg Discography] inmyafricandream.free.fr\n* Greg Kot: [https://web.archive.org/web/20050913023809/http://www.talkingleaves.com/articles/worlds.html Worlds Apart: Johnny Clegg Has Been / Molded by South Africa] [[Chicago Tribune]] April 29, 1990\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070927191703/http://www.talkingleaves.com/pithouse.html A National Treasure Turns 21] talkingleaves.com October 25, 2000\n* Jeremy Cooper: [https://web.archive.org/web/20070223235202/http://www.chico.mweb.co.za/art/2006/2006dec/061215-zulu.html The return of the white Zulu] chico.mweb.co 15 December 2006\n* {{discogs artist}}\n* {{Find a Grave|201345469}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Clegg, Johnny}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:Jewish South African anti-apartheid activists]]\n[[Category:White South African anti-apartheid activists]]\n[[Category:British emigrants to Rhodesia]]\n[[Category:Rhodesian emigrants to South Africa]]\n[[Category:Capitol Records artists]]\n[[Category:Concertina players]]\n[[Category:Jewish English musicians]]\n[[Category:People from Bacup]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Ikhamanga]]\n[[Category:South African anthropologists]]\n[[Category:South African musicians]]\n[[Category:Secular Jews]]\n[[Category:English emigrants to South Africa]]\n[[Category:South African people of English-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:South African people of Lithuanian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:South African people of Polish-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:South African people of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:South African people of Zimbabwean descent]]\n[[Category:South African pop singers]]\n[[Category:University of the Witwatersrand alumni]]\n[[Category:Juluka members]]\n[[Category:Savuka members]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in South Africa]]\n[[Category:Deaths from pancreatic cancer]]\n[[Category:English people of Polish-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:English people of Lithuanian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:English people of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:English people of Zimbabwean descent]]\n[[Category:Burials at Westpark Cemetery]]\n", "name_user": "Edwin of Northumbria", "label": "safe", "comment": "Expanded ref.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Johnny_Clegg"}
{"title_page": "Kippah", "text_new": "{{short description|Skullcap traditionally worn by Jewish men to cover the head}}\n[[File:PikiWiki Israel 38772 Vacation Experience.JPG|thumb|300px|Crocheted kippot for sale in [[Jerusalem]]]]\nA '''kippah''' ({{IPAc-en|k|\u026a|\u02c8|p|\u0251\u02d0}} {{respell|kih|PAH|'}}; also spelled as '''kippa''', '''kipa''', '''kipah'''; {{lang-he-n|\u05db\u05b4\u05bc\u05d9\u05e4\u05b8\u05bc\u05d4}}, plural: {{Hebrew|\u05db\u05b4\u05bc\u05d9\u05e4\u05bc\u05d5\u05b9\u05ea}} ''kippot''; {{lang-yi|\u05e7\u05d0\u05e4\u05dc}} ''koppel''), or {{nowrap|'''yarmulke''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|j|\u0251r|m|\u0259l|k|\u0259}},}} {{Audio|En-us-yarmulke.ogg|pronunciation|help=no}} {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|j|\u0251\u02d0|m|\u0259|k|\u0259}}, {{lang-yi|\u05d9\u05d0\u05b7\u05e8\u05de\u05d5\u05dc\u05e7\u05e2}}), is a brimless [[cap]], usually made of cloth, traditionally worn by [[Jew]]ish males to fulfill the customary requirement that the head be covered. It is worn by men in [[Orthodox Judaism|Orthodox]] communities at all times. Among non-Orthodox communities most people who wear them customarily do so only during prayer, while attending a [[synagogue]] or in other rituals. Most [[synagogue]]s and Jewish funeral services keep a ready supply of ''kippot''.\n\n== Etymology ==\nThe term ''kippah'' ({{lang-he-n|\u05db\u05d9\u05e4\u05d4}}) literally means \"dome\", as the kippah is worn on the head like a dome. \nThe [[Yiddish]] term ''yarmulke'' might be derived from Polish ''jarmu\u0142ka'',<ref>[http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=yarmulke Etymonline.com]</ref> although it is often associated with an [[Aramaic language|Aramaic]] phrase (\u05d9\u05e8\u05d0 \u05de\u05dc\u05db\u05d0) meaning \"fear the King\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Gwynne|first=Paul|title=World Religions in Practice: A Comparative Introduction|edition=2|year=2017|publisher=John Wiley & Sons |page=|ISBN=9781118972274}}</ref> Another suggested etymology of ''yarmulke'' is the Latin word for an ecclesiastical hood worn in the medieval church.<ref>Gold, David L. 1987. The Etymology of the English Noun ''yarmlke'' \u2018Jewish skullcap\u2019 and the Obsolescent Hebrew Noun ''yarmulka'' \u2018idem\u2019 (With An Addendum on Judezmo Words for \u2018Jewish Skullcap\u2019). ''Jewish Language Review'' 7:180-99; Plaut, Gunther. 1955. The Origin of the Word \"Yarmulke.\" ''Hebrew Union College Annual'' 26:567-70.</ref>{{Specify|reason=which word?|date=May 2019}}\n\n''Keppel'' or ''koppel'' is another Yiddish term for the same thing.<ref>http://www.jewish-languages.org/jewish-english-lexicon/words/1534</ref>\n\n== Jewish law ==\n\nThere is debate among [[halakha|Halachic]] authorities as to whether wearing a kippah at all times is required.<ref name=\"Wearing a Kippa\">{{cite web|title=Wearing a Kippa|url=http://www.dailyhalacha.com/displayRead.asp?readID=997&txtSearch=kippot|work=Daily Halacha|publisher=Rabbi Eli Mansour|accessdate=8 December 2011}}</ref> According to the [[Maimonides|Rambam]], Jewish law dictates that a man is required to cover his head during prayer.<ref>[[Mishneh Torah]], ''Ahavah'', ''Hilkhot Tefilah'' 5:5.</ref>\n\nHowever, according to some authorities, it has since taken on the force of law because it is an act of [[Kiddush Hashem]] (lit., \"sanctification of [[Names of God in Judaism|the Name]]\", referring to actions which bring honor to God).<ref>[[Shulchan Arukh]], Orach Chayim 2:6.</ref> The 17th-century authority Rabbi [[David HaLevi Segal]] (The \"Taz\") suggested that the reason was to distinguish Jews from their non-Jewish counterparts, especially while at prayer. He held that nowadays, wearing a kippah is required by [[Halakha|halacha]].<ref name=\"Wearing a Kippa\"/>\n\nOther halachic authorities like Sephardi posek, the [[Chaim Joseph David Azulai|Chida]] (Rabbi Chaim David Yosef Azulai), hold that wearing a head covering is a ''midat hasidut'', an additional measure of piety.<ref name=\"Wearing a Kippa\"/> In a recent responsum, former Sephardic Chief Rabbi of Israel [[Ovadia Yosef]] ruled that it should be worn to show affiliation with the religiously observant community.<ref>{{cite book|last=Yosef|first=Chief Rabbi Ovadia|title=Responsa Yechavei Da'ath}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Talmud]] states, \"Cover your head in order that the fear of heaven may be upon you.\"<ref>[[Shabbat (Talmud)|Shabbat]] 156b.</ref> Rabbi Hunah ben Joshua never walked 4 [[cubits]] (6.6 feet, or 2 meters) with his head uncovered. He explained: \"Because the [[Shekhinah|Divine Presence]] is always over my head.\"<ref>[[Nashim|Kiddushin]] 31a.</ref> This was understood by Rabbi Yosef Karo in the [[Shulchan Arukh]] as indicating that Jewish men should cover their heads, and should not walk more than four cubits bareheaded.<ref>Shulchan Aruch, Orach Chaim, 2:6.</ref> Covering one's head, such as by wearing a kippah, is described as \"honoring God\".<ref>''Shaar HaTzion'', OC 2:6.</ref> The ''[[Mishnah Berurah]]'' modifies this ruling, adding that the ''[[Achronim]]'' established a requirement to wear a head covering even when traversing fewer than four cubits,<ref>Be'er Heitev, Orach Chaim 2:6, note 4, who quotes the ''[[Yoel Sirkis|Bach]]'', ''[[David HaLevi Segal|Taz]]'', and the ''[[Magen Avraham]]''.</ref> and even when one is standing still, indoors and outside.<ref>Mishnah Berurah 2:6, note 9, 10</ref> ''[[Kitzur Shulchan Aruch (book)|Kitzur Shulchan Aruch]]'' cites a story from the Talmud (Shabbat 156b) about [[Rav Nachman bar Yitzchak]], who might have become a thief had his mother not saved him from this fate by insisting that he cover his head, which instilled in him the fear of God.<ref name=autogenerated1>KSA 3:6</ref> In Orthodox communities, boys are encouraged to wear a ''kippah'' from a young age in order to ingrain the habit.<ref>Be'er Heitev, OC 2:6, note 5</ref>\n[[File:IDF soldier kippah put on tefillin-small.jpg|thumb|right|200px|[[Israel Defense Forces|IDF]] soldier prays with kippah and [[tefillin]].]]\nThe Talmud also implies that unmarried men did not wear a kippah:\n:Rabbi Hisda praised Rabbi Hamnuna before Rabbi Huna as a great man. He said to him, 'When he visits you, bring him to me.' When he arrived, he saw that he wore no head-covering. 'Why do you not have head-covering?', he asked. 'Because I am not married', was the reply. Thereupon, he [Rabbi Huna] turned his face away from him, and said, 'See to it that you do not appear before me again before you are married.'<ref>Tractate Kiddushin 29b</ref>\n\nThe Tanakh implies that covering one's head is a sign of mourning:\n{{quote|And [[David]] went up the ascent of the Mount of Olives, and wept as he went, and his head was covered and he walked barefoot. Then all the people who were with him each covered his head and went up weeping as they went.|{{tanakhverse|2 Samuel|15:30}}}}\n{{quote|[Judah mourns,] and their nobles send their lads for water: they come to the pits, and find no water; their vessels return empty; they are ashamed and confounded, and cover their heads. Because of the ground which is cracked, for there hath been no rain in the land, the plowmen are ashamed, they cover their heads.|{{tanakhverse|Jeremiah|14:3\u20134}}}}The argument for the kippa has two sides. The [[Vilna Gaon]] said one can make a ''[[berakhah]]'' without a kippah, since wearing a kippah is only an ''midos chassidus'' (\"exemplary attribute\"). Recently, there has been an effort to suppress earlier sources that practiced this leniency, including erasing lenient [[responsa]] from newly published books.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Yarmulke: A historic cover up?|journal=Flatbush Journal of Jewish Law|url=http://www.hakirah.org/Vol%204%20Rabinowitz.pdf}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Rabbi [[Isaac Klein]], a Conservative Jew ought to cover his head when in the synagogue, at prayer or sacred study, when engaging in a ritual act, and when eating.<ref>Klein, Isaac. ''A Guide to Jewish Religious Practice'', New York: Jewish Theological Seminary of America, 1979.</ref> In the mid-19th century, Reformers led by [[Isaac Mayer Wise|Isaac Wise]] completely rejected the ''kippot'' after an altercation in which Rabbi Wise's kippah was knocked off his head.<ref>Scharfman, Rabbi Harold (1988). ''The First Rabbi''. Pangloss Press.</ref>\n\nThere is still debate about whether wearing a Kippah is Halachic law or simply a custom. Many Sephardic Jews wear a kippah only when praying and eating.{{citation needed|date=September 2014}}\n\n== Types and variation ==\n[[File:Jewish Chaplain Iraq.jpg|thumb|Rabbinical chaplain [[Sarah Schechter]] with fellow U.S. Airmen wearing [[camouflage]] kippot.]]\nIn the [[Middle Ages]] in Europe, the distinctive Jewish headgear was the [[Jewish hat]], a full hat with a brim and a central point or stalk.  Originally used by choice among Jews to distinguish themselves, it was later made compulsory in some places by Christian governments as a discriminatory measure. In the early 19th century in the United States, rabbis often wore a scholar's cap (large saucer-shaped caps of cloth, like a beret) or a Chinese skullcap. Other Jews of this era wore black pillbox-shaped ''kippot''.\n\nOften, the color and fabric of the ''kippah'' can be a sign of adherence to a specific religious movement, particularly in Israel. [[Knit]]ted or [[crochet]]ed ''kippot'', known as ''kippot serugot'', are usually worn by [[Religious Zionist movement|Religious Zionists]] and the [[Modern Orthodox Judaism|Modern Orthodox]],<ref>Boyarin, Jonathan. [https://books.google.com/books?id=Ng2PCUQQ4lwC&pg=PA51&dq=kippah+sruga&cd=3#v=onepage&q=kippah%20sruga&f=false ''Thinking in Jewish''], University of Chicago Press, 1996, p. 51. {{ISBN|0-226-06927-3}}.</ref> who also wear suede or leather ''kippot''. Members of most [[Haredi Judaism|Haredi]] groups wear black velvet or cloth ''kippot''.\n\nMore recently, ''kippot'' have been observed made in the colors of sports teams, especially [[football]]. In the United States, children's ''kippot'' with cartoon characters or themes such as ''[[Star Wars]]'' are popular. (In response to this trend, some Jewish schools have banned ''kippot'' with characters that do not conform to traditional Jewish values.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1990/09/23/style/lifestyle-the-yarmulke-is-now-a-fashion-item.html Lifestyle; \"The Yarmulke Is Now a Fashion Item\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', 23 Sept 1990</ref>) ''Kippot'' have been inscribed on the inside as a souvenir for a celebration (''bar/bat mitzvah'' or wedding). ''Kippot'' for women are also being made and worn.<ref name=\"GU\">{{cite news|url=http://www.jewishindependent.ca/archives/July06/archives06July07-06.html|title=A guide to Jewish head-coverings: Kippot no longer only come in one style, but a medley of colors, shapes and designs|first1=Wendy|last1=Elliman|date=July 7, 2006|work=Jewish Independent|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120309024448/http://www.jewishindependent.ca/archives/July06/archives06July07-06.html|archivedate=March 9, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"MAZ\">[http://www.mazorguide.com/Living/JewishAttire/home.htm Living Jewish \u2013 Jewish Attire!], Mazor Guide. Retrieved December 19, 2010.</ref><ref>[https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/jpost/access/1011733051.html?dids=1011733051:1011733051&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&date=Jul+10%2C+2005&author=AVI+BASS&pub=Jerusalem+Post&desc=California+firm+offers+kippot+for+women&pqatl=google \"California firm offers kippot for women\"], ''[[The Jerusalem Post]]'', July 10, 2005</ref> These are sometimes made of beaded wire to seem more feminine.<ref>[https://www.myjewishlearning.com/article/ask-the-expert-why-dont-women-wear-kippot/ \"Ask the Expert: Can Women Wear Kippot?\" \u2018\u2019My Jewish Learning\u2019\u2019]</ref> A special baby kippah has two strings on each side to fasten it and is often used in a ''[[brit milah]]'' ceremony.<ref name=\"JW\">[http://www.jweekly.com/article/full/22990/from-baby-kippah-to-tylenol-bris-kit-has-everything-but-the-implement/ \"From baby kippah to Tylenol, Bris Kit has everything but the implement\"], ''[[j.|J Weekly]]'', 18 Jun 2004</ref>\n\n[[Samaritan]]s once wore distinctive blue head coverings to separate them from Jews who wore white ones, but today, they more commonly wear ''[[Fez (hat)|fezes]]'' with turbans similar to that of [[Sephardi Jews]] from the Middle East and North Africa. Today, Samaritans do not usually wear head coverings, except during prayer, Sabbath, and religious festivals.{{citation needed|date=October 2012}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Image\n!Type\n!Movement\n|-\n| [[Image:Kippa.jpg|100px]]\n| Crocheted\n| [[Religious Zionism]], Modern Orthodox, Conservative Judaism, Reform Judaism\n|-\n| [[File:Kippa judentum.JPG|100px]]\n| [[Suede]]\n| Modern Orthodox,<ref name=\"MAZ\"/>  Conservative Judaism,<ref name=\"myjewishlearning\">{{cite web|url=http://www.myjewishlearning.com/practices/Ritual/Prayer/Ritual_Garb/Kippah.shtml |title=Kippah |publisher=My Jewish Learning |date=2014-01-31 |accessdate=2017-04-22}}</ref> Reform Judaism<ref name=\"myjewishlearning\"/>\n|-\n| \n| [[Polyethylene terephthalate|Terylene]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.milechai.com/kippot/how-to-buy-a-kippah/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-02-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140301185150/http://www.milechai.com/kippot/how-to-buy-a-kippah/ |archivedate=2014-03-01 }}</ref>\n| [[Yeshivish]], [[Hasidic Judaism|Hasidic]], Haredi, [[Lubavitch]] \u2013 Popular among Rabbis teaching in yeshivas and seminaries\n|-\n| [[File:Black Kippah.jpg|100px]]\n| Black [[velvet]]\n| Yeshivish, Hasidic, Haredi<ref name=\"JPK\">[http://fr.jpost.com/servlet/Satellite?cid=1139395368958&pagename=JPost/JPArticle/ShowFull Barring violence]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, [[The Jerusalem Post]], Yigal Grayeff, February 9, 2006</ref>\n|-\n| [[File:Casamento judeu1.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Satin]]\n| Conservative Judaism, Reform Judaism\n|-\n| [[Image:Na-nach-nachma-yarmulke.jpg|100px]]\n| White crocheted\n| Many [[Jerusalemite]]s wear a full-head-sized, white crocheted ''kippah'', sometimes with a knit pom-pom or tassel on top. The [[Na Nach]] subgroup of the [[Breslov (Hasidic dynasty)|Breslov]] [[Hasidim]], followers of the late Rabbi [[Yisroel Ber Odesser]], wear it with the ''[[Na Nach Nachma Nachman Meuman]]'' phrase crocheted in or embroidered on it.<ref>[http://www.haaretz.co.il/hasen/spages/766226.html On New Year, thousands flock to Rabbi Nachman's grave in Ukraine]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, [[HaAretz]], Yair Ettinger</ref>\n|-\n| [[File:Bukharan kippah.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Bukharan Jews|Bukharan]]<ref name=\"B\">[https://archive.today/20130104135202/http://www.record-eagle.com/features/local_story_103094128.html?keyword=topstory Hats Off To Fashion: Yarmulkes go beyond basic black], [[Traverse City Record-Eagle]], [[Associated Press]], April 13, 2008</ref>\n| Popular with children,<ref name=\"GU\"/><ref name=\"B\"/> and also worn by some Sephardi Jews, as well as liberal-leaning, feminist, and Reform Jews.<ref name=\"FOR\">[http://www.forward.com/articles/4778/ Kippah Couture], [[The Forward]], Angela Himsel, September 29, 2006</ref>\n|-\n| [[File:Yemenite kippah.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Yemenite Jews|Yemenite]]\n| Typically stiff, black velvet with a 1\u20132&nbsp;cm. embroidered strip around the edge having a multi-colored geometric, floral, or [[Paisley (design)|paisley]] pattern.\n|}\n\n== Head coverings in ancient Israelite culture ==\n{{original research|date=November 2017}}\nThe [[Israelites]] on [[Sennacherib]]'s marble relief appear with headdress, and although the ambassadors of [[Jehu]] on the [[Black Obelisk of Shalmaneser III|Shalmaneser stele]] have head coverings, their costume seems to be Israelite. One passage of the older literature is of significance: I Kings 20:31 mentions \u05d7\u05b2\u05d1\u05b8\u05dc\u05d9\u05b4\u05dd ''havalim'',  which are placed around the head. This calls to mind pictures of [[Demographics of Syria|Syrians]] on [[Egypt]]ian monuments, represented wearing a cord around their long, flowing hair, a custom still followed in [[Arabia]].\n\nEvidently the costume of the poorest classes is represented; but as the cord gave no protection against the heat of the sun, there is little probability that the custom lasted very long. Much more common was the simple cloth skullcap, dating back to Egyptian times when those of high society routinely shaved their heads, to prevent lice. Conversely, their skullcaps also served as protection against irritation from their wigs.\n\nThe Israelites might have worn a headdress similar to that worn by the [[Bedouins]], but it is unknown whether a fixed type of headdress was utilized. That the headdress of the Israelites might have been in the fellah style may be inferred from the use of the noun \u05e6\u05b7\u05e0\u05b4\u05d9\u05e3 ''tzanif'' (the verb ''tzanaf'' meaning \"to roll like a ball\", Isaiah 22:18) and by the verb \u05d7\u05b7\u05d1\u05b8\u05bc\u05e9 ''habash'' (\"to wind\", comp. Ezekiel 16:10; Jonah 2:6). As to the form of such turbans, nothing is known, and they may have varied according to the different classes of society. This was customary with the Assyrians and Babylonians, for example, whose fashions likely influenced the costume of the Israelites\u2014particularly during and after the [[Babylonian captivity|Babylonian Exile]].<ref>[http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/view.jsp?artid=465&letter=H&search=Head-Dress \"Head-dress\"], ''Jewish Encyclopedia''</ref> In Yemen, the wrap around the cap was called \u05de\u05b7\u05e6\u05b7\u05e8 ''matzar''; the head covering worn by women was a \u05d2\u05b7\u05bc\u05e8\u05d2\u05d5\u05bc\u05e9 ''[[gargush]]''.<ref>[http://www.chayas.com/garb.htm \"Clothing of the Yemenite Jews\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060220174330/http://www.chayas.com/garb.htm |date=2006-02-20 }}, Chayas.com</ref>\n\n== Civil legal issues ==\n\nIn ''[[Goldman v. Weinberger]]'', 475 U.S. 503 (1986), the [[United States Supreme Court]] ruled in a 5\u20134 decision that active military members were required to remove the yarmulke indoors, citing uniform regulations that state only armed security police may keep their heads covered while indoors.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.oyez.org/cases/1980-1989/1985/1985_84_1097|title=Goldman v. Weinberger|website=[[Oyez Project|www.oyez.org]]|publisher=[[Chicago-Kent College of Law|IIT Chicago-Kent College of Law]]}}</ref>\n\nCongress passed the Religious Apparel Amendment after a war story from the [[1983 Beirut barracks bombing]] about the \"camouflage kippah\" of Jewish Navy Chaplain [[Arnold Resnicoff]] was read into the ''Congressional Record''.<ref>''Congressional Record'', 100th Congress, 11 May 1987.</ref> Catholic Chaplain George Pucciarelli tore off a piece of his [[United States Marine Corps|Marine Corps]] uniform to replace Resnicoff's ''kippah'' when it had become blood-soaked after being used to wipe the faces of wounded Marines after the 1983 Beirut barracks bombing.<ref>\"Solarz Passes Religious Apparel Amendment\", ''The Jewish Press'', 22 May 1987.</ref> This amendment was eventually incorporated into U.S. Department of Defense (DOD) regulations on the \"Accommodation of Religious Practices Within the Military Services\".<ref>[http://www.dtic.mil/whs/directives/corres/pdf/130017p.pdf \"Accommodation of Religious Practices Within the Military Services\"], Department of Defense Instruction</ref>\n[[File:Lea Rabin-Clinton.jpg|thumb|U.S. President [[Bill Clinton]] wearing a kippah to visit the grave of [[Yitzhak Rabin]] on [[Mount Herzl]].]]\nThis story of the \"camouflage kippah\" was re-told at many levels,<ref>Bonko, Larry. \"Rabbi's Camouflage Yarmulke Woven With Tragedy, Heroism\", ''Norfolk Ledger-Star'', 13 January 1984.</ref> including a keynote speech by President [[Ronald Reagan]] to the Baptist Fundamentalism Annual Convention in 1984,<ref>{{cite web |title=Remarks at the Baptist Fundamentalism Annual Convention |date=13 April 1984|accessdate=20 April 2013 |url=http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/ws/index.php?pid=39775#axzz1Nry3hQkr|publisher=The American Presidency Project}}</ref> and another time during a [[White House]] meeting between Reagan and the American Friends of Lubavitch.<ref name=\"top\">{{cite news|title=Rabbis Explain 'Top to Top'|work=Wellsprings|issue=No. 12 (Vol 2, No. 7)|date=August\u2013September 1986|publisher=Lubavitch Youth Organization}}</ref> After recounting the Beirut story, Reagan asked them about the religious meaning of the kippah.<ref name=\"top\"/>  Rabbi [[Abraham Shemtov]], the leader of the group, responded: \"Mr. President, the kippah to us is a sign of reverence.\" Rabbi Feller, another member of the group, continued: \"We place the kippah on the very highest point of our being\u2014on our head, the vessel of our intellect\u2014to tell ourselves and the world that there is something which is above man's intellect: the infinite Wisdom of God.\"<ref name=\"top\"/>\n\nPassage of the Religious Apparel Amendment and the subsequent DOD regulations were followed in 1997 by the passing of the [[Religious Freedom Restoration Act]] (RFRA). However, the Supreme Court struck down RFRA as beyond Congress' powers to bind the states in the 1997 case ''[[City of Boerne v. Flores]]''. RFRA is constitutional as applied to the Federal government, as seen in ''[[Gonzales v. O Centro Espirita Beneficente Uniao do Vegetal]]''.\n\nThe [[Religious Land Use and Institutionalized Persons Act]] of 2000 (RLUIPA), 114 Stat. 804, 42 U. S. C. \u00a72000cc-1(a)(1)-(2), upheld as constitutional in ''[[Cutter v. Wilkinson]]'', 44 U.S. 709 (2005), requires by inference that Orthodox Jewish prisoners be reasonably accommodated in their request to wear yarmulkas.<ref>[http://openjurist.org/391/f3d/1299/benning-v-georgia ''Benning v. Georgia''], 391 F3d 1299</ref>\n\nThe French government [[French law on secularity and conspicuous religious symbols in schools|banned the wearing]] of ''kippot'', ''[[hijab]]s'', and large [[Christian cross|crosses]] in public primary and secondary schools in France in March 2004.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/3531151.stm French Senate backs headscarf ban], [[BBC News]], 3 March 2004.</ref>\n\nThe provincial government of [[Quebec]], Canada passed \"An Act respecting the laicity of the State\"  in June 2019, which prohibits the wearing of \"religious symbols\" by government employees including teachers, police officers, judges, prosecutors, and members of certain commissions.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/quebec-government-adopts-controversial-religious-symbols-bill-1.5177587 |title=Quebec government adopts controversial religious symbols bill |publisher=[[CBC News]] |date=16 June 2019 |access-date=18 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Wearing by non-Jews==\nThough it is not required, when a non-Jew wears a kippah in a synagogue, it is considered a sign of respect.<ref>{{cite book |first=Bradley Shavit |last=Artson|authorlink=Bradley Shavit Artson|title=Jewish Answers to Real-Life Questions |year=1998 |publisher=[[Torah Aura Productions]]|page=23|isbn=9781881283294|url=https://books.google.co.ug/books?id=WnYaLZ7ngWYC}}</ref> Yarmulkes are often provided to guests at a [[Bar or Bat Mitzvah]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Marjabelle Young |first=Stewart |title=The New Etiquette |year=1997 |publisher=Macmillan |page=21}}</ref> They are also often provided at [[Bereavement in Judaism|bereavement]] events and at [[Jewish cemetery|Jewish cemeteries]].  According to the Conservative [[Committee on Jewish Law and Standards]], there is no [[halakhic]] reason to require a non-Jew to cover their head, but it is recommended that non-Jews be asked to wear a kippah where ritual or worship is being conducted, both out of respect for the Jewish congregation and as a gesture of respectfully including the non-Jewish guest.<ref>{{cite journal |first=Jay M. |last=Stein |title=Non Jews and Kippah in the Synagogue |year=2009 |url=https://www.rabbinicalassembly.org/sites/default/files/public/halakhah/teshuvot/20052010/Kippah%20JaySteinfinal.pdf |publisher=[[Committee on Jewish Law and Standards]]}}</ref>\n\nKippahs were adopted as a symbol by some of the non-Jewish African American marchers in the 1965 [[Selma to Montgomery marches]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.jta.org/1965/03/23/archive/negro-marchers-from-selma-wear-yarmulkes-in-deference-to-rabbis|title=Negro Marchers from Selma Wear \u2018Yarmulkes\u2019 in Deference to Rabbis|work=Jewish Telegraphic Agency|access-date=2017-12-25|language=en-us}}</ref> most prominently by [[James Bevel]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y6oaAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA187|title=Selma to Saigon: The Civil Rights Movement and the Vietnam War|last=Lucks|first=Daniel S.|date=2014-03-19|publisher=University Press of Kentucky|year=|isbn=9780813145099|location=|pages=187|language=en}}</ref>\n\nGhost, the host of the True Capitalist Radio broadcast, uses kippahs as coffee filters.\n\n== See also ==\n{{Commons category|Kippah}}\n{{wiktionary}}\n* [[Taqiyah (cap)]]\n* [[Zucchetto]]\n* [[The Philippi Collection]]\n* [[Zachary Wohlman|Kid Yamaka]], Jewish American boxer\n* [[Knit cap]]\n* ''[[Srugim]]'', an Israeli television show based named after the knit Kippah worn by Religious Zionists\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n{{Hats}}\n{{Jewish life}}\n\n[[Category:Jewish ritual objects]]\n[[Category:Jewish religious clothing]]\n[[Category:Non-clerical religious clothing]]\n[[Category:Religious headgear]]\n[[Category:Middle Eastern clothing]]\n[[Category:History of Asian clothing]]\n[[Category:Jewish life cycle]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Skullcap traditionally worn by Jewish men to cover the head}}\n[[File:PikiWiki Israel 38772 Vacation Experience.JPG|thumb|300px|Crocheted kippot for sale in [[Jerusalem]]]]\nA '''kippah''' ({{IPAc-en|k|\u026a|\u02c8|p|\u0251\u02d0}} {{respell|kih|PAH|'}}; also spelled as '''kippa''', '''kipa''', '''kipah'''; {{lang-he-n|\u05db\u05b4\u05bc\u05d9\u05e4\u05b8\u05bc\u05d4}}, plural: {{Hebrew|\u05db\u05b4\u05bc\u05d9\u05e4\u05bc\u05d5\u05b9\u05ea}} ''kippot''; {{lang-yi|\u05e7\u05d0\u05e4\u05dc}} ''koppel''), or {{nowrap|'''yarmulke''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|j|\u0251r|m|\u0259l|k|\u0259}},}} {{Audio|En-us-yarmulke.ogg|pronunciation|help=no}} {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|j|\u0251\u02d0|m|\u0259|k|\u0259}}, {{lang-yi|\u05d9\u05d0\u05b7\u05e8\u05de\u05d5\u05dc\u05e7\u05e2}}), is a brimless [[cap]], usually made of cloth, traditionally worn by [[Jew]]ish males to fulfill the customary requirement that the head be covered. It is worn by men in [[Orthodox Judaism|Orthodox]] communities at all times. Among non-Orthodox communities most people who wear them customarily do so only during prayer, while attending a [[synagogue]] or in other rituals. Most [[synagogue]]s and Jewish funeral services keep a ready supply of ''kippot''.\n\n== Etymology ==\nThe term ''kippah'' ({{lang-he-n|\u05db\u05d9\u05e4\u05d4}}) literally means \"dome\", as the kippah is worn on the head like a dome. \nThe [[Yiddish]] term ''yarmulke'' might be derived from Polish ''jarmu\u0142ka'',<ref>[http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=yarmulke Etymonline.com]</ref> although it is often associated with an [[Aramaic language|Aramaic]] phrase (\u05d9\u05e8\u05d0 \u05de\u05dc\u05db\u05d0) meaning \"fear the King\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Gwynne|first=Paul|title=World Religions in Practice: A Comparative Introduction|edition=2|year=2017|publisher=John Wiley & Sons |page=|ISBN=9781118972274}}</ref> Another suggested etymology of ''yarmulke'' is the Latin word for an ecclesiastical hood worn in the medieval church.<ref>Gold, David L. 1987. The Etymology of the English Noun ''yarmlke'' \u2018Jewish skullcap\u2019 and the Obsolescent Hebrew Noun ''yarmulka'' \u2018idem\u2019 (With An Addendum on Judezmo Words for \u2018Jewish Skullcap\u2019). ''Jewish Language Review'' 7:180-99; Plaut, Gunther. 1955. The Origin of the Word \"Yarmulke.\" ''Hebrew Union College Annual'' 26:567-70.</ref>{{Specify|reason=which word?|date=May 2019}}\n\n''Keppel'' or ''koppel'' is another Yiddish term for the same thing.<ref>http://www.jewish-languages.org/jewish-english-lexicon/words/1534</ref>\n\n== Jewish law ==\n\nThere is debate among [[halakha|Halachic]] authorities as to whether wearing a kippah at all times is required.<ref name=\"Wearing a Kippa\">{{cite web|title=Wearing a Kippa|url=http://www.dailyhalacha.com/displayRead.asp?readID=997&txtSearch=kippot|work=Daily Halacha|publisher=Rabbi Eli Mansour|accessdate=8 December 2011}}</ref> According to the [[Maimonides|Rambam]], Jewish law dictates that a man is required to cover his head during prayer.<ref>[[Mishneh Torah]], ''Ahavah'', ''Hilkhot Tefilah'' 5:5.</ref>\n\nHowever, according to some authorities, it has since taken on the force of law because it is an act of [[Kiddush Hashem]] (lit., \"sanctification of [[Names of God in Judaism|the Name]]\", referring to actions which bring honor to God).<ref>[[Shulchan Arukh]], Orach Chayim 2:6.</ref> The 17th-century authority Rabbi [[David HaLevi Segal]] (The \"Taz\") suggested that the reason was to distinguish Jews from their non-Jewish counterparts, especially while at prayer. He held that nowadays, wearing a kippah is required by [[Halakha|halacha]].<ref name=\"Wearing a Kippa\"/>\n\nOther halachic authorities like Sephardi posek, the [[Chaim Joseph David Azulai|Chida]] (Rabbi Chaim David Yosef Azulai), hold that wearing a head covering is a ''midat hasidut'', an additional measure of piety.<ref name=\"Wearing a Kippa\"/> In a recent responsum, former Sephardic Chief Rabbi of Israel [[Ovadia Yosef]] ruled that it should be worn to show affiliation with the religiously observant community.<ref>{{cite book|last=Yosef|first=Chief Rabbi Ovadia|title=Responsa Yechavei Da'ath}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Talmud]] states, \"Cover your head in order that the fear of heaven may be upon you.\"<ref>[[Shabbat (Talmud)|Shabbat]] 156b.</ref> Rabbi Hunah ben Joshua never walked 4 [[cubits]] (6.6 feet, or 2 meters) with his head uncovered. He explained: \"Because the [[Shekhinah|Divine Presence]] is always over my head.\"<ref>[[Nashim|Kiddushin]] 31a.</ref> This was understood by Rabbi Yosef Karo in the [[Shulchan Arukh]] as indicating that Jewish men should cover their heads, and should not walk more than four cubits bareheaded.<ref>Shulchan Aruch, Orach Chaim, 2:6.</ref> Covering one's head, such as by wearing a kippah, is described as \"honoring God\".<ref>''Shaar HaTzion'', OC 2:6.</ref> The ''[[Mishnah Berurah]]'' modifies this ruling, adding that the ''[[Achronim]]'' established a requirement to wear a head covering even when traversing fewer than four cubits,<ref>Be'er Heitev, Orach Chaim 2:6, note 4, who quotes the ''[[Yoel Sirkis|Bach]]'', ''[[David HaLevi Segal|Taz]]'', and the ''[[Magen Avraham]]''.</ref> and even when one is standing still, indoors and outside.<ref>Mishnah Berurah 2:6, note 9, 10</ref> ''[[Kitzur Shulchan Aruch (book)|Kitzur Shulchan Aruch]]'' cites a story from the Talmud (Shabbat 156b) about [[Rav Nachman bar Yitzchak]], who might have become a thief had his mother not saved him from this fate by insisting that he cover his head, which instilled in him the fear of God.<ref name=autogenerated1>KSA 3:6</ref> In Orthodox communities, boys are encouraged to wear a ''kippah'' from a young age in order to ingrain the habit.<ref>Be'er Heitev, OC 2:6, note 5</ref>\n[[File:IDF soldier kippah put on tefillin-small.jpg|thumb|right|200px|[[Israel Defense Forces|IDF]] soldier prays with kippah and [[tefillin]].]]\nThe Talmud also implies that unmarried men did not wear a kippah:\n:Rabbi Hisda praised Rabbi Hamnuna before Rabbi Huna as a great man. He said to him, 'When he visits you, bring him to me.' When he arrived, he saw that he wore no head-covering. 'Why do you not have head-covering?', he asked. 'Because I am not married', was the reply. Thereupon, he [Rabbi Huna] turned his face away from him, and said, 'See to it that you do not appear before me again before you are married.'<ref>Tractate Kiddushin 29b</ref>\n\nThe Tanakh implies that covering one's head is a sign of mourning:\n{{quote|And [[David]] went up the ascent of the Mount of Olives, and wept as he went, and his head was covered and he walked barefoot. Then all the people who were with him each covered his head and went up weeping as they went.|{{tanakhverse|2 Samuel|15:30}}}}\n{{quote|[Judah mourns,] and their nobles send their lads for water: they come to the pits, and find no water; their vessels return empty; they are ashamed and confounded, and cover their heads. Because of the ground which is cracked, for there hath been no rain in the land, the plowmen are ashamed, they cover their heads.|{{tanakhverse|Jeremiah|14:3\u20134}}}}The argument for the kippa has two sides. The [[Vilna Gaon]] said one can make a ''[[berakhah]]'' without a kippah, since wearing a kippah is only an ''midos chassidus'' (\"exemplary attribute\"). Recently, there has been an effort to suppress earlier sources that practiced this leniency, including erasing lenient [[responsa]] from newly published books.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Yarmulke: A historic cover up?|journal=Flatbush Journal of Jewish Law|url=http://www.hakirah.org/Vol%204%20Rabinowitz.pdf}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Rabbi [[Isaac Klein]], a Conservative Jew ought to cover his head when in the synagogue, at prayer or sacred study, when engaging in a ritual act, and when eating.<ref>Klein, Isaac. ''A Guide to Jewish Religious Practice'', New York: Jewish Theological Seminary of America, 1979.</ref> In the mid-19th century, Reformers led by [[Isaac Mayer Wise|Isaac Wise]] completely rejected the ''kippot'' after an altercation in which Rabbi Wise's kippah was knocked off his head.<ref>Scharfman, Rabbi Harold (1988). ''The First Rabbi''. Pangloss Press.</ref>\n\nThere is still debate about whether wearing a Kippah is Halachic law or simply a custom. Many Sephardic Jews wear a kippah only when praying and eating.{{citation needed|date=September 2014}}\n\n== Types and variation ==\n[[File:Jewish Chaplain Iraq.jpg|thumb|Rabbinical chaplain [[Sarah Schechter]] with fellow U.S. Airmen wearing [[camouflage]] kippot.]]\nIn the [[Middle Ages]] in Europe, the distinctive Jewish headgear was the [[Jewish hat]], a full hat with a brim and a central point or stalk.  Originally used by choice among Jews to distinguish themselves, it was later made compulsory in some places by Christian governments as a discriminatory measure. In the early 19th century in the United States, rabbis often wore a scholar's cap (large saucer-shaped caps of cloth, like a beret) or a Chinese skullcap. Other Jews of this era wore black pillbox-shaped ''kippot''.\n\nOften, the color and fabric of the ''kippah'' can be a sign of adherence to a specific religious movement, particularly in Israel. [[Knit]]ted or [[crochet]]ed ''kippot'', known as ''kippot serugot'', are usually worn by [[Religious Zionist movement|Religious Zionists]] and the [[Modern Orthodox Judaism|Modern Orthodox]],<ref>Boyarin, Jonathan. [https://books.google.com/books?id=Ng2PCUQQ4lwC&pg=PA51&dq=kippah+sruga&cd=3#v=onepage&q=kippah%20sruga&f=false ''Thinking in Jewish''], University of Chicago Press, 1996, p. 51. {{ISBN|0-226-06927-3}}.</ref> who also wear suede or leather ''kippot''. Members of most [[Haredi Judaism|Haredi]] groups wear black velvet or cloth ''kippot''.\n\nMore recently, ''kippot'' have been observed made in the colors of sports teams, especially [[football]]. In the United States, children's ''kippot'' with cartoon characters or themes such as ''[[Star Wars]]'' are popular. (In response to this trend, some Jewish schools have banned ''kippot'' with characters that do not conform to traditional Jewish values.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1990/09/23/style/lifestyle-the-yarmulke-is-now-a-fashion-item.html Lifestyle; \"The Yarmulke Is Now a Fashion Item\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', 23 Sept 1990</ref>) ''Kippot'' have been inscribed on the inside as a souvenir for a celebration (''bar/bat mitzvah'' or wedding). ''Kippot'' for women are also being made and worn.<ref name=\"GU\">{{cite news|url=http://www.jewishindependent.ca/archives/July06/archives06July07-06.html|title=A guide to Jewish head-coverings: Kippot no longer only come in one style, but a medley of colors, shapes and designs|first1=Wendy|last1=Elliman|date=July 7, 2006|work=Jewish Independent|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120309024448/http://www.jewishindependent.ca/archives/July06/archives06July07-06.html|archivedate=March 9, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"MAZ\">[http://www.mazorguide.com/Living/JewishAttire/home.htm Living Jewish \u2013 Jewish Attire!], Mazor Guide. Retrieved December 19, 2010.</ref><ref>[https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/jpost/access/1011733051.html?dids=1011733051:1011733051&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&date=Jul+10%2C+2005&author=AVI+BASS&pub=Jerusalem+Post&desc=California+firm+offers+kippot+for+women&pqatl=google \"California firm offers kippot for women\"], ''[[The Jerusalem Post]]'', July 10, 2005</ref> These are sometimes made of beaded wire to seem more feminine.<ref>[https://www.myjewishlearning.com/article/ask-the-expert-why-dont-women-wear-kippot/ \"Ask the Expert: Can Women Wear Kippot?\" \u2018\u2019My Jewish Learning\u2019\u2019]</ref> A special baby kippah has two strings on each side to fasten it and is often used in a ''[[brit milah]]'' ceremony.<ref name=\"JW\">[http://www.jweekly.com/article/full/22990/from-baby-kippah-to-tylenol-bris-kit-has-everything-but-the-implement/ \"From baby kippah to Tylenol, Bris Kit has everything but the implement\"], ''[[j.|J Weekly]]'', 18 Jun 2004</ref>\n\n[[Samaritan]]s once wore distinctive blue head coverings to separate them from Jews who wore white ones, but today, they more commonly wear ''[[Fez (hat)|fezes]]'' with turbans similar to that of [[Sephardi Jews]] from the Middle East and North Africa. Today, Samaritans do not usually wear head coverings, except during prayer, Sabbath, and religious festivals.{{citation needed|date=October 2012}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Image\n!Type\n!Movement\n|-\n| [[Image:Kippa.jpg|100px]]\n| Crocheted\n| [[Religious Zionism]], Modern Orthodox, Conservative Judaism, Reform Judaism\n|-\n| [[File:Kippa judentum.JPG|100px]]\n| [[Suede]]\n| Modern Orthodox,<ref name=\"MAZ\"/>  Conservative Judaism,<ref name=\"myjewishlearning\">{{cite web|url=http://www.myjewishlearning.com/practices/Ritual/Prayer/Ritual_Garb/Kippah.shtml |title=Kippah |publisher=My Jewish Learning |date=2014-01-31 |accessdate=2017-04-22}}</ref> Reform Judaism<ref name=\"myjewishlearning\"/>\n|-\n| \n| [[Polyethylene terephthalate|Terylene]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.milechai.com/kippot/how-to-buy-a-kippah/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-02-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140301185150/http://www.milechai.com/kippot/how-to-buy-a-kippah/ |archivedate=2014-03-01 }}</ref>\n| [[Yeshivish]], [[Hasidic Judaism|Hasidic]], Haredi, [[Lubavitch]] \u2013 Popular among Rabbis teaching in yeshivas and seminaries\n|-\n| [[File:Black Kippah.jpg|100px]]\n| Black [[velvet]]\n| Yeshivish, Hasidic, Haredi<ref name=\"JPK\">[http://fr.jpost.com/servlet/Satellite?cid=1139395368958&pagename=JPost/JPArticle/ShowFull Barring violence]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, [[The Jerusalem Post]], Yigal Grayeff, February 9, 2006</ref>\n|-\n| [[File:Casamento judeu1.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Satin]]\n| Conservative Judaism, Reform Judaism\n|-\n| [[Image:Na-nach-nachma-yarmulke.jpg|100px]]\n| White crocheted\n| Many [[Jerusalemite]]s wear a full-head-sized, white crocheted ''kippah'', sometimes with a knit pom-pom or tassel on top. The [[Na Nach]] subgroup of the [[Breslov (Hasidic dynasty)|Breslov]] [[Hasidim]], followers of the late Rabbi [[Yisroel Ber Odesser]], wear it with the ''[[Na Nach Nachma Nachman Meuman]]'' phrase crocheted in or embroidered on it.<ref>[http://www.haaretz.co.il/hasen/spages/766226.html On New Year, thousands flock to Rabbi Nachman's grave in Ukraine]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, [[HaAretz]], Yair Ettinger</ref>\n|-\n| [[File:Bukharan kippah.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Bukharan Jews|Bukharan]]<ref name=\"B\">[https://archive.today/20130104135202/http://www.record-eagle.com/features/local_story_103094128.html?keyword=topstory Hats Off To Fashion: Yarmulkes go beyond basic black], [[Traverse City Record-Eagle]], [[Associated Press]], April 13, 2008</ref>\n| Popular with children,<ref name=\"GU\"/><ref name=\"B\"/> and also worn by some Sephardi Jews, as well as liberal-leaning, feminist, and Reform Jews.<ref name=\"FOR\">[http://www.forward.com/articles/4778/ Kippah Couture], [[The Forward]], Angela Himsel, September 29, 2006</ref>\n|-\n| [[File:Yemenite kippah.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Yemenite Jews|Yemenite]]\n| Typically stiff, black velvet with a 1\u20132&nbsp;cm. embroidered strip around the edge having a multi-colored geometric, floral, or [[Paisley (design)|paisley]] pattern.\n|}\n\n== Head coverings in ancient Israelite culture ==\n{{original research|date=November 2017}}\nThe [[Israelites]] on [[Sennacherib]]'s marble relief appear with headdress, and although the ambassadors of [[Jehu]] on the [[Black Obelisk of Shalmaneser III|Shalmaneser stele]] have head coverings, their costume seems to be Israelite. One passage of the older literature is of significance: I Kings 20:31 mentions \u05d7\u05b2\u05d1\u05b8\u05dc\u05d9\u05b4\u05dd ''havalim'',  which are placed around the head. This calls to mind pictures of [[Demographics of Syria|Syrians]] on [[Egypt]]ian monuments, represented wearing a cord around their long, flowing hair, a custom still followed in [[Arabia]].\n\nEvidently the costume of the poorest classes is represented; but as the cord gave no protection against the heat of the sun, there is little probability that the custom lasted very long. Much more common was the simple cloth skullcap, dating back to Egyptian times when those of high society routinely shaved their heads, to prevent lice. Conversely, their skullcaps also served as protection against irritation from their wigs.\n\nThe Israelites might have worn a headdress similar to that worn by the [[Bedouins]], but it is unknown whether a fixed type of headdress was utilized. That the headdress of the Israelites might have been in the fellah style may be inferred from the use of the noun \u05e6\u05b7\u05e0\u05b4\u05d9\u05e3 ''tzanif'' (the verb ''tzanaf'' meaning \"to roll like a ball\", Isaiah 22:18) and by the verb \u05d7\u05b7\u05d1\u05b8\u05bc\u05e9 ''habash'' (\"to wind\", comp. Ezekiel 16:10; Jonah 2:6). As to the form of such turbans, nothing is known, and they may have varied according to the different classes of society. This was customary with the Assyrians and Babylonians, for example, whose fashions likely influenced the costume of the Israelites\u2014particularly during and after the [[Babylonian captivity|Babylonian Exile]].<ref>[http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/view.jsp?artid=465&letter=H&search=Head-Dress \"Head-dress\"], ''Jewish Encyclopedia''</ref> In Yemen, the wrap around the cap was called \u05de\u05b7\u05e6\u05b7\u05e8 ''matzar''; the head covering worn by women was a \u05d2\u05b7\u05bc\u05e8\u05d2\u05d5\u05bc\u05e9 ''[[gargush]]''.<ref>[http://www.chayas.com/garb.htm \"Clothing of the Yemenite Jews\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060220174330/http://www.chayas.com/garb.htm |date=2006-02-20 }}, Chayas.com</ref>\n\n== Civil legal issues ==\n\nIn ''[[Goldman v. Weinberger]]'', 475 U.S. 503 (1986), the [[United States Supreme Court]] ruled in a 5\u20134 decision that active military members were required to remove the yarmulke indoors, citing uniform regulations that state only armed security police may keep their heads covered while indoors.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.oyez.org/cases/1980-1989/1985/1985_84_1097|title=Goldman v. Weinberger|website=[[Oyez Project|www.oyez.org]]|publisher=[[Chicago-Kent College of Law|IIT Chicago-Kent College of Law]]}}</ref>\n\nCongress passed the Religious Apparel Amendment after a war story from the [[1983 Beirut barracks bombing]] about the \"camouflage kippah\" of Jewish Navy Chaplain [[Arnold Resnicoff]] was read into the ''Congressional Record''.<ref>''Congressional Record'', 100th Congress, 11 May 1987.</ref> Catholic Chaplain George Pucciarelli tore off a piece of his [[United States Marine Corps|Marine Corps]] uniform to replace Resnicoff's ''kippah'' when it had become blood-soaked after being used to wipe the faces of wounded Marines after the 1983 Beirut barracks bombing.<ref>\"Solarz Passes Religious Apparel Amendment\", ''The Jewish Press'', 22 May 1987.</ref> This amendment was eventually incorporated into U.S. Department of Defense (DOD) regulations on the \"Accommodation of Religious Practices Within the Military Services\".<ref>[http://www.dtic.mil/whs/directives/corres/pdf/130017p.pdf \"Accommodation of Religious Practices Within the Military Services\"], Department of Defense Instruction</ref>\n[[File:Lea Rabin-Clinton.jpg|thumb|U.S. President [[Bill Clinton]] wearing a kippah to visit the grave of [[Yitzhak Rabin]] on [[Mount Herzl]].]]\nThis story of the \"camouflage kippah\" was re-told at many levels,<ref>Bonko, Larry. \"Rabbi's Camouflage Yarmulke Woven With Tragedy, Heroism\", ''Norfolk Ledger-Star'', 13 January 1984.</ref> including a keynote speech by President [[Ronald Reagan]] to the Baptist Fundamentalism Annual Convention in 1984,<ref>{{cite web |title=Remarks at the Baptist Fundamentalism Annual Convention |date=13 April 1984|accessdate=20 April 2013 |url=http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/ws/index.php?pid=39775#axzz1Nry3hQkr|publisher=The American Presidency Project}}</ref> and another time during a [[White House]] meeting between Reagan and the American Friends of Lubavitch.<ref name=\"top\">{{cite news|title=Rabbis Explain 'Top to Top'|work=Wellsprings|issue=No. 12 (Vol 2, No. 7)|date=August\u2013September 1986|publisher=Lubavitch Youth Organization}}</ref> After recounting the Beirut story, Reagan asked them about the religious meaning of the kippah.<ref name=\"top\"/>  Rabbi [[Abraham Shemtov]], the leader of the group, responded: \"Mr. President, the kippah to us is a sign of reverence.\" Rabbi Feller, another member of the group, continued: \"We place the kippah on the very highest point of our being\u2014on our head, the vessel of our intellect\u2014to tell ourselves and the world that there is something which is above man's intellect: the infinite Wisdom of God.\"<ref name=\"top\"/>\n\nPassage of the Religious Apparel Amendment and the subsequent DOD regulations were followed in 1997 by the passing of the [[Religious Freedom Restoration Act]] (RFRA). However, the Supreme Court struck down RFRA as beyond Congress' powers to bind the states in the 1997 case ''[[City of Boerne v. Flores]]''. RFRA is constitutional as applied to the Federal government, as seen in ''[[Gonzales v. O Centro Espirita Beneficente Uniao do Vegetal]]''.\n\nThe [[Religious Land Use and Institutionalized Persons Act]] of 2000 (RLUIPA), 114 Stat. 804, 42 U. S. C. \u00a72000cc-1(a)(1)-(2), upheld as constitutional in ''[[Cutter v. Wilkinson]]'', 44 U.S. 709 (2005), requires by inference that Orthodox Jewish prisoners be reasonably accommodated in their request to wear yarmulkas.<ref>[http://openjurist.org/391/f3d/1299/benning-v-georgia ''Benning v. Georgia''], 391 F3d 1299</ref>\n\nThe French government [[French law on secularity and conspicuous religious symbols in schools|banned the wearing]] of ''kippot'', ''[[hijab]]s'', and large [[Christian cross|crosses]] in public primary and secondary schools in France in March 2004.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/3531151.stm French Senate backs headscarf ban], [[BBC News]], 3 March 2004.</ref>\n\nThe provincial government of [[Quebec]], Canada passed \"An Act respecting the laicity of the State\"  in June 2019, which prohibits the wearing of \"religious symbols\" by government employees including teachers, police officers, judges, prosecutors, and members of certain commissions.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/quebec-government-adopts-controversial-religious-symbols-bill-1.5177587 |title=Quebec government adopts controversial religious symbols bill |publisher=[[CBC News]] |date=16 June 2019 |access-date=18 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Wearing by non-Jews==\nThough it is not required, when a non-Jew wears a kippah in a synagogue, it is considered a sign of respect.<ref>{{cite book |first=Bradley Shavit |last=Artson|authorlink=Bradley Shavit Artson|title=Jewish Answers to Real-Life Questions |year=1998 |publisher=[[Torah Aura Productions]]|page=23|isbn=9781881283294|url=https://books.google.co.ug/books?id=WnYaLZ7ngWYC}}</ref> Yarmulkes are often provided to guests at a [[Bar or Bat Mitzvah]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Marjabelle Young |first=Stewart |title=The New Etiquette |year=1997 |publisher=Macmillan |page=21}}</ref> They are also often provided at [[Bereavement in Judaism|bereavement]] events and at [[Jewish cemetery|Jewish cemeteries]].  According to the Conservative [[Committee on Jewish Law and Standards]], there is no [[halakhic]] reason to require a non-Jew to cover their head, but it is recommended that non-Jews be asked to wear a kippah where ritual or worship is being conducted, both out of respect for the Jewish congregation and as a gesture of respectfully including the non-Jewish guest.<ref>{{cite journal |first=Jay M. |last=Stein |title=Non Jews and Kippah in the Synagogue |year=2009 |url=https://www.rabbinicalassembly.org/sites/default/files/public/halakhah/teshuvot/20052010/Kippah%20JaySteinfinal.pdf |publisher=[[Committee on Jewish Law and Standards]]}}</ref>\n\nKippahs were adopted as a symbol by some of the non-Jewish African American marchers in the 1965 [[Selma to Montgomery marches]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.jta.org/1965/03/23/archive/negro-marchers-from-selma-wear-yarmulkes-in-deference-to-rabbis|title=Negro Marchers from Selma Wear \u2018Yarmulkes\u2019 in Deference to Rabbis|work=Jewish Telegraphic Agency|access-date=2017-12-25|language=en-us}}</ref> most prominently by [[James Bevel]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y6oaAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA187|title=Selma to Saigon: The Civil Rights Movement and the Vietnam War|last=Lucks|first=Daniel S.|date=2014-03-19|publisher=University Press of Kentucky|year=|isbn=9780813145099|location=|pages=187|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Commons category|Kippah}}\n{{wiktionary}}\n* [[Taqiyah (cap)]]\n* [[Zucchetto]]\n* [[The Philippi Collection]]\n* [[Zachary Wohlman|Kid Yamaka]], Jewish American boxer\n* [[Knit cap]]\n* ''[[Srugim]]'', an Israeli television show based named after the knit Kippah worn by Religious Zionists\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n{{Hats}}\n{{Jewish life}}\n\n[[Category:Jewish ritual objects]]\n[[Category:Jewish religious clothing]]\n[[Category:Non-clerical religious clothing]]\n[[Category:Religious headgear]]\n[[Category:Middle Eastern clothing]]\n[[Category:History of Asian clothing]]\n[[Category:Jewish life cycle]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n", "name_user": "72.208.232.9", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eWearing by non-Jews)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kippah"}
